Question: 'Wrist drop' is a clinical sign indicating damage to which nerve?
Explanation:
Wrist drop is also known as radial nerve palsy. With this condition, extension of the wrist is impossible so when the hand is in a pronated position, the hand will drop down into flexion.

 

This is because the extensor muscles in the hand are supplied by the radial nerve (and the posterior interosseus nerve, which itself is a continuation of the deep branch of the radial nerve).

 

The flexor muscles of the wrist and digits are innervated by the median nerve.

Question: What roots supply the musculocutaneous nerve?
Explanation:
C5 and C6 form the superior trunk, C7 forms the middle trunk. The superior anterior division and the middle anterior division join, forming the lateral cord. The musculocutaneous nerve branches off this cord. 

 

The musculocutaneous nerve supplies the anterior compartment of the arm.

Question: What nerve supplies the serratus anterior muscle?
Explanation: The long thoracic nerve supplies the serratus anterior and originates from the C5, C6, C7 roots of brachial plexus.

Question: Which part of the brachial plexus causes Waiter's Tip?

Explanation: Erb's palsy or Erb–Duchenne palsy is a paralysis of the arm caused by injury to the upper group of the arm's main nerves, specifically the severing of the upper trunk C5–C6 nerves.

Question: Which three muscles act as flexor muscles in the elbow joint?
Explanation:
There are three main flexor muscles at the elbow:

  • Brachialis acts exclusively as an elbow flexor. 
  • Brachioradialis acts essentially as an elbow flexor but also supinates during extreme pronation and pronates during extreme supination.
  • Biceps brachii is the main elbow flexor but, as a biarticular muscle, also plays important secondary roles as a stabiliser at the shoulder and as a supinator.
Tags: Upper limb anatomy, Forearm anatomy, anatomy

Question: Which one of these functions do Carbohydrates NOT primarily perform?
OptionC: Link to proteins and lipids in order to modify function
Explanation: Lipids generally function as thermal and electrical insulators. A good example is the myelin sheath.

Question: Which medical imaging technique does not use ionising radiation?
Explanation: MRI (Magnetic Resonance Imaging) and Ultrasound are two common medical imaging techniques that do not expose a patient to ionising radiation.

Question: Which enzyme converts Pyruvate to Lactate during fermentation?
Explanation: Lactate dehydrogenase is an enzyme found in nearly all living cells. It catalyses the conversion of pyruvate to lactate, as it converts NADH to NAD+. This reaction is reversible, and Lactate dehydrogenase can also catalyse the reverse reaction.

Question: What nerve may be damaged if the surgical neck of the humerus was fractured?
Explanation: As the axillary nerve is located close to the surgical neck of the humerus, there is a high risk of this nerve being damaged when a fracture to the surgical neck takes place.
Tags: anatomy, Skeleton, Upper limb anatomy, osteology, upper limb

Question: What is the role of the subclavius muscle?
Explanation: The subclavius depresses the clavicle. Its origin is the junction of the 1st rib and costal cartilage, it inserts on the inferior surface of the clavicle and it is innervated by nerve to subclavius.

Question: Which undifferentiated cells are found between muscle fibres and the basement membrane and serve to repair damage such as minor tears in the muscle tissue?
Explanation: Satellite cells are found between muscle fibres and the basement membrane. A minor tear of the muscle may be repaired by replacement of of damaged cells with these satellite cells. However, major tears cannot utilise this method of repair.

Question: What is the protein that acts as a store of oxygen in muscle cells?
Explanation: Myoglobin acts as a store of oxygen within the muscle cell. It has a high affinity for oxygen, and provides oxygen to the muscle fibre when there is no blood supply (when the muscle is contracting). In injury, it can be released into the bloodstream - it is toxic when in the blood, and can be used as a marker in clinical situations.

Question: What is a motor unit?
OptionB: The muscle fibres innervated by a motor neurone
OptionC: One motor neurone and one sensory neurone
OptionD: One motor neurone and all the muscle fibres it innervates
Explanation: A motor unit is defined as one motor neurone and all of the muscle fibres it innervates.

Question: Where would transitional epithelium be found?
Explanation: Transitional epithelium lines the urinary system. It offers the ability to distend which is important to allow the bladder to store varying volumes of liquid.

Question: Where is the perineurium found?
Explanation: The perineurium is a layer of connective tissue that surrounds the fascicle.

Question: What is the role of the Golgi apparatus?
OptionE: Contain genetic information of the cell in the form of DNA and RNA
Explanation: The Golgi apparatus is a system of flattened sacs that modifies and packages proteins and lipids for intracellular or extracellular use.

Question: Which type of transporter is the CFTR channel protein?
Explanation: The CFTR gene codes for an ABC transporter-class ion channel protein that conducts chloride and thiocyanate ions across epithelial cell membranes.

Question: Where would (most likely) Pseudostratified Columnar Epithelium be located in the body?
Explanation:
Ciliated pseudostratified columnar epithelia are found in the linings of the trachea as well as the upper respiratory tract.
Non-ciliated pseudostratified columnar epithelia are located in the membranous part of male vas deferens.
Pseudostratified columnar epithelia with stereocilia are located in the epididymis. Stereocilia of the epididymis are not cilia because their cytoskeleton is composed of actin filaments, not microtubules. They are structurally and molecularly more similar to microvilli than to true cilia.
Pseudostratified columnar epithelia are found forming the straight, tubular glands of the endometrium in females.

Question: Which genetic disease causes insufficient activity to hydrolytic enzymes found in lysosomes that breaks down glycolipids?
Explanation: Tay–Sachs disease (also known as GM2 gangliosidosis or hexosaminidase A deficiency) is a rare autosomal recessive genetic disorder. Tay–Sachs disease is caused by insufficient activity of the enzyme hexosaminidase A. Hexosaminidase A is a vital hydrolytic enzyme, found in the lysosomes, that breaks down glycolipids. When hexosaminidase A is no longer functioning properly, the lipids accumulate in the brain and interfere with normal biological processes. Hexosaminidase A specifically breaks down fatty acid derivatives called gangliosides; these are made and biodegraded rapidly in early life as the brain develops. Patients with and carriers of Tay–Sachs can be identified by a simple blood test that measures hexosaminidase A activity.

Question: What are the four "pillar" principles of Medical Ethics?
Explanation:
The four principles are:

Autonomy: Viewing the rights of an individual to self-determination.

Beneficence: The term beneficence refers to actions that promote the well being of others.

Non-maleficence: "first, do no harm".

Justice: Concerns the distribution of scarce health resources, and the decision of who gets what treatment.

Question: What is the name of the process by which leukocytes may move through the walls of the capillaries and enter tissue spaces?
Explanation: Diapedesis is the process by which leukocytes may enter through the walls of the capillaries. See Pococks page 315 for more information.

Question: A patient comes into clinic complaining of an inability to move their wrist resulting in a 'wrist drop'. The patient also complains of a loss of sensation in some of the skin in the forearm. What nerve has the patient likely to have damaged?
Explanation: The radial nerve innervates the posterior compartment of the upper limb. As such it innervates the muscles responsible for extension of the wrist and fingers at the metacarpophalangeal joints. Hence the patient is unable to extend the wrist.

OptionD: Elevates the scapula and tilts its glenoid cavity inferiorly by rotating the scapula.

Explanation: The Axillary nerve arises from the posterior chord. The other chords of the Brachial plexus are the lateral and the medial chords.

Question: Which clotting factor causes Haemophilia A?
Explanation: Haemophilia A is a genetic deficiency in clotting factor VIII, which causes increased bleeding and usually affects males. In the majority of cases it is inherited as an X-linked recessive trait, though there are cases which arise from spontaneous mutations.

Question: Which enzyme converts Glucose 6-Phosphate into Fructose 6-Phosphate?
Explanation: G6P is rearranged into fructose 6-phosphate (F6P) by Phosphoglucose Isomerase. Fructose can also enter the glycolytic pathway by phosphorylation at this point.

Question: What condition results in Radial Angulation of the wrist, Radial shortening and the distinct "Dinner Fork" shape?
Explanation:
A Colles' fracture is a fracture of the distal radius in the forearm with dorsal (posterior) and radial displacement of the wrist and hand. The fracture is sometimes referred to as a "dinner fork" or "bayonet" deformity due to the shape of the resultant forearm. Colles' fractures are often seen in people with osteoporosis.

The Rolando fracture is a comminuted intra-articular fracture through the base of the first metacarpal bone (the first bone forming the thumb). It was first described in 1910 by Silvio Rolando. This is a fracture consisting of 3 distinct fragments; it is typically T- or Y-shaped.

A Smith's fracture, also sometimes known as a reverse Colles' fracture or Goyrand-Smith's, is a fracture of the distal radius. It is caused by a direct blow to the dorsal forearm or falling onto flexed wrists, as opposed to a Colles' fracture which occurs as a result of falling onto wrists in extension. Smith's fractures are less common than Colles' fractures.

The Essex-Lopresti fracture is a fracture of the radial head with concomitant dislocation of the distal radio-ulnar joint and disruption of the interosseous membrane. The injury is named after Peter Essex-Lopresti who described it in 1951.

Boxer's Fracture is a colloquial term for a fracture of one of the metacarpal bones of the hand. Classically, the fracture occurs transversely across the neck of the bone, after the patient strikes an object with a closed fist. Alternate terms include scrapper's fracture or bar room fracture.

Question: Poiseuille's law states that blood flow is proportional to the '...........' power of the radius of the vessel and is inversely proportional to the viscosity. Fill the gap.
Explanation: To the fourth power. This means that is the radius of a vessel is halved, it will carry 1/16th of the volume of blood for the same pressure.

Question: A patient comes into clinic presenting clearly defined veins on her legs. You identify the condition as being caused by 'varicose veins'. What causes varicose veins?
OptionB: Leaflet valves failing allowing for retrograde flow of blood.
OptionC: A blood clot forming in the vein.
OptionE: Damage to the endothelium of the veins.
Explanation: When the leaflet valves fail, the flow of blood in the veins is retrograde. As such the veins become visible under the skin.

Question: Which of the following cells is classified as a 'mononuclear leukocyte'?
Explanation: Lymphocytes are mononuclear leukocytes.

Question: Which of the following upper-limb (axio-appendicular) muscles does not attach to the thoracic cage?
Explanation: The pectoralis major and pectoralis minor both attach to the thoracic cage as does the serratus anterior (anteriorly) and latissimus dorsi (posteriorly).

Question: What shape best describes the appearance of smooth muscle cells?
Explanation: Smooth muscle cells are said to be spindle shaped.

Question: Approximately, how much of a bone's mass is cortical bone?
Explanation: Long bones such as the humerus or the femur consist of cortical bone and cancellous bone. Cortical bone consists of around 80% of the mass of the bone.

Question: The Acromioclavicular joint is an example of what type of synovial joint?
Explanation: The acromioclavicular joint is an example of a joint which allows for movement between the acromion process of the scapular and the clavicle.
Tags: Upper limb anatomy, osteology, anatomy, upper limb

Question: A keen tennis player comes into practice having complained of hearing a 'popping noise' in their arm after a session in the tennis courts. Upon observation of the arm you notice that the belly of biceps brachii has become distally displaced to form what is known as a 'popeye deformity'. What is likely to have happened to the arm to allow for this deformity to occur?
OptionA: The tendon of the short head of the biceps brachii has ruptured from its origin on the coracoid process of the scapula.
OptionB: The tendon of coracobrachialis has detached from the coracoid process of the scapula.
OptionC: The tendon of the long head of biceps brachii has detached from the supraglenoid tubercle of the scapula.
OptionD: The brachialis muscle has detached from its attachments on the humerus.
Explanation: Rupture of the tendon of the long head of the biceps usually results from wear and tear of an inflamed tendon. Normally, the tendon is torn from its attachment to the supraglenoid tubercle of the scapula. See page 436 of Moore's clinical anatomy for more details.
Tags: Upper limb anatomy, Muscle, anatomy, upper limb

Question: How many ribs are there in the anatomically standard human?
Explanation: The human rib cage is made up of 12 paired rib bones: each are symmetrically paired on a right and left side. Of all 24 ribs, the first seven pairs are often referred to as vertebrosternal. These bones are connected to the costal cartilage, while the five other vertebrochondral sets are not.

Question: How many pairs of vertebrosternal ribs are there?
Explanation: The first 7 pairs of ribs are described as vertebrosternal, as they articulate directly with the sternum anteriorly.

Question: Which ribs are described as vertebrochondral?
Explanation: Pairs 8-10 are vertebrochondral ribs. These pairs do not articulate with the sternum directly; the costal cartilages are continuous with the 7th costal cartilage.

Question: Which nerve innervates the diaphragm?
Explanation: The phrenic nerve innervates the diaphragm. It is a spinal nerve with roots from C3, C4 and C5.

Question: A patient regularly attends outpatient appointments to monitor their dosage of the anticoagulant therapy Warfarin. Which test would be likely to be carried out at the clinic?
Explanation: INR is a highly standardised version of the PT and it is typically used to monitor anticoagulant therapy involving warfarin.

Question: What is the substrate of hexokinase?
Explanation: Glucose is phosphorylated to glucose-6-phosphate by hexokinase

Question: What is polycythemia?
OptionB: Calcification of the blood vessels in the heart
OptionD: Decrease in number of red blood cells
OptionE: Increase in number of white blood cells
Explanation: An abnormally increased concentration of haemoglobin in the blood, either through reduction of plasma volume or increase in red cell numbers. It may be a primary disease of unknown cause, or a secondary condition linked to respiratory or circulatory disorder or cancer.

Question: During skeletal muscle contraction which ion binds to troponin causing it to change conformation?
Explanation: Calcium ions released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum following an action potential diffuse into sarcoplasm. Calcium binds to globular troponin proteins causing them to change conformation. This in turn moves tropomyosin and exposes the myosin binding sites.
Tags: Muscle, sliding filament theory, muscle contraction

Question: What does a hematocrit value represent?
OptionA: The proportion of the blood that is made up of liquid
OptionB: The number of cells in the blood
OptionC: The proportion of the blood made up of white blood cells
OptionD: The proportion of the blood that is made up of red blood cells
OptionE: The volume of haemoglobin in the blood
Explanation: The hematocrit (Ht or HCT) is the volume percentage (vol%) of red blood cells in blood. It is normally 45% for men and 40% for women. Anaemia refers to an abnormally low hematocrit, as opposed to polycythemia, which refers to an abnormally high hematocrit.

Question: How much free energy is liberated when ATP is converted to ADP and Pi?
Explanation: -30.5kjmol of energy is released when one phosphate group is removed to convert ATP to ADP and Pi. If two phosphate groups were to be removed though turning ATP into AMP and PPi, double the energy would not be released. Only -45.6kjmol of energy is released as the bond between the third and second phosphate groups is of a higher energy than the bond between the first and second phosphate groups.

Question: What is Bradycardia?
Explanation: abnormally slow heart action.

Question: What is Cyanosis?
OptionA: Bluish discoloration of skin due to poor blood circulation
Explanation: a bluish discoloration of the skin due to poor circulation or inadequate oxygenation of the blood.

Question: During a placement you are asked by your supervisor to palpate the sternal angle of a patient. With the consent of the patient you proceed. Where would one find the sternal angle?
OptionA: Between the body of the sternum and the xiphoid process.
OptionB: Between the manubrium and the body of the sternum between the 1st costal notches of the sternum
OptionC: Between the manubrium and the body of the sternum between the 3rd costal notches of the sternum
OptionD: Between the manubrium and the body of the sternum between the 2nd costal notches of the sternum
OptionE: At the top of the manubrium of the sternum.
Explanation: The sternal angle is a synarthrosis joint found between the manubrium and the body of the sternum. It is found between the 2nd costal notches on the sternum.

Question: Which enzyme is responsible for the maintaining chromosome length in cancerous and germ cells during DNA replication?
Explanation: The ends of the chromosomes are known as telomeres. Telomeres are reformed by telomerase. This allows cells to remain immortal. In most somatic cells it is not present.

Question: In order for a primer to bond to a deoxynucleoside triphosphate during the replication of DNA, what chemical group must be present on the 3 prime carbon of the primer?
Explanation: During the DNA polymerase reaction, the -OH group on the 3 prime carbon acts as a nucleophile. It attacks the phosphate group on the deoxynucleoside triphosphate causing it to join to the primer. In the nucleophilic substitution the two other phosphates are lost.

Question: You are in clinic and are asked to interpret an ECG. You are told to work out the PR interval, which statement best describes the PR interval?

Which of the following muscles is included in the rotator cuff?
which of the following isn't fully innervated by the median nerve?
Explanation: The flexor digitorum profundus is innervated by both median and ulnar nerve!

Question: What nerve innervates the serratus anterior muscle?
Explanation: Long thoracic nerve is part of the brachial plexus
Tags: Innervation, Upper limb anatomy, Muscle, anatomy

Question: What is the imprint found in the atria of the heart that closes up at birth?
Explanation: The fosa oval us is a flap that bypasses the blood flow in the foetus. This usually closes up at birth but if it doesn't this is known as a form of heart murmur

Question: Which bone is not a carpal bone?
What is the name of the condition describing when pressure on the heart increases as a result of fluid filling the pericardial cavity?
Explanation: Cardiac tamponade is pressure on the heart that occurs when blood or fluid builds up in the pericardial cavity
Tags: Cardiovascular System, anatomy, thorax anatomy, Physiology

Question: How many seconds does each small square in an ECG represent?
Explanation:
Smaller square = 0.04 seconds 

Larger square = 0.2 seconds

Question: Which nerve is compressed in Carpal tunnel syndrome?
Where does the short head of the bicep attach?
What nerve does the musculocutaneous nerve continue down the forearm as?
An ECG trace presents the PR interval getting longer and longer until a QRS complex is missed and fhe process repeats, what heart condition may have caused this?
What induces the action potential in cardiac muscle?
OptionA: Flow of sodium ions inducing release of sodium ions from sarcoplasmic reticulum
OptionB: Flow of calcium ions inducing release of sodium ions from sarcoplasmic reticulum
OptionC: Flow of calcium ions including release of calcium ions from sarcoplasmic reticulum
OptionD: Flow of sodium ions including flow of calcium ions from sarcoplasmic reticulum

Question: What type of cartilage is the knee joint made of?
Explanation: inelstic cartilage and articular cartilage is not one of the three types of cartilage we learned!

Question: What intracellular signalling molecule is involved in the modulation of the 'funny current' in cardiac pacemaker cells?
Explanation:
- Sympathetic mechanisms e.g. adrenaline and Beta1 adrenoreceptors upregulate cAMP to increase heart rate

- Parasympathetic mechanisms (vagal suppression), M2 receptors, downregulate cAMP to decrease heart rate 

- Metabotropic receptors

Question: Why is the equation for calculating the mean arterial pressure (MAP) not simply the average of both diastolic and pulse (systolic) pressure?
OptionA: Because systole generates more pressure than diastole
OptionB: Because you need to factor in the elastic recoil of the tunica media
OptionC: Because pressure varies between arteries depending on their distance from the heart
OptionD: Because end diastolic volume is dependent on venous return
OptionE: Because the heart spends longer in diastole
Explanation:
If you measured the arterial pressure over a long period of time, a greater proportion of that time would be spent at the lower (diastolic) pressure. Therefore the mean is closer to the diastolic pressure making the equation:

 

MAP = diastolic pressure + 1/3 pulse pressure

Question: Which one of the arteries below are not branches of the right coronary artery?
Explanation:
Branches from the RCA include; SA nodal, right marginal, posterior IV, AV nodal

 

Branches from the LCA include; anterior IV, circumflex, left marginal
Tags: anatomy, thorax anatomy, Heart, arterial supply of the heart

Question: Which two veins drain directly into the right atrium ?
OptionB: middle cardiac vain and small cardiac vein
OptionC: left marginal vein and left posterior ventricular vein
OptionD: anterior cardiac veins and smallest cardiac veins
Explanation:
Tributaries of the coronary sinus are the great cardiac vein, middle cardiac vein, small cardiac vein, left marginal vein, left posterior ventricular vein and the oblique vein of left atrium.

 

The anterior cardiac veins and smallest cardiac veins drain directly into the right atrium.
Tags: anatomy, thorax anatomy, Heart, venous drainage of heart

Question: Which vitamin is involved in the synthesis of Nicotinamide Adenine Dinucleotide (NAD)?
Explanation: Niacin (B3) contributes to the synthesis of the nuclear Nicotinamide ring in NAD. NAD is an essential electron carrier involved in many processes within the body, including Anaerobic/Aerobic respiration. A deficiency of the B3 vitamin can cause a variety of symptoms (including neurological related signs) due to its importance in many cells within the body!

Question: Between what layers of a blood vessel wall do fatty plaques form in the condition atherosclerosis?
OptionB: The tunica intima and the tunica media
OptionC: The sub endothelium and the internal elastic lamina
OptionD: The tunica media and the tunica adventitia
OptionE: The internal elastic lamina and the tunica media
Explanation: A fatty plaque will form between the tunica intima and the tunica media. Smooth muscle cells in the tunica media are then pushed up into the fatty plaque as it grows. The plasma lipoproteins VLDL and LDL which are atherogenic (carry bad cholesterol) supply immune cells in the vessel wall with lipids causing them to swell with fat forming mast cells. HDL, another lipoprotein is anti atherogenic and is able to remove lipids from the fatty plaques. As the fatty plaques in the vessel walls grow in size they can block blood flow in the vessel causing conditions such as a stroke or heart attack.

Question: The condition Scurvy is caused by a deficiency of vitamin C and gives easy bleeding seen on the gums. How does vitamin C deficiency impact on blood vessel walls?
OptionE: Haemostatic proteins are not able to function correctly in blood clotting
Explanation: vitamin C deficiency causes faulty collagen to be produced which loses vascular integrity causing easy bleeding as haemostasis is faulty

Question:
In South Africa, a 4 year old presents with a fever, a headache and vomiting. It is noted that his family cannot afford mosquito nets around their beds. 

How would you describe the most likely microbe causing these symptoms?
Explanation: The 4 year old is likely to have Malaria, which is transmitted by mosquitoes and is common in South Africa. Malaria is caused by a protozoan called Plasmodium.

Question:
Cornelia de Lange Syndrome (CdLS) is a very rare genetic disorder sometimes called Amsterdam Dwarfism. 

Child with CdLS

 

It is caused by mutations affecting the cohesin complex in chromosomes. 

What is the main role of cohesin in the cell?
OptionA: Pulling cells towards each other to form coherens junctions
OptionC: Facilitating spindle attachment to the cell membrane
OptionE: Causing cell width to increase to facilitate binding with other cells
Explanation: Cohesin is the protein that keeps sister chromatids held together at the centromere. It also facilitates spindle attachment onto chromosomes and facilitates DNA repair by recombination.

Question:
Parkinson's Disease is a disorder of the central nervous system that is both long-term and degenerative.


It is caused by the death of neurones in the substantia nigra, a part of the brain. This causes a reduction in the amount of dopamine produced in the brain.

 

Research in 2014 suggested that embryonic stem cells could be used to make new dopamine producing cells in the substantia nigra. 

Which of these statements about embryonic stem cells is the most likely reason for the theoretical treatment being developed?
OptionA: Embryonic stem cells produce more dopamine than other types of cell
OptionB: Embryonic stem cells have the ability to self-renew
OptionC: Embryonic stem cells are structurally similar to adult neurones
OptionD: Embryonic stem cells act similarly to dopamine in the brain
Explanation:
The correct answer is E: "Embryonic stem cells are totipotent". 

Embryonic stem cells can be used in this treatment as they can differentiate to form dopamine producing neurones. This could increase dopamine production and potentially treat Parkinson's patients. 

B is also a correct statement, but the ability to regenerate is not the most important reason for using embryonic stem cells.

A, C and D are incorrect.

Question: Which of the following terms best describes "Haemostasis"?
OptionC: The prevention of blood loss in the body
OptionD: The process of aiding blood loss in the body
OptionE: A disease in which prevents blood from flowing in the body
Explanation: Haemostasis is the process whereby blood loss is prevented

Question: A school teacher is brought into hospital having collapsed with a seizure following confusion and talking gibberish. Radiation therapy does not improve her condition. Upon treatment with steroids her condition greatly improves but she soon lapses back into temporary blindness, cardiac arrest and brain damage. What does the woman suffer from?
Explanation: D is correct as the steroids would kill the tapeworm causing the immune system to kick in, resulting in the second wave of symptoms. Radiation treatment failed so it isn't a brain tumour and steroids would not improve the condition of the other afflictions. Bonus points if anyone got the reference.
Tags: Radiology, Vital Signs Monitoring, Physiology, Neurobiology, Pharmacology

Question: The recurrent laryngeal nerve originates from which other plexus or nerve of the thorax?
Explanation: The recurrent laryngeal nerve which innervates the intrinsic muscles of the larynx (except cricothyroid) originates from the vagus nerve, after it enters the thorax.

Question: The P wave of a standard ECG usually has a duration of approximately what?
Explanation: The P wave is normally a smooth and rounded wave, which in a standard ECG of a healthy patient lasts in the region of <0.12 seconds

Question: An intermittent failure of excitation to pass to the ventricles is most commonly a sign or effect of which heart defect?
OptionD: Bundle Branch Block in Bundle of His
Explanation:
B - Second Degree Heart Block is the correct answer

 

First Degree heart block is a defect in which each wave of depolarisation originating in the SA node is conducted to the ventricles, but there is an abnormally long PR interval 

Second Degree heart block is a defect in which there is an intermittent failure of excitation to pass to the ventricles and includes Mobitz type I, Mobitz type II and 2:1 or 3:1 heart block 

Third Degree heart block (complete heart block) is a defect in which the wave of excitation originating in the SA node fails to excite the ventricles completely (there is an atrioventricular block) 

Bundle Branch block is a defect in which the excitation reaches the AV node and passes through the Bundle of His, only to be delayed or fail to pass from one or other branch to the ventricular muscle

Left Anterior Fascicular block (LAF) or left anterior hemlock is the block of the conduction through the left anterior fascicle

Question:
Haemophilia is a genetic condition in which causes increased and uncontrollable bleeding in suffering patients. 

Which of the following types of Haemophilia leads to a deficiency of blood coagulating factor IX (9)?
Explanation:
Haemophilia B has a deficiency in IX coagulation factor. This leads to complications in the function of the complex IXa.VIIIa in the intrinsic/propagation stages of Haemostasis, causing the inability to coagulate blood to form clots. 

 

Haemophilia A has a deficiency in VIII (8), and Haemophilia B has a deficiency in XI (11).

Question: Which of the following is NOT a layer within a blood vessel?
Explanation:
The general layers of blood vessels consist of:

 

Endothelium, 

Subendothelium,

Internal Elastic Lamina,

Tunica Media,

Tunica Adventitia 

 

(Tunica Aridimas is a made up layer - I wouldn't suggest looking that one up!)

Question: What innervates teres minor?
What clinical case would be seen if the C3, C4, C5 cords were to be damaged?
Explanation:
C3, C4, C5 - Keeps the Diaphragm alive! The diaphragm is an essential muscle within the thorax, responsible for helping physical/mechanical respiration. 

 

The fact that the phrenic nerve has roots very high up the vertebrae (C3/4/5) is an advantage to the body: if the lower back is damaged, the patient will still be able to breathe.

Question: Which medical condition is usually the result of a viral or bacterial infection of the pericardium?
Explanation:
Pericarditis is the correct answer.

 

Pericardial Bactosis is a made up condition; don't bother researching it!

Question: The most efficient gas exchange takes place at what VA:Q ratio?
Explanation: Matched ventilation and perfusion optimise gas exchange, this happens at at VA:Q ratio of 1.

Question: What is the most common cause of mitral valve stenosis?
Explanation:
Stenosis (narrowing) of the mitral valve is most commonly associated with rheumatic heart valve disease. 

Although atherosclerosis is associated with the narrowing of vessels and mixed valve disease may lead to the stenosis of some heart valves, it is known that rheumatic heart valve disease is the condition associated with stenosis of the mitral valve.

Question: DNA methylation typically acts to.......
Explanation: DNA methlyation in mammals most commonly involves the binding of a CH3 group to the 5th carbon of a cytosine ring, and typically acts to repress transcription

Question: Which type of bacteria contains the highest proportion of peptidoglycan in its cell wall?
OptionB: They have the same amount of peptidoglycan
Explanation: Gram-positive bacteria have a thick mesh-like cell wall made of peptidoglycan (50–90% of cell envelope), and as a result are stained purple by crystal violet, whereas gram-negative bacteria have a thinner layer (10% of cell envelope), so do not retain the purple stain and are counter-stained pink by safranin. Gram negative bacteria are also resistant to penicillin, due to lipopolysaccharide and protein layer that surrounds the peptidoglycan layer of the cell wall, preventing penicillin from attacking.

Question: The tunica intima is made up of 3 layers EXCEPT for the
Explanation:
The tunica intima comprises of the endothelium, subendothelium and internal elastic lamina.

the external elastic lamina lies between the tunica media and the tunica adventitia.

Question: Vitamin C deficiency causes scurvy because
OptionB: it effects the pH within the tunica adventia
OptionD: faulty elastic fibres are generated in the tunica media
Explanation: Vitamin C is required by an enzyme to hydroxylate proline. The hydroxyproline is important for collagen stability in our vessels and so lack of this results in structurally weak vessels which leads to the bleeding of gums seen in scurvy.

Question: Venous return to the heart is facilitated predominantly by 3 things except
OptionD: contraction and relaxation of smooth muscle fibres in the tunica media
Explanation:
Musculoskeletal pump: contractions and relaxation of muscles in the extremities.

 

Respiratory pump: changes is pressure of the thorax during inspiration and expiration assists venous return of blood to the heart.

 

leaflet valves: open and close in systole and diastole to facilitate unidirectional flow of blood in veins.

Question: A plaque formed by atherosclerosis in a vessel does NOT contain
Explanation: A plaque may contain smooth muscle cells and foam cells

Question: Arteries have a lower compliance than veins.
Explanation: Compliance of a vessel is the ease with which the vessel deforms under the same pressure and volume conditions. Arteries are harder to deform than veins due to the thicker tunica media/ adventitia layer and hence arteries are less compliant than veins.

Question: The popliteal vein has 6 valves and the femoral vein has 4 valves.
Explanation: While not all veins have valves, the femoral vein has about 6 valves and the popliteal vein has about 4 valves although this may vary between individuals.

Question: How is first degree heart block recognised on an ECG trace?
OptionA: Every second or third P wave fails to produce a QRS complex.
OptionB: The QT interval is less than 0.34 seconds.
OptionC: The PR interval becomes increasingly longer until a QRS complex is not produced and then the pattern is repeated.
OptionD: Most P waves produce a QRS complex but some fail to.
OptionE: The PR interval is greater than 0.2 seconds.
Explanation:
First degree heart block is recognised on an ECG by a PR interval of greater than 0.2 seconds and is not usually a problem in itself but can be a sign of other disease processes.

 

A is 2:1 or 3:1 second degree heart block

B is short QT and is caused by hypercalcaemia

C is Mobitz type 1 second degree heart block

D is Mobitz type 2 second degree heart block

Question: An elderly man comes to clinic complaining of an inability to achieve a strong grip in his right hand. Which of the following nerves is likely to have been damaged?
Explanation: The man has damaged his median nerve. This is due to the paralysis of the thenar eminence resulting in a weakened grip

Question: Which type of white blood cell below is an agranulocyte?
Explanation:
There are 3 granulocytes; neutrophils, eosinophils and basophils.

There are 2 agranulocytes: monocytes and lymphocytes.

Question: Which type of white blood cell in the largest of the granulocytes?
Explanation: Basophils are the largest type of granulocytes while monocytes are the largest type of white blood cell.

Question: Which type of white blood cell is the most commonly found in blood?
Explanation:
Neutrophils form 40-60% of WBC.

Eosinophils vary from 1-4% 

Basophils are the rarest of the WBC varying from 0.5-1%

Monocytes vary from 2-8%

Lymphocytes vary from 20-40%

Question: What surface landmark can we use to distinguish transversely the superior mediastinum from the rest of the mediastinum?
OptionA: The intercostal space between the 3rd and 4th rib.
OptionB: The apex of the xiphoid process of the sternum
OptionE: A transverse line between each of the axilla.
Explanation: The sternal angle found between the body of the sternum and the manubrium serves to separate the mediastinum underneath it. The mediastinum superior to this landmark is said to be the superior mediastinum.

Question: Which one of the answers below in not an immunoglobulin?
Explanation:
There are 5 types of immunoglobulins; IgM, IgA,IgG,IgE,IgD

Think Imaged.
Tags: immunity, Cell biology, white blood cells

Question: Haemophilia A results from a deficiency of which blood clotting factor ?
Explanation:
Haemophilia A: VIII deficiency 

Haemophilia B: IX deficiency 

Haemophilia C: XI deficiency

Question: Which protein converts fibrinogen to fibrin?
Explanation:
Thrombin allows fibrinogen to form fibrin subunits which then join to form fibrin strands due to their affinity for one another. 

Plasmin is activated by thrombin to break down cross links formed between fibrin strands.

Question: Which of the following is not a blood disorder?
Explanation:
Atherosclerosis is the formation of a plaque between the tunica intima and tunica media of a vessel due to the deposition of fatty material. 

Conjunctival pallor is more commonly known as anaemia

Question: Which protein is the most abundant in the blood?
Explanation: Albumin is a non-specific transport protein of the blood (50-60% of blood protein).

Question: Which of the following is not a type of lipoprotein?
Explanation: There are 5 types of lipoproteins: very low (VLDL), low (LDL), intermediate (IDL), high (HDL), and chylomicrons.

Question: The initiation phase of the cell-based model for blood clotting relates to which pathway of the classical model?
Explanation:
Initiation phase- extrinsic

Propagation phase- intrinsic

Question: In the cell-based model for blood clotting, in which phase does thrombin burst occur?
Which of the following is not a screening test?
Explanation: INR: international normalised ratio

Question: A platelet that binds directly to collagen has a weaker bond that a platelet that binds to von Willebrand factor.
Explanation: Platelets that bind to Von Willebrand factor (via glycoprotein IB on surface of platelet) form a stronger bond than when platelets bind to collagen (via glycoprotein IA on platelet surface) during primary haemostasis.

Question: Cell death can be caused by Apoptosis. Which of these is a cell death always due to Apoptosis?
Explanation:
Fusion of palate is a correct answer. A, C and D are displays of necrosis, the other form of cell death. E, rigor mortis, is not a form of cell death at all. 

Other displays of apoptosis include:
- Loss of vertebrate tail in development
- Formation of free digits
- Nerve cell reduction
- Tissue homeostasis 
- Cell mediated immunity 

 


EDIT: As pointed out by a commenter, viruses can cause cells to undergo apoptosis. I have edited the question to state 'always' due to apoptosis. This keeps in line with the SBA format, as more than one answer is correct, but one is more correct than the other.

Question: Which of the following is not an example of post-transcriptional modification?
Explanation: DNA methylation of cytosine residues occurs before transcription when DNA is still wrapped around the Histone proteins in nucleosomes

Question: Which type of chromatin is most transcriptionally active?
Explanation:
In euchromatin, the DNA is less tightly bound to its histone proteins than in heterochromatin (more dense) so is more transcriptionally active.

The two alternative answers are not types of chromatin.

Question: Which ofthe following represents "Aneuploidy"?
OptionA: "A cell that has the capability to differenitate into many somatic cells"
OptionB: "The presence of an abnormal number of chromosomes in a cell"
OptionC: "The presence of chromosomes tripled (3n) in the cell"
OptionD: 'The abiltiy of a cell to be differentiated into ALL somatic Cells"
OptionE: "The ability of a cell to produce a haploid polar body"
Explanation:
A - Pluripotent 

B - Aneuploidy

C - Triploid

D - Totipotent
Tags: Cell Cycle, Cell Differentiation, Cell Specialisation, Cell biology

Question: Progeria is a genetic condition in which a gene known as LMNA within cells is mutated to cause premature aging symptoms in sufferers. What is molecular consequence of this mutation for the sufferer?
OptionA: Prelamin A is not attached to the nuclear envelope in the cell.
OptionB: Lamin A is used to abnormally strengthen the nucleus
OptionC: The LMNA produces Lamin B instead of Lamin A
OptionD: Prelamin A becomes permanently attached to the nuclear rim
OptionE: An enzyme is produced which breaks down the nuclear envelope
Explanation: Progeria is caused by the mutation of Cytosine into Thymine in the gene sequence of LMNA. The mutation causes a yield of an abnormal form of Prelamin A called Progerin, in which causes the Prelamin A-type molecule to become permanently fixed to the nuclear rim. Lamin A thus not produces and is not used as a part of the Nuclear Lamina, and thus the nuclear envelope is not provided with adequate support; their nucleus takes an abnormal shape and weakens the cells ability to organise the chromatin and thus divide. This produces the symptoms mentioned above.
Tags: Genetics, Cell Differentiation, Mutation, Genetic Conditions, Cell Biology

Question: Haemophilia A is caused by a problem in which factor of the intrinsic pathway?
During Transcription Termination in Prokaryotes, which Factor determines the release of the RNA Polymerase and mRNA from the Transcription "bubble"?
Explanation: Termination of Prokaryotic Transcription is known as "Rho-Dependent".

Question:
For the second year running, London has been named the 'Cocaine capital of Europe'.

 

 

Long term crack cocaine users often experience a specific issue in the cells of the blood, as seen in the micrograph of a blood smear below. 

 

 

Which of these statements is most likely to be true about the blood of long term crack cocaine users?
OptionA: All white blood cells apart from neutrophils are destroyed.
OptionB: Eosinophils merge with lymphocytes to form eosonolymphocytes.
OptionC: The percentage composition of neutrophils in the blood rises.
OptionD: Neutrophils start to break down and form small clumps (agglutinations).
OptionE: The percentage composition of eosinophils in the blood rises.
Explanation:
E is the correct answer.
You should be able to recognise that the leukocytes in the micrograph are eosinophils, not neutrophils or a strange hybrid. The granules are clearly seen in the cell membrane and the nuclei are often joined together.

 

Crack cocaine usage can cause pulmonary and systemic eosinophilia: the increase in the amount of eosinophils in the blood. This is also seen in allergic reactions and parasitic infections. 

In crack cocaine use, eosinophilia is known to lead to eosinophilic pneumonia. This is the accumulation of eosinophils in the lung, reducing the surface area available for gas exchange to take place.
Tags: Respiration, Blood, Cell biology, Circulation, Drug use

Question: A TLR (Toll-Like Receptor) binds with 'patterns' on the cell membrane of pathogens. What is the name for these patterns?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. TLRs recognise Pathogen-associated molecular patterns. For example, TLR4 recognises lipopolysaccharide, a component of many gram-negative bacteria. 

The other options show a range of correctness.

 

B - DAMPs are also recognised by TLRs, but they are not found on the pathogen cell surface membrane. A DAMP is a result of damage caused to cells, where TLRs recognise cell elements that should not be present in the surrounding fluid. 
C - Although cAMP also ends in 'AMP', in this case it stands for "Adenosine Monophosphate" rather than "associated molecular patterns". It is not a feature of the immune response.
D & E - These are entirely incorrect.

Question: A patient presents in the clinic with significant abdominal pain. Following an ultrasound it is discovered that gallstones are likely to be the cause of this. Which of the following components of their diet are likely to be responsible for the gallstones?
Explanation: Gallstones often occur when cholesterol is crystallised in the gallbladder (or if bile is concentrated too much by the gallbladder), where bile is stored. Formation of gallstones also involves the recruitment of phosphate and calcium ions to form salts.

Question: Which of the following is not a role of the protein p53?
Explanation: p53 is a phosphoprotein consisting of 393 amino acid. It's role is to regulate the cell cycle and to prevent tumour growth. In humans 50% of tumours contain a mutation in the p53 gene. The roles of p53 are as follows: growth arrest, DNA repair and apoptosis. Apoptosis is the last resort to prevent tumour growth. Necrosis however is associated more with trauma rather as the process of necrosis causes the cell to burst causing the intracellular components to leak out. Whereas in apoptosis, the intracellular components are budded off and recycled.

Question: A young patient comes into your clinic with questions on their genetic condition known as 'Hutchinson-Gilford progeria'. Having read about the symptoms on the internet, the patient is concerned about the condition. Which of the following is not a symptom of 'progeria'?
OptionA: Arteriosclerosis increasing the risk of a heart attack.
Explanation: Progeria is a genetic disorder which essentially results in a short cell life span, hence the process of cellular aging is accelerated. Of the following symptoms, impaired intellectual development is not a symptom of the disease.

Question: You are working on an A&E ward. Late at night a man is rushed onto your ward having suffered a severe head trauma inflicted by a viscous attack by a man wielding a baseball bat wrapped in barbed wire. Upon inspection of the resultant injury, what two types of wounds are you likely to see on the skull of this man?
Explanation:
Avulsion wounds are made by strong shearing forces and friction. Unlikely to occur with a blunt weapon.

Lacerated wounds are made by tears in tissues produced by jagged, irregular edges. In this case barbed wire is likely to inflict such a wound. 

Contused wounds are made by blunt force causing tissue damage and swelling. A blunt object such as a baseball bat could produce such wounds.

Incised wounds are made by a sharp instrument such as a scalpel, unlikely to be produced in this scenario.

Burn wounds are produced by thermal, chemical or electrical injury. Again, unlikely to occur. 

Puncture wounds are produced by a pointed instrument. Perhaps evident in this scenario, but unlikely accompanied by the incised wounds as the second potential option I presented.

Abrasions are injuries where only the superficial layer of skin is removed, again unlikely in this scenario.

Question:
Smirnoff is a popular brand of vodka. In the UK alone, over 6 million people consumed Smirnoff products in the year 2015. 

 

 

Vodka is produced by fermenting sugars. Initially, grains are heated to release starch. 

Starch is a polysaccharide containing amylose and amylopectin. To allow fermentation to take place, the enzyme α-Amylase is added. α-Amylase is also found in the human pancreas and saliva. 

Which of these statements best describes the role of α-Amylase in the fermentation process?
OptionA: α-Amylase cleaves a glucose monomer off the end of the polysaccharide. This glucose can be fermented.
OptionB: α-Amylase converts amylopectin into amylose. This unbranched polysaccharide can be fermented.
OptionC: α-Amylase acts as a mixer, sweetening the taste of the drink and diluting the alcohol within.
OptionD: α-Amylase converts starch to its active form, starchinogen. This can undergo fermentation.
OptionE: α-Amylase cuts polysaccharides into maltose and maltotriose, which can be broken down further.
Explanation:
E is the correct answer. α-Amylase can only cut polysaccharides into di/trisaccharides, not into individual glucose monomers like statement A suggests.

 

In the human body, maltase is then used to break down maltose and maltotriose into α-glucose monomers. These monomers are then transported away from the gut lumen using SGLT1 transporters. 

In vodka production, maltose and maltotriose is suitable for use in distillation. 

A, B, C and D are all incorrect.

Question:
Wilson's disease is caused by the buildup of copper in the body due to a genetic defect. An overload of copper can damage your liver, brain and other organs.

 

A ring of deposited copper can be seen around the iris in many sufferers of Wilson's disease.

 

The liver is prevented from being able to metabolise and remove unnecessary amounts of copper from the bloodstream.

 

 

What is copper used for in a healthy individual?
OptionA: Copper is used for growth, development, and maintenance of bone, connective tissue and major organs.
OptionB: Copper is used in decarboxylases in the synthesis of neurotransmitters such as serotonin.
OptionC: Copper encourages hair to turn grey in old age.
OptionD: Copper binds the collagen helix-helix tighter together, thereby strengthening structures.
OptionE: Copper is used in the eye to enable vision in low light conditions.
Explanation:
A is the correct answer. Copper is used for many additional purposes, such as the formation of red blood cells, the absorption and utilization of iron, the metabolism of cholesterol and glucose, and the synthesis and release of life-sustaining proteins and enzymes.

 

These enzymes in turn produce cellular energy and regulate nerve transmission, blood clotting, and oxygen transport. Copper also stimulates the immune system to fight infections, to repair injured tissues, and to promote healing. 

 

The other answers are mostly related to other vitamins and minerals. 
B - Vitamin B6 has this function.

C - Copper deficiency can cause grey hair in Menkes Disease. 

D - Vitamin C has this role in collagen.

E - Vitamin A enables low light vision.

Question:
A neutrophil is the most common type of lymphocyte. 


In order to reach a site of infection, a neutrophil undergoes the process of diapedesis. The cytokine TNFα binds to endothelium in order to allow diapedesis to occur. 

Which of these statements best describes the action of diapedesis?
OptionA: A neutrophil breaks itself into smaller parts, diapeds, before diffusing out of the blood vessels.
OptionB: Leukocytes are squeezed out of the blood vessels between endothelial cells.
OptionC: A neutrophil moves from a lymph vessel to a blood vessel.
OptionD: Neutrophils bind to the endothelium, replacing one of the endothelial cells. The ex-endothelial cell can move on to fight infection.
OptionE: The neutrophil binds to the endothelium to wait for the pathogen to emerge.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

The other answers, A, C, D and E are all incorrect.

Question: Which of the following complement proteins is an opsonin (any molecule which enhances phagocytosis by marking a pathogen for an immune response)?
Explanation:
- C3b is an opsonising protein 

- C3a and C5a are both complement proteins that trigger an inflammatory response 

- Membrane attack complex mediates cell lysis

- CD8+ is a glycoprotein marker of cytotoxic T cells

Question: In the cell cycle, when do the 'checkpoints' that regulate the processes take place?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C - The checkpoints are after G1, G2 and Metaphase.

After G1 the environment is checked to be favourable for the daughter cells to survive.
After G2 the environment is checked to be favourable again, and the DNA is checked to have fully replicated.

After Metaphase, the chromosomes are checked to ensure they are attached to the spindle. This is critical for separation.

Question:
A 51 year old, Mr Baucher, arrives in A&E with serious lacerations on his face.

Mr Baucher is a photographer and had a bottle thrown at him while he was working at a concert. 

 

 

What is the first step you should take when Mr Baucher arrives?
OptionA: Using tweezers, remove glass from the wound.
OptionB: Send Mr Baucher to radiography to find the location of the glass.
OptionC: Refer Mr Baucher for plastic surgery due to a facial injury.
OptionD: Assess Mr Baucher and check for additional injuries.
OptionE: Check his camera to find out what happened.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. If you immediately concentrate on the wound, you may miss something life threatening elsewhere. 


A - This could open the wound further and may increase the bleeding. 

B - You are recommended to do this, but not before checking for dangers and other injuries.
C - Mr Baucher may well be referred for plastic surgery, but his safety takes priority at first.
E - There is a small chance this could be helpful (in this story, Mr Baucher did take a photo of his attacker) but not immediately or without his permission. 

 

This is a real story that took place in Belfast, in June 2016. If you are interested, there is an article about the attack here.

Question:
Telomeres are often compared to Aglets, the plastic caps on the ends of shoelaces.

 

.

 

During normal cell replication, telomeres shorten, eventually rendering the cell unable to undergo mitosis. In embryotic stem cells, the telomeres do not shorten. 

 

How do embryotic stem cells maintain their telomere length?
OptionA: Stem cells use an enzyme called hTERT to regenerate telomeres by reverse transcription.
OptionC: Stem cells have longer telomeres than somatic cells, so the shortening does not affect them.
OptionD: The cells are terminally differentiated and so do not divide.
OptionE: The enzyme Human Elongation Telomerase (hET) is used to stretch the telomere back to its original length.
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. hTERT is Human Telomerase Reverse Transcriptase, which can regenerate the sections of the telomere which shorten. 

Only embryotic stem cells produce hTERT in large amounts. When a child is born, hTERT ceases production in the majority of cells. Adult stem cells contain some hTERT, but only enough to slow the degredation process slightly.  

B - Correct, but irrelevant in this question.
C - This is not true.

D - Stem cells are undifferentiated, so this answer is incorrect. 
E - This answer represents a different idea that rather than remaking the telomere, the shortened section is stretched to maintain length. This does not make sense as the telomere shortens due to loss of bases in the chain. Stretching out the DNA further would not aid this.
Tags: Cell Cycle, Cell Differentiation, Cell Specialisation, Cell biology

Question: When triggered, which toll-like receptor(s) activate the transcriptional factor NF-kB?
Explanation: These are found in the plasma membrane. When triggered, NF-kB is activated and cytokines (TNFa, IL-1 and IL-6) are expressed and co-stimulatory ligands (B7-1/CD80 and B7-2/CD86) are also expressed. (see tutorial booklet for further info.)

Question:
You attend a pub quiz at the SU one night and come home to find a gruesome bite on your shoulder.

 

 

 

You suspect that the wound may be infected. 

What actions should be taken?
OptionA: Phone your GP, demanding that they prescribe you morphine tablets.
OptionB: Have hospital staff stitch the wound and dress using aseptic technique.
OptionC: Clean the wound and dress aseptically with a non-adherent dressing.
OptionD: Dress with aseptic technique, then take antibiotics until the wound heals.
OptionE: Take a tetanus vaccination and put some ice on the wound.
Explanation:
The correct answer is C, although it is still incomplete. 

A - This is incorrect, but talking to A&E staff and your GP about pain relief is encouraged. 

B - Although the wound is getting dressed, an infected wound should not be immediately sewn shut, as this would trap bacteria under the skin.
C - This is the only answer that does not have incorrect statements, but tetanus shots, analgesics and antibiotics should be considered.
D - Taking antibiotics is recommended, but a full course of antibiotics should be taken, not just until the symptoms fade.
E - Tetanus vaccinations are wise as you are unsure what (or who) bit you, and what their vaccination status is. However, placing ice on the wound will not keep it clean and could slow the inflammatory response. 

This question is based on a true story.

Question: In 1947 Dr Sidney Farber conducted an experiment whereby he administered anti-folates to children suffering from leukemia. The administration of the anitfolate 'aminopterin' induced remission in the patients suffering from leukemia. Anti-folates inhibit folic acid. What function of folic acid was inhibited which led to the subsequent remission?
OptionA: Folic acid is involved in the formation of DNA and RNA, thus a deficiency in folic acid would result in reduced cell division.
OptionB: Folic acid is involved in the differentiation of hematopoietic cells, thus a deficiency would reduce the number of abnormal leukocytes formed.
OptionC: Folic acid is involved in glycolysis and as such inhibiting it would reduce the number of abnormal leukocytes.
OptionD: Folic acid is involved in the formation of intrinsic protein channels that are found in the cell membranes of leukocytes, hence inhibiting them prevents the production of leukocytes.
OptionE: Folic acid is involved in the immune response which removes cancerous cells from body.
Explanation: Folic acid is essential in the formation of DNA and RNA. As such in rapidly dividing cells cannot conduct DNA replication required in cell replication. Aminopterin is an example of a substance used in chemotherapy.
Tags: Biochemistry, Blood, Cell Cycle, Metabolic pathways, osteology

Question: An 83 year old man walks into your practice with questions about a drug he has been prescribed. The drug is called Omeprazole. The man is taking the drug for treatment for gastroesophageal reflux disease. The man is a retired health care professional and would like to know about the mechanism of the action of omeprazole. Which of the following describes the function of omeprazole?
OptionA: Omeprazole directly inhibits gastrin, reducing secretion of gastric juices.
OptionB: Omeprazole is a basic compound and acts to neutralise stomach acid.
OptionC: Omeprazole acts on the parasympathetic nervous system, inhibiting AcH from stimulating the G cells to produce gastrin.
OptionD: Omeprazole stimulates increased secretion of CCK by the enteroendocrine cells. CCK inhibits gastrin.
OptionE: Omeprazole acts to inhibit H+/K+-ATPase found at the secretory surface of gastric parietal cells. This inhibits acid production.
Explanation:
'Omeprazole is a selective and irreversible proton pump inhibitor. It suppresses stomach acid secretion by specific inhibition of the H+/K+-ATPase system found at the secretory surface of gastric parietal cells. Because this enzyme system is regarded as the acid (proton, or H+) pump within the gastric mucosa, omeprazole inhibits the final step of acid production.'

 

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omeprazole
Tags: Biochemistry, Digestion and Absorption, Drug use, Pharmacology, Physiology

Question: Which of the following is an irreversible step that forms part of the series of reactions which results in gluconeogenesis.

OptionB: Phosphoenolpyruvate being converted into pyruvate by pyruvate kinase.
OptionC: Pyruvate being converted into oxaloacetate by pyruvate carboxylase.

B- This is the last step in glycolysis, however it is an irreversible reaction. 

C- This is the first step in gluconeogenesis and is an irreversible reaction. 

D- This is the first step in glycolysis and is an irreversible reaction. 

E- This is the 9th step in gluconeogenesis and is a reversible reaction. 

 

The equations will help you to work out which reactions are reversible/irreversible.

Question: Why is it significant that acetyl coA is converted to ketone bodies in response to fasting?
OptionA: Ketones yield more ATP than acetyl coA
OptionB: Ketones travel faster than acetyl coA in the blood to supply energy to the tissues
OptionC: Ketone bodies are able to cross the blood brain barrier
OptionD: The body can yield energy more easily from ketone bodies than it can from acetyl coA
Explanation: In response to fasting, amino acids are broken down (proteolysis) which requires oxaloacetate. Therefore, acetyl coA cannot bind with oxaloacetate to make citrate, halting the TCA cycle. Acetyl coA cannot cross the blood brain barrier so it is converted to ketone bodies which can. The ketone bodies travel in the blood to the brain where they are then converted back to acetyl coA and enter the TCA cycle in brain cells, thus supplying the brain with energy.

Question: Which of one of these options are in a haploid state?
Which 2 vitamins are recommended to be taken whilst pregnant?

While humans usually have two sex chromosomes, XY or XX, a duck billed platypus has XYXYXYXYXY.

 

While humans are unlikely to have 8 extra chromosomes like the platypus, sex chromosome aneuploidies are relatively common. 
Unlike aneuploidies of other chromosomes, there tends to be little impact on the life of an individual with a sex chromosome aneuploidy. 

Why are the effects of sex chromosome aneuploidies so mild?
OptionA: Y chromosomes dominate any X chromosomes, so any extra X chromosomes don't affect males.
OptionB: Only one X chromosome is active; any extras are deactivated.
OptionC: Sex chromosomes only code for production of sex cells, so the only symptoms are overproduction of sperm and egg cells
OptionD: Mutations are often miscarried and do not survive longer than a few days.
OptionE: Only factors such as the likelyhood of developing leukemia is affected by sex chromosome aneuploidy.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. In aneuploidies such as XXX or XXY, extra X chromosomes are inactivated. This means there is little impact in terms of symptoms.

 

A: This is incorrect. 

C: This too is incorrect.

D: Miscarriages are far more likely with aneuploidies of other chromosomes. 

E: You may have confused this with Trisomy 21, or Down Syndrome. In Down Syndrome the risk of leukemia is higher than for non-Down individuals.

All others are incorrect.

Question:
Erik Adolf Von Willebrand was the first to describe the blood coagulation disorder, von Willebrand disease.

This condition first caught his interest in the case of a five-year-old girl whose family had an extensive history of bleeding. Mapping her family history, von Willebrand found that 23 of the girl's 66 family members were affected by the disease.

Von Willebrand disease is due to a lack on von Willebrand factor in the blood.

Which option best describes the normal function of Von Willebrand factor?
OptionA: vWF forms clots in blood by triggering the extrinsic pathway of secondary haemostasis.
OptionC: Proteins can flow more easily in blood due to vWF.
OptionD: vWF is the type of platelet used in primary haemostasis.
OptionE: vWF binds to collagen and changes shape, allowing platelets to bind to the vWF.
Explanation:
E is the correct answer. vWF forms a strong bond with collagen and platelets. Without vWF, the platelets can only form a weak direct bond with collagen.

 
A, B and C are incorrect. 

D shows that vWF is used in Primary haemostasis, but it is not a form of platelet.

Question:
'The facial skeleton (also known as the viscerocranium) supports the soft tissues of the face. In essence, they determine our facial appearance.

It consists of 14 individual bones, which fuse to house the orbits of the eyes, nasal and oral cavities, as well as the sinuses. The frontal bone, typically a bone of the calvaria, is sometimes included as part of the facial skeleton.' - http://teachmeanatomy.info/head/osteology/skull/

 

Which of the following bones of the skull is not part of the facial skeleton?
Explanation:
The facial bones are:


Zygomatic (2) – Forms the cheek bones of the face, and articulates with the frontal, sphenoid, temporal and maxilla bones.
Lacrimal (2) – The smallest bones of the face. They form part of the medial wall of the orbit.
Nasal (2) – Two slender bones, located at the bridge of the nose.
Inferior nasal conchae (2) – Located within the nasal cavity, these bones increase the surface area of the nasal cavity, thus increasing the amount of inspired air that can come into contact with the cavity walls.
Palatine (2) – Situated at the rear of oral cavity, and forms part of the hard palate.
Maxilla (2) – Comprises part of the upper jaw and hard palate.
Vomer – Forms the posterior aspect of the nasal septum.
Mandible (jaw bone) – Articulates with the base of the cranium at the temporomandibular joint (TMJ).

 

http://teachmeanatomy.info/head/osteology/skull/

Question: how does the body increase the GFR?
OptionB: constricts the afferent arteriole and dilates the efferent arteriole
OptionC: constricts the efferent arteriole and dilates the afferent arteriole
Explanation: constricts the efferent arteriole and dilates the afferent arteriole- this means that more blood will reach the glomerulus quicker because of the wider afferent arteriole, but cannot leave quickly because of the narrower efferent arteriole. In 1953, Chapman and Hillier first discovered the mesosome in bacterial cells. 



Initially, it was thought that mesosomes played a role in cell wall formation during cell division, chromosome replication and acted as a site for oxidative phosphorylation.

 

What is the function we know now for mesosomes?
OptionA: Chromosomes wrap around the mesosome for structural integrity.
OptionC: They contain mesolytic enzymes, used to mesolate foreign bodies in the bacterial cell.
OptionD: Mesosomes have no function, as they do not exist.
OptionE: Mesosomes are an extension of the cell membrane used in exocytosis.

Question:
The compliment system produces various protein fragments known as anaphylatoxins.

 

                     C4a, an anaphylatoxin.

An anaphylotoxin triggers degranulation in surrounding cells, causing an inflammatory response. 

Which of the following protein fragments is an anaphylotoxin?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. Although this question seems far too specific, we only need to know the action of 3 parts of the complement system. 
These are: 
- C3b (an opsonin)

- C5a (an anaphylotoxin)
- Membrane Attack Complex (Forms a channel through the cell membrane, disrupting osmotic gradients in the pathogen)

If you are interested, here are the functions of each of the options given. 

A: C3b is an opsonin, binding to pathogenic cell surface membranes to attract phagocytes.
B: C5a is an anaphylotoxin, causing degranulation of endothelial cells, mast cells and phagocytes.
C: C5b is part of the membrane attack complex.
D: C8 is also part of the membrane attack complex.
E: C1q is involved in the original attachment of the antibody to the antigen on the cell surface membrane.

Question: What is a possible treatment for Dupuytren contracture, a disease resulting in progressive shortening, thickening and fibrosis of the palmar fascia and aponeurosis?
OptionB: Surgical excision of the fibrotic parts of the palmar fascia
OptionC: A plaster cast is places on the patients' fingers for 3 months to try and straighten the fingers
OptionE: Immersion of the whole hand in ice cold water daily for 5 minutes
Explanation: B is the correct answer. However, many mild forms of Dupuytren's contracture do not require treatment. Treatment is usually only required if the condition affects the function of your hand. See Moore's page 459 for more information.

Question: Where is an ulnar nerve injury unlikely to occur?
OptionA: Posterior to the medial epicondyle of the humerus
OptionB: In the cubital tunnel formed by the tendinous arch connecting the humeral and ulnar heads of the Flexi Carpi Ulnaris (FCU)
Explanation: D is the correct answer. Ulnar nerve injury usually occur in one of fours places: In the hand, at the wrist, In the cubital tunnel formed by the tendinous arch connecting the humeral and ulnar heads of the FCU and posterior to the medial epicondyle of the humerus (most common).

Question: An 89 year old man comes into your practice complaining of a drop in the quality of his vision. The patient reports that the periphery of his vision seems to be less effected than the centre of his vision. With your ophthalmoscope you observe the back of the eye to be presented with the following image. The patient has no history of diabetes and appears to have a normal blood pressure for his age. What is the likely cause of the loss in vision?
Explanation:
Age-related macular degeneration sees the atrophy of the macular leading to the loss of rods and cones. This occurs at the centre of the retina leaving the periphery unaffected. 

 

Papilloedoma- This occurs when the optic disc protrudes outward due to raised inter-cranial pressure.  

 

Glaucoma- Inward 'cupping' of optic disc due to raised intraocular pressure. 

 

Malignant hypertension- Capillaries in the retina burst, optic disc bulges forward.  

 

Cataract- Lens becomes cloudy.

Question: What type of cell junction is in cardiac myocytes?
Explanation: Gap junctions form channels that allow small, intracellular water-soluble molecule (including inorganic ions and metabolites) to pass from cell to cell. Gap junctions between cardiac myocytes allows the electrical coupling that allows electrical waves of excitation to spread synchronously through the heart.

Question: What does an RER of 0.7 suggest that the prominent fuel source of respiration is?
OptionC: An equal mix of fat and carbohydrates
Explanation:
The Respiratory Exchange Ratio is the ratio of CO2 produced (VCO2) to oxygen consumes (VO2). 

 

Glucose completely oxidised to water:

 

6O2 + C6H12O6 --> 6CO2 + 6H2O   RER = 6CO2 : 6O2 = 1

 

Fat completely oxidised to CO2 and H2O:

 

C16H32O2 + 23O2 --> 16CO2 + 16H2O   RER = 16CO2  : 23O2 = 0.7

Question: Which of these is an example of an amphibolic pathway?

Question: A diuretic means that there is increased passing of urine, and less water is reabsorbed into the blood. Alcohol and tea are example of diuretic substances. How does ADH work in a normally functioning kidney (with water rather than alcohol)?

Question: Which complex do electrons from NADH NOT pass through during aerobic respiration?

In the glycerate-3-phosphate shuttle, electrons pass through complexes 3, 4 and 5. This is found in skeletal muscle cells.

Question: A patient presents with pain in his left shoulder following a sharp, severe pain in his left chest. What is the term for when pain is felt somewhere else in the body to where it is being generated?
Explanation:
• Referred pain is pain felt in a part of the body other than its actual source.
  • Hyperalgesia is increased sensitivity to pain which may be due to tissue inflammation or damage to nociceptors.
  • Analgesia means without pain. Drugs that act to relieve pain are called analgesics.
  • Modulation - from where a noxious stimulus is detected to the brain detecting and processing the pain, the pain is modulated by inhibitory or facilitatory controls in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord. 
  • Hypersensitivity - an exaggerated immune response to a foreign agent.

Question:
You are in live lounge having a boogie and you suddenly find yourself wondering what the effects of the alcohol you are drinking are on your water retention. 

 

 

What do you conclude?
OptionA: Alcohol causes you to produce a small volume of very concentrated urine.
OptionB: Alcohol causes the kidneys to reabsorb lots of water so very small volumes of urine are produced.
OptionC: Alcohol inhibits pituitary secretions of oxytocin, so lots of urine is produced.
OptionD: Alcohol has no effect on water retention.
OptionE: Alcohol causes you to produce large volumes of dilute urine as the kidneys are not reabsorbing sufficient water.
Explanation: ADH acts on the collecting ducts of the kidneys to reabsorb water by inducing translocation of aquaporin channels into the plasma membrane. Alcohol inhibits the pituitary secretions of ADH so water isn't reabsorbed so a large volume of dilute urine is produced.

Question:
You're in the SU on the last night of term and realise you need the toilet. 

 

  

 

You decided to squeeze your way across the dancefloor between other dancers and start to remember neutrophils and their action of diapedesis during inflammation.

 

Which substances, secreted by mast cells, cause endothelial cells to retract?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

Degranulation of the mast cells causes secretion of histamine, prostaglandins, leukotrienes and interlukins, as well as other cytokines.

Histamine and interlukins cause cell-adhesion proteins (known as selectins) to move to the surface of the cell facing the blood. The neutrophils bind to these selectins. 

At the same time, prostaglandins and histamine cause vasodilation. This is what causes the gap between endothelial cells for the now-binded neutrophils to pass through.
Tags: Blood, immune response, immunity, white blood cells

Question: In an effort to improve your health, you decide to go to the gym. You return home from the gym and you start to admire the muscles of the anterior abdominal wall. You wonder, what is the name of the surface landmark highlighted with the yellow arrow?

Explanation: Exercise can trigger angina because coronary arteries fill during diastole and exercising results in a shorter diastole period. Therefore there will be less blood entering the coronary arteries and hence less blood to supply the heart. This could trigger angina.

Question: Phosphofructokinase-1 and Fructose 1,6-Bisphosphatase are two key enzymes in the regulation of glycolysis and gluconeogenesis. Their activation and inhibition is controlled allosterically by a particular molecule (produced by a bi-functional enzyme). What is the name of this molecule?
Explanation:
PFK-1 and Fruc-1,6-BPase are affected allosterically by Fructose-2,6-Bisphosphate. 

This molecule inhibits the Fruc-1,6-BPase and activates PFK-1 

The bi-functional enzyme controls the conversion of this molecule to Fructose-6-Phosphate and visa versa. 

Low levels of Fructose-2,6-Bisphosphate will increase gluconeogenesis, inhibiting glycolysis
High levels of Fructose-2,6-Bisphosphate will increase glycolysis, inhibiting gluconeogenesis.

This is important in ensuring a futile cycle does not occur between glycolysis and gluconeogenesis.

Question: Which of these is NOT an example of one of the regulatory mechanisms of the TCA cycle?

Explanation:
Glycogen Phosphorylase is involved in the removal of glucose molecules from glycogen in glycogenolysis.

NAD+ is needed as an electron acceptor n the TCA cycle and so A and B do regulate the cycle. 
Isocitrate dehydrogenase is a major regulatory enzyme in the TCA cycle that is allosterically inhibited by the products of its reaction. 
The pyruvate dehydrogenase complex is involved in the links reaction that produces a supply of Acetyl CoA for the TCA cycle. Less production of Acetyl-CoA will limit the rate of the cycle.
