Question:
Quaaludes (Methaqualone) are a type of medication that became popular as a recreational drug in the 1960s. They became recognised by the public again in 2013 by the movie The Wolf of Wall Street.

 

    

 

'Ludes' work by positively allosterically modulating GABA receptors. 

 

Using your knowledge of GABA receptors and their effect on action potentials, suggest the drug class of Quaaludes.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B: Quaaludes are a type of sedative. 

'Positive allosteric modulator' means that the drug changes the shape of the GABA receptor, allowing it to be activated more easily than normal.

 

 

 

GABA generates inhibitory signals, so when more GABA receptors are triggered:
- More Cl- channels open in the post-synaptic membrane.

- Cl- ions flood into the neurone.
- The membrane becomes hyperpolarised.
- The amount of neurotransmitter needed to produce an action potential increases. 
- Fewer action potentials fire in the neurones, so sedation is achieved.
Tags: Neurotransmitters, Physiology, Membrane transport, Central Nervous System, Neurology

Question: How do phosphodiesterase inhibitors affect the heart?
OptionA: less cAMP produced and less calcium enters cell decreasing force of contraction.
OptionB: more cAMP produced and therefore less calcium enters cell decreasing force of contraction
OptionC: Less cAMP produced and more calcium enters cell increasing the force of contraction
OptionD: More cAMP produced and therefore more Calcium enters cell, increasing the force of contraction.
Explanation: Phosphodiesterases inhibit cAMP production, therefore as the phosphdiesterases are inhinited, more cAMP will be produced. This will then cause the phosphorylation of phospholamban and voltage gated Calcium channels by protein kinase A. The calcium channels will be open for longer and therefore more Ca will enter the SR from the ECF. There is therefore more Ca in the SR. The phosphorylated phospholamban then means that there is enhanced CaATPase in the SR causing more Ca in the SR. There is therefore increased Ca release and greater force of contraction. Also due to the increased CaATPase activity, the Ca is removed from the cytosol faster and then the Ca-troponin  binding time is shorter and the cross bridge time is shorter creating shorter duration of contractions.

Question:
On 15th December 2016, doctors in Newcastle were officially approved to use IVF to make a baby with 3 parents.

 

 

The babies will have two mothers and a father. Suggest why this procedure is being used.
OptionA: Designer babies can be created by choosing which genes to keep from each mother.
OptionB: Three parents allows for a wider genetic variation in communities with over-average rates of inbreeding.
OptionC: An increase in golgi from an extra cell allows more enzymes to be produced, if the child is likely to inherit a faulty enzyme.
OptionD: Mitochondria from the second egg are used when the original mother has mitochondrial disease, as mitochondria are passed directly to the child from the mother.
OptionE: This increases the immune response of the baby by up to 50% as there are potentially more antibodies.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. Mitochondria are passed directly from mother to child, so if mitochondria are damaged, it is very likely the child will inherit the faulty organelles and die at a young age. 

 

At the time of writing (16/12/16), this was only confirmed yesterday. Of course, there are ethical arguments claiming that this is a slippery slope to allowing 'Designer babies'. The full article can be found here.

Question: Billy Shears works as a barber. He comes into your practice having cut himself whilst slicing through a particularly thick head of hair. Upon inspection of the wound you see that it has already began to heal. The first step in the healing of a wound is primary haemostasis. The first step in this process is vasoconstriction of blood vessels. Which of the following substances secreted by endothelial cells causes vasoconstriction?
Explanation:
Endothelin is the only vasoconstrictor on this list. In a healthy endothelial cell, NO and prostacyclin are secreted along with endothelin to strike a balance between vasoconstriction and vasodilation. Once an injury has occurred, production of NO and prostacyclin falls, causing the balance to shift towards endothelin. Hence we see vasoconstriction. Adrenaline is secreted by the adrenal glands and acts as a beta 2 adrenergic receptor agonist, causing vasodilation. Histamines are produced by basophils and mast cells in order to stimulate inflammation as part of the immune response. 

 

For more information on primary haemostasis check out this Khan academy video.

Question: Which of the following best describes frequency potentiation?
OptionA: A build-up of neurotransmitter in the synaptic cleft.
OptionD: The increase in neurotransmitter secreted following action potentials in close succession.
Explanation: If the interval between successive action potentials is short, the EPSPs will increase in amplitude as more neurotransmitter is secreted (and therefore it is more likely that threshold potential is reached). This phenomenon is referred to as frequency potentiation. A build-up of neurotransmitter in the synaptic cleft is referred to as temporal summation. (This may be a consequence of frequency potentiation). Sometimes the increase in amplitude may last many hours after the successive action potentials and this is referred to as long-term potentiation and is an example of synaptic plasticity.

Question:
Your friend comes to you and says 'hey you're a medical student, why does my nose look like this?'.

 

Having been told prior to this that your friend likes to take cocaine, what do you tell your her?
OptionA: You have damaged your trochlear nerve (CN IV) which causes vasoconstriction of the blood vessels that supply the nose. This means not enough oxygen is reaching the septum causing the septum lining to die. This causes perforation of the septum.
OptionB: Sniffing cocaine causes vasodilation of the blood vessels that supply the nose. This means too much blood is reaching the septum causing perforation of the septum.
OptionC: Cocaine is an anaesthetic. By taking it you will have numbed your nose so will not have felt being hit in the nose or hitting your nose on something. Trauma has caused this.
OptionD: Cocaine acts directly on the cells of the septum tissue and causes necrosis resulting in perforation of the septum.
OptionE: Sniffing cocaine causes vasoconstriction of the blood vessels that supply the nose. This means not enough oxygen is reaching the septum causing the septum lining to die. This causes perforation of the septum.
Explanation:
Sniffing cocaine causes vasoconstriction of the blood vessels that supply the nose. This means not enough oxygen is reaching the septum (ischaemia) causing the septum lining to die. Once the lining dies, it can no longer support the cartilage underneath it and the cartilage dies. This is perforation of the septum. Once the septum is perforated, the nose can collapse because the septum is the structural support of the nose.

 

A is incorrect because the trochlear nerve has nothing to do with vasoconstriction or vasodilation and damage to it will not have this effect.

B is incorrect because cocaine stimulates the sympathetic nervous system and therefore causes vasoconstriction and not vasodilation.

C is incorrect because although cocaine is an anaesthetic, septum perforation in this case is more likely to be as a result of the vasoconstriction caused by cocaine abuse and not trauma. 

D is incorrect because cocaine does not act in this way.

Question: A patient presents with muscle pain, weakness, vomiting and confusion. You suspect he has Rhabdomyolysis. You take a blood sample. If your diagnosis is correct, which enzyme do you expect to see at higher than normal concentrations (>1000 U/L).
Explanation:
Creatine Kinase would be detected in the blood at a level >1000 U/L. (>5000 U/L in severe cases). Creatine kinase is found at high concentrations in muscles, so detecting high concentrations of it in the blood, together with the above symptoms, is a good indication that the patient has rhabdomyolysis (rapid breakdown of skeletal muscle).

Myoglobin would also be detected in the blood in the case of rhabdomyolysis but it is not an enzyme.

Question: What are the key differences between skin dermis dense connective tissue and tendon dense connective tissue?
OptionA: The tendon has significantly more elastic tissue and much less frequent fibroblasts than the skin dermis connective tissue.
OptionB: In the tendon, the collagen fibres are multi-directional instead of unidirectional, there are more frequent fibroblasts and more elastic tissue.
OptionC: In the skin, there are more frequent fibroblasts, however there are unidirectional collagen fibres compared to the multi-directional fibres of a tendon.
OptionD: In the skin, the collagen fibres are multi-directional instead of unidirectional, there are more frequent fibroblasts and more elastic tissue.
OptionE: The skin has much less collagen fibres than the tendon, its fibroblasts are less frequent and its collagen fibres are multi directional.
Explanation:
The skin has multi-directional collagen fibres, the tendon has unidirectional fibres. This is because the skin can be under multi-directional stress whereas stress in a tendon tends to come in a unidirectional movement. 

The skin also has more fibroblasts in its dermis as it has a higher turnover of collagen.

The skin also has a more significant amount of elastic fibre as if not, the skin would be non-stretchy and would not spring back to its original position after being stretched.
Tags: PCS-1, PCS1, Histology, Epithelium Histology, PCS 1

Question: What type of cartilage does this image represent?
Explanation:
In elastic cartilage, the chondrocytes are found in a threadlike network of elastic fibres within the matrix.
Elastic cartilage provides strength, and elasticity, and maintains the shape of certain structure such as the external ear.

Fibrocartilage  the strongest kind of cartilage, because it has alternating layers of hyaline cartilage matrix and thick layers of dense collagen fibres oriented in the direction of functional stresses.


Hyaline cartilage has widely dispersed fine collagen fibres (type II), which strengthen it. The collagen fibres are hard to see in sections.


In terms of spotting the cartilage. Fibrocartilage has more unidirectional collagen fibres. Hyaline cartilage has more spaced out chondrocytes. Its collagen fibres are also harder to see in the matrix.

Question: during regulatory volume decrease, which channels open in response to a hypotonic cell?
Explanation: A hypotonic cell occurs when a cell swells as it has a lower water potential than its surroundings. In response to a cell swelling, the cell undergoes regulatory volume decrease in which K+ ion channels, Cl- ion channels, and K+/Cl- co-transporters are activated which causes an efflux of the respected ions out of the cell. A hypertonic cell occurs when the cell has a higher water potential than its surroundings so water moves out causing the cell to shrink. Regulatory volume increase occurs in which the Na+/H+ antiporter, Na+ channels and Na+/K+/Cl- co-transporters are activated to cause an influx of these respected ions to re-establish the cell.

Question: What does the ECG show?
Explanation:
Atrial fibrillation is a lack of synchronised depolarisation of atria but is not life threatening. 

 

Third degree heart block is where conduction through AV node does not occur at all. Ventricular contraction occurs independent of stimulation from the AV node. However, the rate is very slow (30-40 times per minute) because it is determined by the rate of bundle of His fiber discharge.

 

Premature atrial contraction - stimuli outside of normal conduction pathway may cause an extra contraction called extrasystole.

 

Ventricular fibrillation is lack of synchronized depolarization of ventricles and is incompatible with life.

 

Second degree heart block is where Conduction through the AV node does not always occur. This is indicated by the occasional absence of QRS complex and T wave after P wave. 

 

 

Source - http://droualb.faculty.mjc.edu/Course%20Materials/Physiology%20101/Chapter%20Notes/Fall%202011/chapter_13%20Fall%202011.htm

Question:
A group of scientists are studying mitosis in a lab. They add a solution containing radioactively labelled Guanine nucleotides to a culture of cells undergoing mitosis. The nucleotides are added at the start of mitosis, during prophase and their growth is stopped at the end of Telophase.

Where in the cells at the end of this study would you find the radioactively labelled Guanine?
OptionA: Only in the nuclei of the original cells, not the nuclei of the daughter cells produced by mitosis.
OptionB: Only in the nuclei of the daughter cells produced by mitosis.
OptionC: Not in any of the cells' nuclei.
OptionE: Only in the nuclei of half of the cells.
Explanation:
The nucleotides would be in none of the cells. 

This is because DNA replication, where the radioactively active nucleotides could be incorporated into the DNA of the cells, occurs during the S phase of the cell cycle. 

Mitosis, is the process of separating the DNA to form two identical daughter cells.

Question: Which of these lists best describes the components needed in order for DNA replication to occur?
OptionA:
• a single stranded template
  • deoxynucleoside triphosphates
  • a primer
  • a DNA helicase enzyme
OptionB:
• a DNA polymerase enzyme
  • a primer
  • free nucleotides 
  • a single stranded template
OptionC:
• deoxynucleoside triphosphates 
  • a single stranded template
  • a DNA polymerase enzyme
  • a primer
OptionD:
• a primer
  • a DNA polymerase enzyme
  • a double stranded template
  • deoxynucleoside triphosphates
OptionE:
• a primer
  • deoxynucleotide phosphates 
  • a single stranded template
  • a DNA polymerase enzyme
Explanation:
In order for DNA replication to occur, the following components are needed: 

  • single stranded template: a pre-existing strand of DNA. Hydrogen bonds form between the nitrogenous base on the new nucleotide and the complementary base on the pre-existing strand, forming new DNA. 
  • DNA polymerase: catalyses the joining of nucleotides. 
  • deoxynucleoside triphosphates (dATP, dGTP etc): these provide the nucleotide subunits needed to make DNA. Free nucleotides cannot be used alone as breaking off two of the phosphate groups present on the deoxynucleoside triphosphate releases the energy required to drive the reaction. 
  • a primer: a short piece of nucleic acid base-paired to the template, which acts as a start point; a 3’-OH group. Primers are made from RNA and so can be synthesised from scratch.
Tags: PCS 2, Biochemistry, Cell biology, Cellular Function, Chromosomes

Question:
There is a man called Tim. Tim's blood flow through the descending aorta at a point in his cardiac cycle is 7 litres per minute. 

Tim begins exercising and the increased cardiac output of his left ventricle causes the descending aorta to stretch, doubling its radius. 

For some reason, Tim's blood then becomes unusually thick during his exercise, and its viscosity triples. 

What will his new blood flow rate be? (provided all other variables remain constant)


Please note: The values and scenarios in this question do not reflect real life, they are simply made up for the purposes of this question, to understand how Haemodynamics work.
Explanation:
Flow rate through a tube is proportional to the change in radius ^4

This means doubling the radius of the tube (aorta in this case) will change the radius by x2^4 

So in this case 7 x 2^4 = 112 litres per minute 

His blood viscosity (thickness) then triples. Viscosity is inversely proportional to flow rate. 

This means that tripling the viscosity of the blood will mean the flow rate is 3 times less than originally. 

So in this case 112 / 3 = 37.3 litres per minute (1dp)

Now answer D says 37.3 but it is litres per second not minute

If we divide 37.3 by 60 to get the flow rate in litres per second, the answer is 0.6 L/s (1dp)

The answer is therefore B.

For more information, refer to the 'cardiac cycle components' tutorial in PCS unit 2.
Tags: PCS 2, Heart, Cardiovascular System, Circulation, Haemodynamics

Which of these are the three regulatory points of glycolysis?

Question: Here is a diagram of the complement activation pathways. But which pathway is A,B,C and D?
OptionA:
A = Lectin pathway
B = Classical pathway
C = Alternative pathway
D = Terminal pathway
OptionB:
A = Alternative pathway
B = Lectin pathway
C = Classical pathway
D = Terminal pathway
OptionC:
A = Terminal pathway
B = Alternative pathway
C = Lectin pathway
D = Classical pathway
OptionD:
A = Classical pathway
B = Alternative pathway
C = Lectin pathway
D = Terminal pathway
OptionE:
A = Classical pathway
B = Lectin pathway
C = Alternative pathway
D = Terminal pathway
Explanation:
Looking at what complements each pathway activates was how to work through this question.

The classical pathway is activated when an antibody (IgM of IgG) binds to a pathogen, this is recognised by C1. This indicated that pathway A was the classical pathway.

The lectin pathway is activated by mannose residues on pathogens. This is recognised by mannan binding lectin (MBL). This indicated pathway B was the lectin pathway.

Also, both the classical pathway and lectin pathway cause the activation of C4. 

The alternative pathway eventually leads to the accumulation of C3b. This is an indication that pathway C was the alternative pathway. 

All these 3 pathways converge to form the terminal pathway, indicating pathway D was the terminal pathway.

For more information, look at the immunity tutorial in PCS Unit Two.

Question: What is commensalism?

OptionB: When the microbe benefits whilst the host does not benefit and is harmed in the process.

OptionD: When the host benefits but the microbe does not benefit.
OptionE: When neither the host or the microbe benefit from each other.
Explanation:
This question is relating to how microbes interact with host cells.

C is an example of commensalism and is the correct answer.

Mutualism is when both the host and microbe benefit.

Parasitism is when the host is damaged due to the presence of the microbe, but the microbe benefits from the process.

Question: Where would you direct the patient to look if you wanted to test the function of the function of their superior oblique muscles?
Explanation:
If you want to test the function of a single extraocular muscle, you have to turn the eye to a position where a single action of each muscle predominates. This is because the actions of the extraocular muscles are complex.

 

Turning the eye inwards places the superior oblique in position to lower the eye.

 

This may seem contradictory, as the action of the superior oblique is to turn the eye down + out, but if  it was tested clinically by asking the patient to look down and out its action could be mimicked by the combined action of inferior and lateral recti. This is particularly so as the inferior rectus acts most effectively when the eye is abducted (looking laterally). Therefore by asking the patient to look down and in these muscles are excluded and the problem is solved. Essentially we are testing the ability of the superior oblique to look downwards. (BMJ)

Question: Which of the following gene mutations causes an almost 100% risk of offspring suffering from Down's Syndrome (Trisomy 21) IF either parent is a carrier?
Explanation:
Robertsonian Translocation is the mutation process whereby the two long (q) arms one from one chromosome of a set, and the other from another, (i.e. set 21 and 14) fuse - the short (p) arms are discarded. This forms a total of three chromosomes (21, 14, t14:21) that, if fertilised, can cause a variety of genetic disorders.

 

In the relevance of Down's Syndrome, the two chromosomes of set 21 are mutated to only form t21:21. Therefore, the possible gametes produced are either the t21:21 (as the translocated material cannot be separated) or nothing. This means that the two possible outcomes are either Trisomy 21 or Monosomy 21 on fertilisation - Monosomy 21 is lethal and usually causes spontaneous termination during pregnancy. Therefore, the only other offspring possibility is Trisomy 21: the child is born with Down's Syndrome.

During the Translation Stage of protein synthesis, the tRNA molecules are required to "transfer" corresponding amino acids to the codon found at the ribosome.

 

What does the P binding site stand for, and what is its function?
OptionA:
Polymerisation binding site.

 

Area where only pre-made polymers of protein attach to the ribosome.
OptionB:
Peptidase binding site.

 

Where the enzyme Peptidase binds to the ribosome
OptionC:
Peptidyl binding site.

 

Where the Aminoacyl tRNA holding the polypeptide chain binds to the ribosome.
OptionD:
Polymerisation binding site.

 

Where the Aminoacyl tRNA holding the polypeptide chain binds to the ribosome.
OptionE:
Protein binding site.

 

Where the manufactured protein binds before exiting the ribosome.
Explanation:
There are three main binding sites on the ribosome for tRNA molecules carrying amino acids to bing:

1. P - peptidyl; "Holds" the tRNA supporting the polypeptide chain made in downstream translation.

2. A - Aminoacyl; Accepts "new" tRNA molecules once the Initiation complex has been formed.

3. E - Exit; tRNA molecules that shift into this site can exit the ribosome can become free to be reused.

Question: Pyruvate Kinase is involved in the third irreversible steps of glycolysis. Which of the following is NOT a regulatory point of Pyruvate Kinase.
OptionA: It is inhibited by ATP, because if there is lots of ATP glycolysis is not required
OptionB: It is inhibited by Alanine because Alanine is made from pyruvate so if there is a lot of alanine, there is no need for any more pyruvate.
OptionC: It is up regulated by Fructose 1,6 bisphosphate (from previous irreversible step) in a feed forward mechanism. Therefore, if there is more Fructose 1,6 bisphosphate coming through, it will speed up the reaction of this enzyme (more substrate).
OptionD: There is a different isoform of this enzyme present in the Liver (L form), where it is covalently regulated by high blood glucose level triggered by insulin.
Explanation: Pyruvate Kinase is covalently regulated in the Liver by AMP cascade triggered by low glucose levels and glucagon release. In this cascade, Pyruvate Kinase is phosphorylated and this switches off the enzyme, so less glucose is broken down. Instead, it is conserved for brain and muscles.

Question: When playing frisbee with your friends, you trip over and graze your face so that it starts to bleed. Despite the pain, you begin to think about how primary hemostasis works. During primary hemostasis, endothelial cells play a vital role in initiating the formation of the platelet plug in a wound. What secretion of endothelial cells causes vasoconstriction of the blood vessel?
Explanation:
D - Endothelin is the correct answer - it is a vasoconstrictor.

 

A, C - nitric oxide and prostacyclin are secreted by endothelial cells and they are vasodilators. They are in a balance with endothelin to keep the blood vessel at the right diameter.

B - von Willebrand factor is secreted by endothelial cells and platelets to bind to the subendothelial collagen and act as a glue for the platelets to stick to and form the platelet plug.

D - correct

E - fibrinogen is released as one of the granules in a platelet and when it is released into the blood, it needs to be converted into fibrin to be used to stabilise the platelet plug. It does this by the coagulation cascade. This cascade is activated in 2 ways: Firstly, it can be activated by the exposure of subendothelial collagen which activates its own coagulation factors to trigger the coagulation cascade - this is the intrinsic pathway. Or the cascade can be activated by the extrinsic pathway, which is when thromboplastic (tissue factor) is released by endothelial cells into the blood when they are damaged.

Question: Type 1 interferons are proteins involved in innate immunity. They play a role in preventing the spread of a viral infection throughout the body. Which of the following best describes the function of type 1 inferferons?

OptionB: Type 1 interferons bind to receptors on neighbouring cells surrounding an infected cell. This causes a reduction in mRNA translation, hence the virus is surrounded by cells which cannot replicate it.
OptionC: Type 1 interferons bind to H1 receptors on the cell membranes of endothelial cells. This causes the activation of a protein called phospholipase C, which then makes a chemical called IP3, which is involved in making blood vessels dilate.
OptionD: Type 1 inteferons are released during phagocytosis in order to convert superoxide to hydrogen peroxide which is used to destroy the contents of a phagosome.

A- Explanation describes the activation of natural killer cells. 

B- Correct explanation of the function of type 1 interferons. 

C- This describes the mechanism of histamines.

D- This describes the role of superoxide dismutase in phagocytosis.

Question:
Conditions in which people are born, grow, work, live, and age, and the wider set of forces and systems shape the conditions of daily life. These forces and systems include economic policies and systems, development agendas, social norms, social policies and political systems. 

 

What is this definition of:
Explanation:
Social determinants of health:

 Inequality – not absolute poverty or absolute richness – is what causes significant health issues. It is not limited to a lifestyle / individual choice.
 Income and status or class, gender, and ethnicity all produce different forms of inequalities. Greatest influences on the improvement in health have been not so much medical discoveries as improved social conditions.
 Importance of the social world and how it is structured (not all about personality or biology).

 

Social cohesion:
- Feeling part of a community.
- Good social networks .
- Putnam’s (1993) notion of “social capital”: trust, support, community identity, and social networks.

 

Stigmatisation:

- Bodies are inscribed with social meanings (shaped by certain values and experiences).
- Sets possessors apart from normal people and mark them as socially unacceptable or inferior beings.
- Seen as to be avoided, rejected, or shunned to varying degrees by others (e.g. disability/mental illness, severe burns, AIDS, deafness?).
- ‘[the person] possesses a stigma, an undesired different from what we anticipated’ (Goffman 1963: 1).

Aetiology
E.g. How does stress cause illness or where is the root of the problem

Public health

Question:
After talking to a Health Psychologist about the behaviour of her son (who plays violent games), her husband (heavy smoker) and her friend (who is obese), Jane has come up with the following ideas:

 

i) To Take her husband on a holiday if he tried to give up smoking

ii) To help her friend repay her debts if she tried to eat healthy food and exercise

iii) To make her son do all the washing if he continued to play violent games

 

Match the above actions with the consequences on the behaviours:
OptionA:
i) Positive Reinforcement

ii) Negative Punishment

iii) Negative Reinforcement
OptionB:
i) Positive Reinforcement

ii) Negative Reinforcement

iii) Positive Punishment
OptionC:
i) Positive Punishment

ii) Negative Reinforcement

iii) Positive Reinforcement
OptionD:
i) Negative Reinforcement

ii) Negative Punishment

iii) Positive Punishment
Explanation:
Negative reinforcement try to think of removal (taken away) of an undesirable stimulus as a result of a behaviour and the behaviour that led to this removal is reinforced in the future because it created a favourable outcome.


Positive reinforcement involves the addition of a desirable stimulus following a behaviour that makes it more likely that the behaviour is reinforced and will occur again in the future.


Positive punishment, try to think of it as adding a negative consequence after an undesired behaviour to decrease future responses.


Negative punishment, try to think of it as removal (taking away) a desired stimulus item after the undesired behaviour happens in order to decrease future responses.

Question:
Tanya ran the Cardiff half marathon with her friends. She remembered that she was advised by her personal trainer to drink hypotonic solutions. It is best for hydration and sustained energy. It's a good idea to use a hypotonic solution of a carbohydrate drink containing a good balance of electrolytes during a run, so she drank 600 ml of hypotonic solution.

 

How will the 600 ml hypotonic solution affect her GFR (glomerular filtration rate) and urine excretion if she was at rest.
OptionA:
Blood osmolality increased so concentrated/low  volume of urine excreted (high ADH release) 

Blood volume has increased a little so no measurable effect on GFR
OptionB:
Blood osmolality decreased so dilute/high volume of urine excreted (Low ADH release)
Blood volume has increased a little so no measurable effect on GFR
OptionC:
Blood osmolality decreased so dilute/high volume of urine excreted (Low ADH release)
Blood volume has decreased so GFR goes down
OptionD:
Blood osmolality unchanged so no difference in volume of urine excretion

Blood volume increased so slight increase in GFR
OptionE:
Blood osmolality increased so concentrated/low volume of urine excreted (high ADH release)

Blood volume increase so slight increase in GFR
Explanation:
A and C are made up

D- This happens when you drink isotonic 600 ml solution so no change in osmolality but there is an increase in volume, as there is additional fluid in the blood.

E- This happens when you take 3g of salt. This increases the osmolality of the blood as there is more solute dissolved in the blood. Because the blood has become hypertonic, fluid will move from the cells into the blood and this will increase the volume of the fluid in the blood. 

B- This happens when you take hypotonic 600 ml solution. Some of the fluid moves into the cell (400 ml) and some stays in Extra cellular fluid (200 ml). Blood gets about 1/4 of the total ECF fluid (1/4 of 200 = 50 ml) which  decreases its osmolality. There is a very small increase in volume of blood so no effect seen in GFR.

Question: What is the cause of the dicrotic notch (also known as incisura)?
Explanation: The aortic valve opens when the pressure in the left ventricle is greater than the aorta. However the aorta is compliant "stretchability". The blood entering pushes off into the wall and cause the walls to stretch. The aortic pressure increases, once exceeding that of the left ventricle the aortic valve closes. There is passive recoil in the aorta caused by the stored elastic energy, this causes the release of blood from within their walls, some of which goes back to the aortic valve, only to bounce off; "snap back", resulting in a slight increase in aortic pressure shown by the dicrotic notch.

Question: Why is vagal withdrawal necessary during exercise?

Many fractures of bones within the wrist are possible after falling onto the wrist in different ways. When someone has fallen onto an outstretched palm and with the hand abducted, one particular fracture is very common. The likelihood of a carpal bone having fractured (with a very high likelihood of this bone in particular) can quickly be established in a patient without an x-ray and in only a few seconds by very gently applying pressure into the region of the anatomical snuff box - the patient will almost certainly feel some pain (be sure to warn them beforehand).

 

Which carpal bone is most likely to have been fractured?
Explanation:
The scaphoid bone is the most commonly fractured in this type of fall, often down onto an outstretched hand. Whilst trapezium is also underneath the anatomical snuff box, it is because the hand is abducted that the scaphoid bone is more likely to have taken the pressure of the fall and fractured in the process.

 

That this type of fall - onto an outstretched palm, with abducted hand - causes a fracture of this particular carpal bone might help you remember where the scaphoid is relative to other carpal bones. It's closer to the wrist (which is why the abduction places more pressure on it when fallen onto), and it's underneath the anatomical snuff box.

Question:
While scrolling through Facebook you find this meme:

You begin to tag your friends when you start to think of the fact that around 50% of the world's population suffers from Vitamin D Deficiency. You are aware that there are two forms of Vitamin D, which form can by synthesised by the body in the presence of UV-B radiation?
Explanation:
Vitamin D is a fat soluble vitamin that exists in two forms: D2 & D3. D2 is produced by plant life in response to sun light, while D3 is made in the body from cholesterol when exposed to sunlight (through hydroxylation in the liver and kidneys).

 

Your body can use both forms, but D3 performs a lot better than its counterpart. Vitamin D plays a key role in Calcium absorption.

Question:
Your elderly neighbour has a nasty fall outside their house after coming home in the dark. She goes to A&E and is seen to but she's so tired and exhausted by then that she forgets a lot of what was said to her - she knows she broke her arm in the fall, but little else. You meet her a few days later and since she knows you've studied medicine for all of a few weeks she mistakes you for a consultant.

 

As you're trying to explain that you remember nothing but the hangovers and falling asleep in lectures she suddenly remembers some details, and says that doctors told her she fractured her humerus at the surgical neck.

 

At which position did your neighbour's humerus suffer a fracture?
Explanation:
A is roughly speaking the anatomical neck of the humerus, just next to the head.

B is the surgical neck - this kind of fracture is common in elderly people with osteoporosis, even when the fall is low energy or onto the hand.

C is an arbitrary point a little below the deltoid tuberosity, though it's possible to sustain what's called a transverse fracture (following some blunt trauma directly to the humerus) on this line or the area around it.

D is another unremarkable point on the humerus, just above the epicondyles and the site of articulation with the radius and ulna. It could be the site of a supra-epicondylar fracture (which can be caused following a bad fall during childhood).

  • Solar plexus = a complex of ganglia and radiating nerves of the sympathetic system at the pit of the stomach.
  • Choriod plexus = plexus of cells that produces the cerebrospinal fluid in the ventricles of the brain

Question: What does having Ventilation to Perfusion ratio of 0 indicate:
Which of the following decreases Lung Compliance?
OptionB: Surfactant produced by type II alveolar cells
OptionD: Increase in age due to reduction in elastic tissue of lungs
Explanation:
Pulmonary fibrosis is a condition in which the lung tissue becomes thickened, stiff and scarred over a period of time. The development of the scar tissue is called fibrosis. As the lung tissue becomes scarred and thicker, the lungs lose their ability to distend, which reduces their compliance. 

 

Compliance is increased in obstructive lung disease like pulmonary emphysema, less in asthma and at a minor degree in chronic bronchitis. In emphysema, the elastic recoil is decreased and the P-V curve is shifted up and left. This is due to the loss of elastic tissue as a result of alveolar wall destruction so less elastic recoil and increased compliance. 

 

There loss of elastic tissue, less elastic recoil and increased compliance comes with increasing age as well.

 

Pulmonary surfactant increases compliance by decreasing the surface tension of water. The internal surface of the alveolus is covered with a thin coat of fluid. The water in this fluid has a high surface tension, and provides a force that could collapse the alveolus. The presence of surfactant in this fluid breaks up the surface tension of water, making it less likely that the alveolus can collapse inward

These are associated with reduced risks of heart disease, obesity and diabetes and other inflammatory conditions.

Question:
In the 1960's James W. Black developed a drug called propranolol after modifying a structurally similar agent called dichloroisoprenaline. Both dichloroisoprenaline and propranolol are beta-blockers - they inhibit the effects of catecholamines on beta adrenoceptors. Use of propranolol quickly increased following release on the market due to its efficacy treating a variety of heart conditions such as angina (or as treatment following a heart attack) as well as hypertension.

 

However, in 1976 atenolol - a drug in the same class as propranolol - was released, and has since almost completely overtaken use of propranolol for treating these same conditions.

 

Why?
OptionA: Propranolol is too non-specific and has an action on beta-3 adrenoceptors in addition to beta-1 adrenoceptors; atenolol only has an action on beta-1 adrenoceptors.
OptionB: Atenolol does not have the same toxicity problems as propranolol when metabolised.
OptionC: Propranolol is too non-specific and has an effect on beta-2 adrenoceptors in addition to beta-1 adrenoceptors; atenolol only has an action on beta-1 adrenoceptors
OptionD: Propranolol is too non-specific and has an action on alpha-1 adrenoceptors in addition to beta-2 adrenoceptors; atenolol only has an action on beta-2 adrenoceptors.
OptionE: Atenolol is less specific than propranolol and therefore has a useful effect on more classes of beta receptor.
Explanation:
The answer is C. Propranolol effects both beta-1 and beta-2 adrenoceptors; atenolol only effects beta-1 adrenoceptors. I'll explain why that's better:

 

Adrenoceptors come in two categories, and there are five types: there are alpha-1 and alpha-2; then there are beta-1, beta-2 and beta-3.

 

The two most important ones are beta-1 and beta-2. An easy way I was shown to remember their roles or where they're found is that you have one heart, so beta-1 adrenoceptors are found in the heart; and you have two lungs, so beta-2 adrenoceptors are found in the lungs (specifically the brochi and bronchioles, as well as any other significant smooth muscle features present).


The fundamental issue with propranolol that isn't apparent when atenolol is used is the unwanted activation of beta adrenoceptors outside the heart and vasculature - specifically, you have activation of the beta-2 adrenoceptors as well as beta-1, which can cause significant problems in any patients with underlying or additional pulmonary conditions such as asthma or fibrosis. If you're treating a heart problem and you have one drug with an effect on receptors found only in the cardiac system vs. another drug with effects outside it, you should (all other things being equal) use the more specific drug to treat as there is less potential for adverse or unwanted effects.

Question: Where is the lumbar puncture performed on a child?
OptionA: At the level L1 - L2  because the Lumbar cistern is largest at the Conus Medullaris.
OptionB: At the level L4 - L5 because the spinal cord and lumbar cistern extends lower in the spine in children.
OptionC: At the level L2 - L3 because the spinal cord and lumbar cistern is shorter in children.
OptionD: At the level L3 - L4 because this is the location of the lumbar cistern, where CSF can be extracted easily.
Explanation: Children are born with a longer spinal cord. During development the growth of the spinal cord slows before that of the vertebra, meaning that the level of termination of the cord and dural sac is higher in adults and lower in children.

Question: What is the suggested Daily Intake for women in Kj?

It is believed that by eating hot food regularly, degeneration of the of the receptive terminals of nociceptors occur. This is because of an agonist which binds to the TRPV1 receptors and constant exposure to this agonist inactivates the receptor. This agonist is used as an analgesic for diabetic neuropathies. What is this agonist called?
Explanation:
TRPV1 is a nonselective cation channel that may be activated by a wide variety of exogenous and endogenous physical and chemical stimuli. The best-known activators of TRPV1 are: capsaicin, the irritating compound in hot chili peppers; and allyl isothiocyanate, the pungent compound in mustard and wasabi. The activation of TRPV1 leads to a painful, burning sensation.

 

Upon prolonged exposure to capsaicin, TRPV1 activity decreases, a phenomenon called desensitization. Extracellular calcium ions are required for this phenomenon, thus influx of calcium and the consequential increase of intracellular calcium mediate this effect.

Question: Which of the following Analgesics assert the Gate Control Theory of pain?
Explanation:
Gate Theory of pain: low threshold mechanoreceptors (touch), synapse onto same interneurone in substantia gelatinosa – inhibition of nociceptive signal. (This is why rubbing painful area makes it feel better – same concept used in TENS = transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation)

 

Opioid neurotransmitters: e.g. endorphins, enkephalins, inhibit transfer of signals from nociceptive nerve endings to spinothalamic interneurones in dorsal horn

 

Descending modulation: e.g. via serotonin from serotonergic neurones; also inhibits transmission from nociceptive endings; can be under control of higher brain centres to reduce pain sensation depending on emotional state

 

NMDA Antagonists: accumulation of Substance P in the dorsal horn as a result of prolonged stimulation, leads to potentiation (wind-up) of nociceptive pathways, due to increased activity of NMDA glutamatergic receptors.

 

NSAIDs: tissue damage results in release of histamine (from mast cells), prostaglandins and bradykinin. These substances increase sensitivity of nociceptive sensory endings. NSAIDs inhibits the release of these inflammatory chemicals.

Question: Which area of the brain controls fine, skilled movements?
Explanation:
The primary motor cortex is in the frontal lobe of the brain. It projects to motor neurones through corticobulbular tracts (to brainstem), corticospinal tracts (directly to spinal cord) and cortical extrapyramidal tracts (indirectly to spinal cord).

It projects to contralateral motorneurones - which descend down the spinal cord in the lateral part of the ventral horn.The lateral motor neurones in the spinal cord control the distal muscles in the body and therefore are involved in skilled movement.

 

The supplementary motor area (SMA) also projects to distal muscles but is involved in the initiation and planning of movement.

 

The premotor cortex (PMC) projects to the brainstem, reticulospinal and corticospinal tracts. It descends down more medial pathways, and so controls more proximal muscles. This means that it is important in postural control. It also controls movement sequence and preparation for movement.

 

The Basal ganglia work with the cortical projection areas and regulate the planning and execution of movement.

 

The cerebellum processes sensory information and can compare intended movement with actual movement.
Tags: PCS 3, Central Nervous System, Neurology, Neurology PCS 3

Question: Which of the following is FALSE regarding Pemphigus vulgaris?
OptionB: There is a fault with cohesion between keratinocytes
OptionC: Antibodies attack the connexins, claudins and occludins
OptionD: Fluid builds up between the keratinocytes and basement membrane, forming blisters
Explanation:
Pemphigus is an autoimmune disease caused by antibodies directed against both desmoglein 1 and desmoglein 3 present in desmosomes. Loss of desmosomes results in loss of cohesion between keratinocytes in the epidermis, and a disruption of the barrier function served by intact skin.

Question: What type of Collagen fibres  can be found in articular and hyaline cartilages, and the eyes?
Explanation:
Collagen type 1 is the most numerous in number among all collagen types. It can be found in bones, skin, and intervertebral disks. It can also be found in scar tissue. Among the collagen types, it is used in the research industry.

 

Collagen type 2 has fibrils that are important for providing tensile strength to tissues. It can be found in articular and hyaline cartilages, and the eyes. Type II collagen is used in the treatment of arthritis, cellulite, and wrinkles.

 

Collagen type 3 is the second most abundant collagen in the body. It is closely related to collagen type I in terms of location and manner of synthesis. It is primarily located in the intestinal walls, muscles, and blood vessels, although it can also be found with collagen type I. Collagen type I and type III can be mixed together to create supplements for the skin, bone, and muscles. Mostly Reticulate (around organs like spleen and liver)

 

Collagen type 4: forms basal lamina, the epithelium-secreted layer of the basement membrane.


Collagen type 5: cell surfaces, hair and placenta

Question: What is the principle excitatory neurotransmitter in nociceptive sensory neurones?
Explanation:
Most sensory neurones, including nociceptive sensory neurones, use glutamate as their primary excitatory neurotransmitter.

 

Substance P is also released by nociceptive sensory neurones, but only when the axons are carrying high frequency trains or continuous spike trains of action potentials. The release of substance P is required for a stimuli to be perceived as moderate to intense pain.

Question:
Glucose is the primary source of energy for humans and animal life, but it can't cross membranes without help. To move it into cells or more generally across the phospholipid bilayer we have a specialised group of membrane proteins, known as the GLUT (glucose transporter) or SLC2A (solute carrier) family.

 

There are five that have been addressed in lectures: GLUT1, 2, 3, 4 and, predictably enough, GLUT 5. Which GLUT proteins are insulin responsive?
Explanation:
First off I hope this table works in whatever window you're viewing it; it's what was in the lecture 'Energy without Oxygen' and is the basis for the question.

 

             Tissue:                                           Function                           Km(mM)       

_________________________________________________________________

GLUT1   All tissues                                      Basal uptake                  1                   

GLUT2   Liver & beta pancreas tissues       Insulin responsive          15-20

GLUT3   All tissues                                      Basal uptake                  1

GLUT4   Muscle & adipose tissue               Insulin responsive           5

GLUT5   Tissue within the ileum                 Mainly fructose uptake    n/a

 

Km is a value we can use as a marker for glucose affinity, or how attracted to glucose/likely to bind glucose a molecule is. The lower a Km value is, the higher the affinity.

 

As you can see from the table, only GLUT2 & GLUT4 are insulin responsive; GLUT1 & GLUT 3 are responsible for the basal uptake (think of it as baseline supply of glucose to the cell) and GLUT5 is mainly used in uptake of fructose (since fructose is a structural isomer of glucose the transporter is included in the family).

Question:
V2: You wake up late the morning after the night before and your bike's got a puncture. You arrive late to your 9am with the notorious Andrew Shore who, true to form, makes you walk back out the door you came in through and round to the entrance at the back of the lecture hall. When you finally sit down you catch a last glimpse of the previous slide, with the enzymes responsible for the ten steps of glycolysis ordered and summarised.

 

What do you scribble down when you ask your mate what the order of the enzymes was?
OptionA:
1. triose phosphate isomerase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3. phosphofructokinase

4. aldolase

5. hexokinase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate kinase

8. enolase

9. phosphoglycerate mutase

10. pyruvate kinase
OptionB:
1. hexokinase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3. phosphofructokinase

4. aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate mutase

8. phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase
OptionC:
1. triose phosphate isomerase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3. phosphofructokinase

4. phosphoglycerate kinase

5. hexokinase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. aldolase

8. phosphoglycerate mutase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase
OptionD:
1. hexokinase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3.phosphofructokinase

4.aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate kinase

8. phosphoglycerate mutase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase
OptionE:
1. hexokinase

2. phosphofructokinase

3. phosphoglucose isomerase

4. aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase

8. phosphoglycerate mutase

9. pyruvate kinase

10. enolase
Explanation:
I appreciate that this is a nightmare question and one that hopefully never sees the light of the exam hall. As such, I'm going to post two editions of this question, beginning V1 and V2: that way if you want to try it again on the other version without being shown your answer, you can. The format will be the same, the answers will be mixed up.

 

The correct sequence is that listed in answer D:

 

1. hexokinase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3.phosphofructokinase

4.aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate kinase

8. phosphoglycerate malase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase

 

Some of these should be simple to remember, or at least reason out.

 

First some key enzyme name hints. Kinases phosphorylate molecules, isomerases change shapes of molecules, dehydrogenases dehydrate or move hydrides (H-) and phosphatases remove phosphate groups from molecules

  • If you remember the structure of a glucose molecule, it is often displayed or drawn as a hexagon; hexokinase phosphorylates something hexagonal, i.e. glucose, so it has to be the first out of the ten!
  • If hexokinase has phosphorylated glucose, it seems reasonable that the next enzyme could be named along those lines  - so phosphoglucose isomerase will hopefully stick in your mind as the second enzyme.
  • phosphoglucose isomerase will have changed the shape of the previous molecule without adding or taking away (hence the isomer part of the name). The exact product is fructose 6-phosphate. Fructose is a well-known isomer of glucose. Applying the same logic as the last step then, phosphofrucokinase is likely to act on fructose 6-phosphate and therefore be the third enzyme.
  • The next step is harder to remember, and I'm much less scientific. Aldolase is the fourth enzyme, and I always think of the shoe company Aldo (a free pair for the product placement would be good if you're reading this CEO of Aldo). Aldolase's function is to split the 6-carbon chain we've had since phosphoglucose isomerase into a pair of two 3-carbon chain molecules, so I think of a pair of shoes and that makes me think of Aldo and aldolase; hence, aldolase comes fourth.
  • After splitting the carbon chain into two 3-carbon molecules their shapes are changed again. The Latin for 3 is tri, like triangular, tricycle, and triose - so keeping in mind the splitting effect of aldolase, triose phosphate isomerase is the fifth enzyme.
  • The products of aldolase were 2 unequal 3-carbon chains: one was dihydroxyactone phosphate (DHAP), the other is glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (GAP). Triose phosphate isomerase has changed the shape of DHAP ---> GAP, so that there are now 2 identical molecules of GAP. Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate is vital to the pathway from glucose to pyruvate. I am emphasising the importance of Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate so it sticks - because you need to remember that the next (sixth) enzyme is glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase. This is one of the other hard ones to remember - if you have something that works to help then let me know.
  • The next two steps are seventh and eighth. As you process glucose with each enzyme it slightly changes from the last molecule; bearing this in mind, phosphoglycerate is a slightly changed form of the name glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate, so the two enzymes beginning phosphoglycerate should come next. How to choose between phosphoglycerate kinase and mutase? This again in unscientific, but since this process started with a kinase (it seems so long ago by now!), the kinase goes first, then the mutase. That gives us the phosphoglycerate kinase as seventh, and phosphoglycerate mutase as eighth.
  • Now we only have left enolase and pyruvate kinase vying for ninth and tenth. The end result of glycolysis of one glucose molecule is two molecules of pyruvate, so seeing pyruvate kinase at the end should be a good prompt; we know pyruvate kinase comes tenth. Now we know by deduction that there is only enolase left, and only the ninth space to fill - enolase has to be ninth.

It's not a very well ordered or consistent explanation but it does help me remember - let me know if it's any good or if it's too confusing. The same explanation will be at the bottom of the other version.

Question:
V1: You wake up late the morning after the night before and your bike's got a puncture. You arrive late to your 9am with the notorious Andrew Shore who, true to form, makes you walk back out the door you came in through and round to the entrance at the back of the lecture hall. When you finally sit down you catch a last glimpse of the previous slide, with the enzymes responsible for the ten steps of glycolysis ordered and summarised.

What do you scribble down when you ask your mate what the order of the enzymes was?
OptionA:
1. hexokinase

2. phosphofructokinase

3. phosphoglucose isomerase

4. aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase

8. phosphoglycerate mutase

9. pyruvate kinase

10. enolase
OptionB:
1. triose phosphate isomerase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3. phosphofructokinase

4. phosphoglycerate kinase

5. hexokinase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. aldolase

8. phosphoglycerate mutase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase
OptionC:
1. hexokinase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3. phosphofructokinase

4. aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate malase

8. phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase
OptionD:
1. triose phosphate isomerase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3. phosphofructokinase

4. aldolase

5. hexokinase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate kinase

8. enolase

9. phosphoglycerate malase

10. pyruvate kinase
OptionE:
1. hexokinase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3.phosphofructokinase

4.aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate kinase

8. phosphoglycerate malase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase
Explanation:
I appreciate that this is a nightmare question and one that hopefully never sees the light of the exam hall. As such, I'm going to post two editions of this question, beginning V1 and V2: that way if you want to try it again on the other version without being shown your answer, you can. The format will be the same, the answers will be mixed up.

 

The correct sequence is that listed in answer E:

1. hexokinase

2. phosphoglucose isomerase

3.phosphofructokinase

4.aldolase

5. triose phosphate isomerase

6. glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate

7. phosphoglycerate kinase

8. phosphoglycerate malase

9. enolase

10. pyruvate kinase

 

Some of these should be simple to remember, or at least reason out.

 

First some key enzyme name hints. Kinases phosphorylate molecules, isomerases change shapes of molecules, dehydrogenases dehydrate or move hydrides (H-) and phosphatases remove phosphate groups from molecules

 

  • If you remember the structure of a glucose molecule, it is often displayed or drawn as a hexagon; hexokinase phosphorylates something hexagonal, i.e. glucose, so it has to be the first out of the ten!
  • If hexokinase has phosphorylated glucose, it seems reasonable that the next enzyme could be named along those lines - so phosphoglucose isomerase will hopefully stick in your mind as the second enzyme.
  • Phosphoglucose isomerase will have changed the shape of the previous molecule without adding or taking away (hence the isomer part of the name). The exact product is fructose 6-phosphate. Fructose is a well-known isomer of glucose. Applying the same logic as the last step then, phosphofrucokinase is likely to act on fructose 6-phosphate and therefore be the third enzyme.
  • The next step is harder to remember, and I'm much less scientific. Aldolase is the fourth enzyme, and I always think of the shoe company Aldo (a free pair for the product placement would be good if you're reading this CEO of Aldo). Aldolase's function is to split the 6-carbon chain we've had since phosphoglucose isomerase into a pair of two 3-carbon chain molecules, so I think of a pair of shoes and that makes me think of Aldo and aldolase; hence, aldolase comes fourth.
  • After splitting the carbon chain into two 3-carbon molecules their shapes are changed again. The Latin for 3 is tri, like triangular, tricycle, and triose - so keeping in mind the splitting effect of aldolase, triose phosphate isomerase is the fifth enzyme.
  • The products of aldolase were 2 unequal 3-carbon chains: one was dihydroxyactone phosphate (DHAP), the other is glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (GAP). Triose phosphate isomerase has changed the shape of DHAP ---> GAP, so that there are now 2 identical molecules of GAP. Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate is vital to the pathway from glucose to pyruvate. I am emphasising the importance of Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate so it sticks - because you need to remember that the next (sixth) enzyme is glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase. This is one of the other hard ones to remember - if you have something that works to help then let me know.
  • The next two steps are seventh and eighth. As you process glucose with each enzyme it slightly changes from the last molecule; bearing this in mind, phosphoglycerate is a slightly changed form of the name glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate, so the two enzymes beginning phosphoglycerate should come next. How to choose between phosphoglycerate kinase and mutase? This again in unscientific, but since this process started with a kinase (it seems so long ago by now!), the kinase goes first, then the mutase. That gives us the phosphoglycerate kinase as seventh, and phosphoglycerate mutase as eighth.
  • Now we only have left enolase and pyruvate kinase vying for ninth and tenth. The end result of glycolysis of one glucose molecule is two molecules of pyruvate, so seeing pyruvate kinase at the end should be a good prompt; we know pyruvate kinase comes tenth. Now we know by deduction that there is only enolase left, and only the ninth space to fill - enolase has to be ninth.

It's not a very well ordered or consistent explanation but it does help me remember - let me know if it's any good or if it's too confusing. The same explanation will be at the bottom of the other version.

Question: What is meant by the term facultative metabolism?
The classical and alternative pathways meet at which complement component?
Explanation: Each pathway of complement activation produces a C3 convertase, either C4b2b (classical and lectin pathways) or C3bBb (alternative pathway), which cleaves C3 into C3a (chemotaxis: causes leaky epithelium) and C3b (opsonisation).

Question:
Here is an image of a scapula:

 

 

Two muscles, teres minor and teres major, have their proximal attachment or 'origin' on the lateral border of the scapula. Where are the distal attachments or 'insertions' for teres minor and major respectively?
OptionA:
Teres minor inserts on the inferior facet of the greater tubercle of the humerus;

 

teres major inserts on the medial lip of the intertubercular sulcus of the humerus.
OptionB:
Teres minor inserts on the inferior facet of the greater tubercle on the humerus;

 

teres major inserts on the deltoid tuberosity of the humerus.
OptionC:
Teres minor inserts on the middle facet of the lesser tubercle on the humerus;

 

teres major inserts on the inferior region of the intertubercular sulcus of the humerus.
OptionD:
Teres minor inserts on the middle facet of the greater tubercle of the humerus;

 

teres major inserts on the inferior facet of the greater tubercle of the humerus.
OptionE:
Teres minor inserts on the superior facet of the greater tubercle on the humerus;

 

Teres major inserts on the lesser tubercle on the humerus.
Explanation:
The answer is A.

 

Whilst teres minor and major have attachments adjacent to each other on the lateral border of the scapula they have very different insertions, relations and hence function.

  1. Teres minor laterally rotates the shoulder joint, i.e. it helps the arm rotate away from the body, so the muscle runs from the scapula around the outside of the scapula to the greater tubercle on the humerus (see first image below).
  2. Teres major adducts and medially rotates the shoulder joint, i.e. helps the arm come down or rotate towards the body - the muscle actually runs close under the armpit and inserts on the medial lip of the intertubercular sulcus, so that when it contracts it pulls the arm 'inward' (see second image).

Question:
Aspirin is non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID), but also acts as an anticoagulant. 

 

 

Which part of haemostasis does aspirin affect?
OptionB: It inhibits the biosynthesis of Thromboxane A2.
OptionC: It causes a conformational change in Glycoprotein 1b.IX on the cell surface of platelets so they can't bind to Von Willebrand factor.
OptionD: It stimulates increased levels of Thromboxane A2 to be synthesised by platelets.
OptionE: It prevents the conformational change that Von Willebrand factor undergoes when it binds to collagen, so platelets don't bind to Von Willebrand factor.
Explanation:
B is the correct answer.

In the normal clotting cascade, once platelets have bound to Von Willebrand factor (which is bound to collagen), they are activated and release ADP and Thromboxane A2. Aspirin inhibits the production of Thromboxane A2. Aprspirin is therefore an effective anti-platelet drug.

Because this glycoprotein is crucial for the normal absorption of B12, its lack in the presence of pernicious anemia causes a vitamin B12 deficiency.

 

What is this Glycoprotein called?
Explanation:
Haptocorrin also known as transcobalamin-1 (TC-1) or cobalophilin is a protein that protects the acid-sensitive vitamin B12 while it moves through the stomach.

 

Pepsin is an enzyme in the stomach

Question: Which of the following statements is FALSE in the regulation and secretions of Gastrin?
OptionA: D cells in the stomach release Somatostatin which inhibits Gastrin
OptionB: CCK from I cells of duodenum and secretin inhibit Gastrin
OptionC: Histamine work similar to Gastrin by stimulating gastric acid secretion from the parietal cells
OptionD: When food enters the stomach, G cells trigger the release of gastrin in the blood during the Gastric phase
OptionE: Leptin increases Gastrin secretion by G cells in the pyloric antrum of stomach
Explanation:
Leptin:
Released by adipose tissue:  Makes you feel not hungry (supresses appetite)/ stimulates brown fat metabolism

 

Secretin: helps  to regulate the pH of the duodenum by inhibiting Gastrin and the secretion of gastric acid from the parietal cells of the stomach. Also, it stimulates the production of bicarbonate from the centroacinar cells and intercalated ducts of the pancreas.

 

CCK mediates digestion in the small intestine by inhibiting gastric emptying and decreasing gastric acid secretion. It stimulates the acinar cells of the pancreas to release a juice rich in pancreatic digestive enzyme.

 

Histamine:

 

Enterochromaffin-like cells, located within the gastric glands of the stomach, release histamine that stimulates nearby parietal cells by binding to the apical H2 receptor. Stimulation of the parietal cell induces the uptake of carbon dioxide and water from the blood, which is then converted to carbonic acid by the enzyme carbonic anhydrase.

 

Somatostation:

In the stomach, somatostatin acts directly on the acid-producing parietal cells via a G-protein coupled receptor (which inhibits adenylate cyclase, thus effectively antagonising the stimulatory effect of histamine) to reduce acid secretion. Somatostatin can also indirectly decrease stomach acid production by preventing the release of other hormones, including gastrin,

Question: The drug Tetracaine is a local anaesthetic which decreases the coral reflex of the eye, how is this effect causes?
OptionA: Decreased secretion of neurotransmitter from the pre-synaptic cleft
OptionD: Increased secretion of neurotransmitter into synaptic cleft
Explanation:
The corneal reflex 

Sensory input: mechanoreceptors detect pressure caused by particulates on the sensitive cornea

Motor-response: Blinking helps spread the tears across the cornea and sweep the particulate matter out of the eye 

 

Tetracaine blocks the voltage-gates Na+ channels which prevents an action potential being propagated along the sensory neurone and therefore acts as a local anaesthetic and decreases the corneal reflex of the eye.

Question: Which of the following do NOT apply to 5 alpha reductase  deficiency syndrome
OptionB: Many people with 5-alpha reductase deficiency are born with external genitalia that appear female. In other cases, the external genitalia do not look clearly male or clearly female (sometimes called ambiguous genitalia)
OptionD: Most affected males are unable to father a child (infertile).
Explanation:
All the others are true apart from A. Genetics of 5 alpha reductase deficiency is 46 XY. During puberty, people with this condition develop some secondary sex characteristics, such as increased muscle mass, deepening of the voice, development of pubic hair, and a growth spurt. The penis and scrotum (the sac of skin that holds the testes) grow larger. Unlike many men, people with 5-alpha reductase deficiency do not develop much facial or body hair. Most affected males are unable to father a child (infertile).

 

Children with 5-alpha reductase deficiency are often raised as girls. About half of these individuals adopt a male gender role in adolescence or early adulthood.

 

47 XXY = Klinefelter syndrome (sometimes called Klinefelter's, KS or XXY) is where boys and men are born with an extra X chromosome. They have enlarged breasts (gynaecomastia) and in adulthood – inability to have children naturally (infertility).

Question: There is structure  located in the right ventricular apex that connects the interventricular septum to the anterior papillary muscle. What is this structure called?
Explanation:
The trabeculae carneae (columnae carneae, or meaty ridges), are rounded or irregular muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the right and left ventricles of the heart

 

The pectinate muscles (musculi pectinati) are parallel ridges in the walls of the atria of the heart

 

The chordae tendineae, or heart strings, are cord-like tendons that connect the papillary muscles to the tricuspid valve and the mitral valve in the heart

 

The coronary sinus is a collection of veins joined together to form a large vessel that collects blood from the heart muscle (myocardium). It delivers deoxygenated blood to the right atrium

Question:
Fick's Principle to measure Flow (Cardiac Output): A marker substance is used like oxygen. Total oxygen consumption (ml per minute) by the body divided by the difference between the oxygen concentration in arterial and venous blood (ml per ml of blood) gives Cardiac Output. 

 

 

Using Fick's Principle calculate the Cardiac Output
Explanation:
1. 700 ml / min (total oxygen consumption)
  2. 0.14 ml / mL of blood (Pulmonary artery blood is deoxygeneated so it is same as Venous blood)
  3. 0.21 ml /mL of blood (Brachial artery blood is oxygenated so it is same as Arterial Blood)
  4. 700/0.07 = 10000 mL/min = 10 L / min

Question:
On an ECG each small square represent 0.04 second and each large square represent 0.2 seconds.

John did an ECG and on his ECG there were 4 large squares between two successive R waves. His stroke volume (amount of blood pumped around the body per beat) was 80 ml.

 

Calculate his Cardiac Output:

 

Cardiac Output = Stroke Volume x Heart Rate
Explanation:
1. RR interval = 0.2 x 4 = 0.8
  2. Heart Rate = 60/ RR interval = 60/0.8 = 75
  3. CO = 75 x 80 = 6000 mL/min = 6 L/min

Question:
Bitemporal hemianopsia is the medical description of a type of partial blindness where vision is missing in the outer half of both the right and left visual field:

 

Lesion/Compression in which part of the Visual Pathway leads to the above deficit in vision?
Explanation:
Bitemporal hemianopsia is the medical description of a type of partial blindness where vision is missing in the outer half of both the right and left visual field. It is usually associated with lesions of the optic chiasm, the area where the optic nerves from the right and left eyes cross near the pituitary gland.

 

Homonymous hemianopsia, or homonymous hemianopia, is hemianopic visual field loss on the same side of both eyes. If there is a lesion on the Left side of the optic tract, visual pathways for the right hemifield of both eyes will be damaged, and if the lesion is on right side of the optic tract then the visual pathways for the left hemifield of both eyes

Question:
Medical ethics is a sensible branch of moral philosophy and deals with conflicts in obligations/duties and their potential outcome.

 

 

Different strands of thoughts exist in ethics regarding decision-making:In one approach, all that matters is that we do the right thing even if the outcomes/consequences does not just justify the means to achieve it. All that matters is that we consider our duties and obligations.

 

What is this approach called?
Explanation:
- Deontology 
- All that matters is that we do the right thing (ends alone may not justify means)
- Utilitarianism
- All that matters is how things turn out (ends justify the means)
- Virtue ethics
- All that matters is what sort of person we are: difficult because does it mean that you are not influenced by others or does it mean you are

 

 

Autonomy in ethics refers to individual freedom or one's right to make decisions without being coerced. It is the concept of social, political and ethical morals that give individuals the rational right to make their own informed choices.

Question: Which of the following is NOT a principle of Medical Ethics?
Explanation:
Autonomy
Requires that the patient have autonomy of thought, intention, and action when making decisions regarding health care procedures. Therefore, the decision-making process must be free of coercion or coaxing. In order for a patient to make a fully informed decision, she/he must understand all risks and benefits of the procedure and the likelihood of success. Because ARTs are highly technical and may involve high emotions, it is difficult to expect patients to be operating under fully-informed consent.

Justice

The idea that the burdens and benefits of new or experimental treatments must be distributed equally among all groups in society. Requires that procedures uphold the spirit of existing laws and are fair to all players involved. The health care provider must consider four main areas when evaluating justice: fair distribution of scarce resources, competing needs, rights and obligations, and potential conflicts with established legislation. Reproductive technologies create ethical dilemmas because treatment is not equally available to all people.

Beneficence

Requires that the procedure be provided with the intent of doing good for the patient involved. Demands that health care providers develop and maintain skills and knowledge, continually update training, consider individual circumstances of all patients, and strive for net benefit.

Non-maleficence

Requires that a procedure does not harm the patient involved or others in society. Infertility specialists operate under the assumption that they are doing no harm or at least minimizing harm by pursuing the greater good. However, because assistive reproductive technologies have limited success rates uncertain overall outcomes, the emotional state of the patient may be impacted negatively. In some cases, it is difficult for doctors to successfully apply the do no harm principle.

Question:
Descending motor pathways can be divided into lateral and medial motor systems based on their location in the spinal cord.

 

The lateral motor pathways control movements of the extremities and the medial pathways control the movements of the proximal axial and girdle muscles.

 


Which of the following motor pathways control the voluntary rapid dexterous movement at individual digits or joints.
Explanation:
Descending motor pathways can be divided into lateral and medial motor systems based on their location in the spinal cord.

 

  • The two lateral motor systems are the lateral corticospinal tract (voluntary) and the rubrospinal tract (subconscious), which control movements of the extremities.The lateral corticospinal tract in particular is essential for rapid dexterous movement at individual digits or joints.
  • Most of these pathways cross over from their site of origin and descend in the contralateral spinal cord to control contralateral extremities.

 

  •  The four medial motor systems are the anterior corticospinal tract (voluntary) , the vestibulospinal tract, the reticulospinal tract, and the tectospinal tract (all three are subconscious).
  • These pathways control proximal axial and girdle muscles involved in postural tone, balance, orienting movements of the head and neck, and automatic gait-related movements.
  • The medial motor systems descend ipsilateral

Question: Where is aldosterone released from?
Explanation: Aldosterone is released from the adrenal glands in response to decreases in blood volume. It stimulates the reabsorption of sodium (and water therefore follows) in the kidney leading to increases in blood volume.

Question:

In humans, fungal infections in the ear are relatively uncommon. Why is this?

Question:
There are networks responsible for locomotion that are distributed throughout the lower thoracic and lumbar regions of the spinal cord. These biological neural networks  produce rhythmic patterned outputs in the limbs without sensory feedback.

 

These networks inhibit and excite alternative extensors and flexors in different legs which leads to rhythmic movements. 

Transection of the spinal cord (cutting off dorsal roots) doesn’t abolish the stepping mechanism. Spontaneous  recovery of stepping movements still present.

 

 

What are these neural networks called?
Explanation:
A monosynaptic reflex has only one synapse in between an outgoing motor response and an incoming sensory; a good example of this would be kicking the leg outward, which is also referred to as a knee jerk. Monosynaptic reflexes are the most basic type of reflex motions.

Basically the afferent (sensory neurone) forms ONE synapse with the efferent (motor neurone)

 

Polysynaptic reflex: Afferent forms multiple synapses with interneurones connecting to efferent motor neurones. In polysynaptic reflex pathways, one or more interneurons connect afferent (sensory) and efferent (motor) signals. 

 

Central Pattern Generation: Brown proposed half-centre model where one set of CPG neurones project to flexors and the other set project to extensors.

 Increasing activity in one pool of
motoneurons (e.g., extensors) would be gradually inhibited
by a corresponding increase of recurrent inhibition. Architecturally,
this model takes into account known neuronal
connections — it is constituted of a closed chain of neurons
to which flexor and extensor motoneurons are connected in

Question: Beyonce is busy slaying the stage on her formation world tour, giving you vocals, aesthetic and general greatness, and of course you can't avert your eyes, and god forbid you dare to leave for one second to buy a bottle of water. The arena is hot and you're becoming thirstier by the minute. Which hormone is responsible for this increased thirst?
Explanation:
Macula densa cells in the Distal convoluted tubule detect low concentration of Na+ in the epithelia and communicate with the Juxtaglomerular cells causing them to release renin. Renin is released into circulation where it hydrolyses Angiotensin into Angiotensin 1. Angiotensin 1 is then cleaved into Angiotensin 2 by Angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE). Angiotensin 2 does a few things:

 

- Stimulates ADH release

- Vasoconstriction

- Thirst reflex

 

It also acts on the adrenal cortex causing it to produce aldosterone which in turn causes an increase of Na+ resorption, therefore increasing water resorption as water will follow.

Question: What type of receptor does noradrenaline bind to to cause smooth muscle contraction?
Explanation:
Noradrenaline is involved in both smooth muscle contraction and relaxation.
When it is released and binds to an α1 adrenoreceptor at a neuromuscular junction it stimulates smooth muscle contraction (it causes smooth muscle relaxation when it binds to a β2 adrenoreceptor)
The α1 adrenoreceptor is a G-Protein Coupled Receptor (GPCR).
The stimulation of this receptor causes the α and βγ sub-units of the G-protein to dissociate.
The Gαq subunit activates the enzyme Phospholipase C.
This causes the cleavage of PIP2 into IP3 and DAG.
IP3 causes the release of Ca2+ from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.
The Ca2+ binds to and activates the protein calmodulin.
Calmodulin is a myosin light chain kinase - it phosphorylates myosin which means that the smooth muscle is able to contract.
Tags: Neurology, Neurology PCS 3, Neurotransmitters, muscle contraction

D = ADH
