Question:
Chronic myeloid leukemia is a slow-growing cancer of the blood-forming tissue (bone marrow).

Normal bone marrow produces red blood cells (erythrocytes) that carry oxygen, white blood cells (leukocytes) that protect the body from infection, and platelets (thrombocytes) that are involved in blood clotting.

In chronic myeloid leukemia, the bone marrow produces too many white blood cells. Initially, these cells function relatively normally. However, as the condition progresses, immature white blood cells called myeloblasts (or blasts) accumulate in the blood and bone marrow. The overgrowth of myeloblasts impairs development of other blood cells, leading to a shortage of red blood cells (anemia) and platelets.

 

Which of the following shows the karytotype of this condition?
Explanation:
A - The chromosomal defect in the Philadelphia chromosome is a translocation, in which parts of two chromosomes, 9 and 22, swap places. The result is that a fusion gene is created by juxtaposing the ABL1 gene on chromosome 9 (region q34) to a part of the BCR (breakpoint cluster region) gene on chromosome 22 (region q11). This is a reciprocal translocation, creating an elongated chromosome 9 (termed a derivative chromosome, or der 9), and a truncated chromosome 22 (the Philadelphia chromosome)

 

B- Cri du chat syndrome is due to a partial deletion of the short arm of chromosome number 5, also called "5p monosomy" or "partial monosomy."

 

C- Normal dystrophy gene: The dystrophin gene is located on the short arm (p) of chromosome X and is found on the band 21.1 Any abnormalities will result in Duchenne and Becker muscle dytrophy 

 

D- Normal beta-globin gene. the hemoglobin beta gene (HBB). This means that the HBB gene lies on the short arm (p) of chromosome 11 and is found at the band labeled 15.4.

 

E- t(14:21) Robertsonian Translocation: The long arm of chromosome 21 is attached to the long arm of another chromosome, often chromosome 14: Down syndrome.

Question: In a normal sinus rhythm ECG, what does the QT interval represent?
OptionA: The time taken for the ventricles to depolarise and then repolarise.
OptionB: The time taken for electrical activity to move between the atria and the ventricles.
OptionC: The time between depolarisation and repolarisation of the ventricles (i.e. contraction)
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

B -  P-R interval

C - S-T segment

D - QRS complex

E - T wave

 

P-waves
P-waves represent atrial depolarisation.
In sinus rhythm, there should be a P-wave preceding each QRS complex.

 

PR interval
The PR-interval is from the start of the P-wave to the start of the Q wave.
It represents the time taken for electrical activity to move between the atria and ventricles.

 

QRS complex
The QRS-complex represents depolarisation of the ventricles.
It is seen as three closely related waves on the ECG (Q,R and S wave).

 

ST segment
The ST-segment starts at the end of the S-wave and finishes at the start of the T-wave.
The ST segment is an isoelectric line that represents the time between depolarization and repolarization of the ventricles (i.e. contraction).

 

T-wave
The T-wave represents ventricular repolarisation.
It is seen as a small wave after the QRS complex.

 

RR-interval
The RR-interval starts at the peak of one R wave and ends at the peak of the next R wave.
It represents the time between two QRS complexes.

 

QT-interval
The QT-interval starts at the beginning of the QRS complex and finishes at the end of the T-wave.
It represents the time taken for the ventricles to depolarise and then repolarise.

 

 

https://geekymedics.com/understanding-an-ecg/

Question: Which of the following ligaments of the hip joint is intracapsular?
Explanation:
The ligaments of the hip joint act to increase stability. They can be divided into two groups – intracapsular and extracapsular:


Intracapsular
The only intracapsular ligament is the ligament of head of femur. It is a relatively small structure, which runs from the acetabular fossa to the fovea of the femur.

It encloses a branch of the obturator artery (artery to head of femur), a minor source of arterial supply to the hip joint.

Extracapsular

There are three main extracapsular ligaments, continuous with the outer surface of the hip joint capsule:

Iliofemoral ligament – spans between the anterior inferior iliac spine and the intertrochanteric line of the femur.
It has a ‘Y’ shaped appearance, and prevents hyperextension of the hip joint

Pubofemoral – spans between the superior pubic rami and the intertrochanteric line of the femur.
It has a triangular shape, and prevents excessive abduction and extension.

Ischiofemoral – spans between the body of the ischium and the greater trochanter of the femur.
It has a spiral orientation, and prevents excessive extension.

ACL is a ligament that supports the knee joint
Tags: Anatomy of Lower Limb, anatomy, Ligaments

Question:
For 23 years, Jim Becker funded tickets to watch the Green Bay Packers by donating blood. At the time, in America, people could be paid $15 a pint of their blood - over $100 adjusted for inflation. 

 

Little did he know, donating blood so regularly saved his life from a genetic liver disease. After 145 donations, he was diagnosed. 

 

      

 

Using your knowledge of genetic liver diseases, which disease did Jim Becker have?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. Haemochromatosis is an excess of iron deposits. Blood transfusions removed the excess iron and Jim Becker is outliving his father (who had the same condition) by over 40 years.

 

The only current treatment for haemochromatosis is regular blood transfusion. 

Haemochromatosis is mentioned in Dr Maleri Morgan's lecture on the liver in Case 3. The real story is found here.

Question:
Right axis deviation occurs when the overall direction of electrical activity in the heart is distorted to the right. This means that a strong positive signal is picked up by leads on the right side of the heart, so that the deflection in lead I becomes more negative, and the deflection in lead III is more positive.

 

What is the most common cause of RAD?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

 

Conduction defects are the main cause of left axis deviation (LAD). Although increased mass of the left ventricle could cause LAD this is not usually the cause.

 

Answer D is made up.

Question: Which of the following is true about Cytochrome P450?
OptionC: Cytochrome P450 plays a part in Phase II metabolism
OptionD: Cyrochrome P450 is mostly found in the pancreas
Explanation:
Cytochrome P450 is predominantly found within the liver and plays a role in activation of pro-drugs in Phase I metabolism. The enzyme works by oxidising the drug to an active form for pharmacological use. 

 

Remember: if the drug is oxidised by the enzyme, then the enzyme is reduced by the drug.

Question:
A patient comes into your surgery and tells you that their heartburn is getting worse so has therefore started taking over the counter rennies as well as the lanzoprazole you prescribed her. 

what do you tell her?
OptionA: to carry on taking both as it will take time for the dyspepsia to improve
OptionB: to stop taking the rennies as both can't be taken the same time
OptionC: to stop taking the rennies as the lanzoprozole will not work unless there is acid in the stomach to activate them
OptionD: that she is overweight and needs to diet
Explanation:
PPIs should not be taken the same time as over the counter antacids because;

 

antacids neutralise the acid in the stomach using magnesium carbonate and calcium carbonate. this means that the pH in the stomach is increased.

PPIs are prodrugs that need to be activated using the acid in the stomach. 

If taken together, there is no acid in the stomach to activate the PPIs and therefore there will not be any therapeutic affect. 

the antacids should help soothe the dyspepsia a bit but these are not good long term

Question:
A patient is admitted to A&E at UHW after being in a car accident. She has lost a significant amount of blood and hence there is a drop in blood pressure of her circulating blood. 

 

What changes, if any, would you expect to occur in the arterioles at the glomerulus?
Explanation:
GFR needs to be maintained.

When there is a drop in blood pressure of circulating blood, it's detected by the kidneys. In response the afferent arteriole dilates to increase volume of blood reaching the glomerulus to be filtered.  The efferent arteriole constricts in order to increase resistance to blood so it cannot leave the glomerus too quickly. This causes a back up of the blood increasing pressure in the glomerulus, and therefore will increase GFR to a normal level.

Question: Which of the following supplies general sensation to the skin over jaw, lower gum, lower teeth and tongue?
Which of the following  nerves are responsible for the sense of taste?

Jonathan is performing a Cranial Nerve Examination:

 

Jonathan asks the patient to follow his finger with his eyes (without moving his head) as he draws an imaginary H. He then uses penlight to shine light into his eyes to see whether his pupils constrict. He also asks him if he can open and close his upper eye lid:

 

Which Cranial Nerve is Jonathan examining?
Explanation: As the name suggests, the oculomotor nerve supplies the majority of the muscles controlling eye movements. Thus, damage to this nerve will result in the affected individual being unable to move his or her eye normally. In addition, the nerve also supplies the upper eyelid muscle (levator palpebrae superioris) and the muscles responsible for pupil constriction (sphincter pupillae) .

Question: Why do males tend to be taller and have more muscle mass than females?
OptionA:
• boys have a shorter period of pre-pubertal growth
  • boys experience a greater peak linear growth velocity during adolescence than girls
  • levels of circulating androgens are higher in males
OptionB:
• boys have a longer period of pre-pubertal growth 
  • boys experience a greater peak linear growth velocity during adolescence than girls 
  • levels of circulating androgens are higher in males
OptionC:
• boys have a longer period of pre-pubertal growth
  • boys experience a greater peak linear growth velocity during adolescence than girls
  • levels of circulating gonadotrophins are higher in males
OptionD:
• boys have a longer period of pre-pubertal growth
  • boys experience a lesser peak linear growth velocity during adolescence than girls
  • levels of circulating androgens are lower in males
OptionE:
• boys have a longer period of pre-pubertal growth
  • boys experience a greater peak linear growth velocity during adolescence than girls
  • levels of circulating growth hormone are higher in males
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. 

  • boys enter puberty later than girls, and so they have a longer period of pre-pubertal growth before their growth spurts start
  • boys experience a greater peak linear growth velocity during adolescence than girls
  • levels of circulating androgens are higher in males, and androgens have a direct anabolic effect on muscle

Question: Which of the following cranial nerves has purely motor function?
Explanation:
All the other are mixed nerves (autonomic, sensory and motor) apart from hypoglossal which is purely motor: tongue 

 

Treigeminal: 

The trigeminal nerve carries general somatic afferent fibers (GSA), which innervate the skin of the face via ophthalmic (V1), maxillary (V2) and mandibular (V3) divisions. The trigeminal nerve also carries special visceral efferent (SVE) axons, which innervate the muscles of mastication via the mandibular (V3) division.

 

Facial: 

The facial nerve carries axons of type GVE, general visceral efferent, which innervate the sublingual, submandibular, and lacrimal glands, also mucosa of nasal cavity.
Axons of type SVE, special visceral efferent, innervate muscles of facial expression, stapedius, the posterior belly of digastric, and the stylohyoid.
The axons of type SVA, special visceral afferent, provide taste to the anterior one-thirds of tongue via chorda tympani.
Finally, the facial nerve also carries axons of type GVA, general visceral afferent, which provide sensation to the soft palate and parts of the nasal cavity.

 

Glossopharyngeal nerve: Sense of taste to the posterior 2/3rd of tongue and It supplies parasympathetic fibres to the parotid gland via the otic ganglion.

 

Vagus nerve: The vagus nerve carries sensory and motor parasympathetic fibres to all the organs (except the adrenal glands), from the neck down to the second segment of the transverse colon. Also, tested by swallowing reflex.

Question:
Mr Jones is a heavy smoker, and has suffered from COPD for several years. He attends a check up with his respiratory specialist, who takes an X-ray to see how the disease is progressing.

 

Which of the following is an X-ray of COPD?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E.

 

A - Bronchiectasis

B - Normal

C - Pleural Effusion

D - Pulmonary Oedema

E - COPD

 

"Plain chest radiographs have a poor sensitivity to detect COPD and usually only show features suggestive of COPD in advanced disease. Possible findings include:

  • Flattened diaphragmatic contour due to hyperinflation as a consequence of the expiratory airflow limitation
  • Decreased peripheral bronchovascular markings and increased radiolucency of the lung, due to lung parenchyma destruction
  • Bullae (a bulla is defined as a rounded focal lucency > 1cm demarcated by a thin wall and is often associated with emphysematous changes in the rest of the lung)
  • Prominence of the hilar vessels if there is pulmonary hypertension"

Question:
82yr old Mrs McGonagall has been diagnosed with NVAF (non-valvular atrial fibrillation) related venous thromboembolism. You prescribe her Dabigatran.

 

What kind of drug is Dabigatran?
Explanation:
Tenecteplase- tPA (fibrinolytic-used when there is evidence of a thrombus causing tissue ischemia)

tPA binds to fibrin on the surface of the clot
Activates fibrin-bound plasminogen
Plasmin is cleaved from the plasminogen associated with the fibrin
Fibrin molecules are broken apart by the plasmin and the clot dissolves

 

Vasodilators 

Venous dilators reduce venous pressure, which reduces preload on the heart thereby decreasing cardiac output. This is useful in angina because it decreases the oxygen demand of the heart and thereby increases the oxygen supply/demand ratio. Oxygen demand is reduced because decreasing preload leads to a reduction in ventricular wall stress by decreasing the size of the heart.

 

WARFARIN - anti-coagulant

Used where there is evidence of increased risk of clotting events (from non-vascular trauma causes e.g. turbulent blood flow caused by AF)

 

CLOPIDOGREL - anti-platelet agent

Used where there is risk of vascular-trauma-induced platelet activation (e.g. post-MI) that may lead to intra-vascular clotting (thrombosis)

 

DOACs is the correct answer

Advantages of DOACs include predictable pharmacokinetics, few drug-drug interactions, and low monitoring requirements.

Warfarin use is complicated by a narrow therapeutic window, unpredictable dose response, numerous food and drug interactions, and requirements for frequent monitoring. so DOACs were developed.

 

sources:

Dr Coffey- case 4 lightbulb

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27293895

http://www.cvpharmacology.com/thrombolytic/thrombolytic

Question:
There are several different mechanisms that may be involved in the metabolic regulation of blood flow:

 

Reduction in the availability of which of the following will lead to vasodilation in coronary vessels?
Explanation:
Decreased tissue pO2 :

resulting from reduced oxygen supply or increased oxygen demand causes vasodilation. Hypoxia-induced vasodilation may be direct (inadequate O2 to sustain smooth muscle contraction) or indirect via the production of vasodilator metabolites.

NOTE: , however, that hypoxia induces vasoconstriction in the pulmonary circulation (i.e., hypoxic vasoconstriction)

 

Potassium ion is released by contracting cardiac and skeletal muscle. Small increases in extracellular K+ produces hyperpolarization of vascular smooth muscle and relaxation through stimulation of the electrogenic Na+/K+-ATPase pump and increasing membrane conductance to K+

 

Carbon dioxide formation increases during states of increased oxidative metabolism. It readily diffuses from parenchymal cells in which it is produced to the vascular smooth muscle of blood vessels where it causes vasodilation.

 

Hydrogen ion increases when CO2 increases or during states of increased anaerobic metabolism, which can produce metabolic acidosis. Like CO2, increased H+ (decreased pH) causes vasodilation, particularly in the cerebral circulation

 

Adenosine formation increases during hypoxia and increased oxygen consumption, especially if the latter is accompanied by inadequate oxygen delivery. - High adenosine = activates K+ channels and more NO. Adenosine produces vasodilation through increases in cGMP, through Nitric Oxide, which leads to inhibition of calcium entry into the cells as well as opening of potassium channels.

Question:
a young woman comes into your surgery looking quite anxious. she tells you that she thinks she may be pregnant although she's on the contraceptive pill. you ask her if she would do a pregnancy test for you, which comes back to be positive. she reacts well, as she is already aware that she may be pregnant. however she really wants to know how this happened. 

 

you ask her how she has been since you've last seen her and she replies with 'not great'. as you ask her to explain further, she seems to have been anxious and depressed. she admits after looking on the internet that she has started taking herbal remedies to help her depression.

 

the herbal remedies used was St John's Wort which contains hyperforin. this is known to have undesirable effects on the contraceptive pill.

 

what is the name of the effect and what does it do?
OptionA: Enzyme induction effect- the hyperforin (drug A), causes an decrease in the cytochrome p450 enzymes (CYP3A4) meaning that drug B (the contraceptive pill) is there in excess and therefore cannot be metabolised and is no longer effective.
OptionB: Enzyme inhibition effect- the hyperforin (drug A), causes a decrease in the cytochrome p450 enzymes (CYP3A4) meaning that drug B (the contraceptive pill) is metabolised quicker and therefore is no longer effective.
OptionC: pre-systemic inhibition - the hyperforin (drug A), causes drug B (the contraceptive pill) to be activated in the upper GI tract and therefore is excreted before it has given a therapeutic effect.
OptionD: enzyme induction effect- the hyperforin (drug A), causes an increase in the cytochrome p450 enzymes (CYP3A4) meaning that drug B (the contraceptive pill) is metabolised quicker and therefore is no longer effective.
OptionE: enzyme inhibition effect- the hyperforin (drug A), causes a decrease in the cytochrome p450 enzymes (CYP3A4) meaning that drug B (the contraceptive pill)  cannot be metabolised.

Question:
Sympathetic adrenergic stimulation act through β-adrenoceptors. Overall, the effect of β-agonists , adrenaline and noradrenaline in the heart are:

Increase contractility
(positive inotropy)
Increase relaxation rate
(positive lusitropy)
Increase heart rate
(positive chronotropy)
Increase conduction velocity
(positive dromotropy) 

 

With regards to positive lusitropy: The disinhibition of ____________ by cAMP dependent pathway leads to an increased in the rate of calcium uptake by the Sarcoplasmic reticulum, thus increased relaxation rate .
Explanation: Activation of the cAMP-dependent protein kinase from beta-adrenoceptors phosphorylates a protein (phospholamban) on the SR that normally inhibits calcium uptake. This disinhibition of phospholamban leads to an increased rate of calcium uptake by the SR. Therefore, beta-adrenergic stimulation  increases the rate of relaxation (i.e., positive lusitropy).

Question: An 88 year old woman with osteoporosis presents to A and E with an intracapsular fracture along the neck of her right femur. As a result of this fracture avascular necrosis of the head of the femur sets in. This is due to damage to which arteries?
OptionC: Retinacular arteries of the ascending branch of the medial/lateral circumflex.
OptionD: Retinacular arteries of the descending branch of the medial/lateral circumflex.
Explanation:
Although the acetabular artery does supply the head of the femur, it would not be damaged in an intracapsular fracture. 

The femoral artery branches off from the external iliac with no further supplies to the head of the femur.

The Retinacular arteries lie along the neck of the femur and supply its head, they might be damaged in such a fracture. They are supplied by the ascending branches of the medial and lateral circumflex arteries.

The profunda femoris supplies the lateral and medial circumflex, however it is unlikely to be damaged.
Tags: Anatomy of Lower Limb, Bone, Bone Health, Bones, Case 1

Question:
Respiratory failure occurs when pulmonary gas exchange is insufficient, which causes hypoxaemia (and sometimes hypercarbia). Hypoxaemia is the lack of oxygen in arterial blood. It is defined as such when the partial pressure of oxygen in the arterial blood is below a certain level.

 

Which of the following arterial PaO2 levels would be defined as hypoxaemic?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

Hypoxaemia is defined as a partial pressure of oxygen in the arterial blood of below 8kPa (60mmHg). Normal PaO2 is 11 - 13 kPa.

 

Hypercarbia is when there is too much carbon dioxide in arterial blood. It is defined as a partial pressure of CO2 of over 7kPa (55mmHg). Normal 4 - 6kPa

 

(Source: Respiratory Failure and Blood Gases Lecture - Case 5)

Question:
Lucy is a 12 year old girl who has kyphoscoliosis (a twisted spine). This sometimes causes an inability to overcome resistance to ventilation, due to the chest wall deformity, causing Type 2 respiratory failure.

 

Which of the following statements does NOT describe an aspect of Type 2 respiratory failure?
OptionA: It only affects part of the lung
OptionD: Causes include obesity, drug overdose, severe asthma and motor neurone disease.
Explanation:
The correct answer is A which refers to Type 1 Respiratory Failure.

 

Type 1 Respiratory Failure

Type 1 respiratory failure is caused by poor oxygenation.
There is damage to part of the lung, but the remaining good lung is able to excrete CO2.
Less lung tissue is needed for CO2 excretion than oxygenation.
This presents as hypoxaemia, without hypercarbia.

 

Type 2 Respiratory Failure

Type 2 respiratory failure is ventilatory failure, and so causes both hypoxaemia and hypercarbia.
It affects the lung as a whole, so there is insufficient excretion of CO2, causing accumulation of CO2.
This can be caused by hypoventilation, which can be caused by several things:

 

  • The inability to overcome resistance to ventilation, due to chest wall deformity from obesity, or kyphoscoliosis (twisted spine).
  • Failure of drive from the respiratory centres in the brainstem, e.g. due to drug overdose, which reduces rate and depth of breathing.
  • Pump failure, due to respiratory muscle weakness, e.g. motor neurone disease, muscular dystrophy, reduces depth of breathing.

Type 2 respiratory failure can also be caused by severe chronic lung disease (e.g. emphysema or severe asthma), which increases airway resistance.

Question:
6 year old Jimmy has managed to get hold of a pack of matches and, ignoring everything the fireman told  him in his fire-safety lesson at school, decides to light one. As a budding pyromaniac he sets fire to his favourite toy - ironically a wooden fire-engine - and manages to burn his hand in the process.

 

Which afferent nerve fibre responds to heat to produce the initial "sharp" pain sensation?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

There are three primary types of afferent nerve fibres.
A-delta fibres (fast, myelinated) – respond to heat and pressure (1st ‘sharp’ pain sensation)
C fibres (slow, unmyelinated) – polymodal, respond to thermal, mechanical & chemical stimuli (2nd ‘throbbing’ or ‘burning’ pain sensation)
A-Beta fibres respond to non-noxious stimuli; detect light touch, vibrations

 

Although it is clear from the explanation that C-fibres also respond to burning, they are not responsible for the initial sharp pain, but are responsible for the slow burning pain that would come after.
Tags: Nervous system, Nociception, Case 1, Physiology of Pain

Question: Which of these is NOT a stage of bone formation or remodelling?
OptionD: Osteocytes assist in the production of osteoid
Explanation:
Bone formation

Bone is formed in 2 stages:

1. Osteoblast cells deposit osteoid

2. Osteoid is mineralised (apatite is incorporated into bone), ~10 days between deposit and mineralisation

 

Bone remodelling

1. Osteoclastic resorption

2. Osteoblast deposits new bone

Question: Whilst doing a bouncy castle 5k fun run, you somehow manage to fall off one of the inflatable fun slides. This results in a broken leg and a (relatively) speedy trip to the Heath. As your bone begins to heal afterwards, calcium ends up being deposited in the cartilage. Roughly when does this occur after the initial break?
Explanation:
Stage 4 of natural bone healing (Callus):

Islands of cartilage appear (especially near the periosteum). The fracture ends are now united by a sleeve of vascularised granulation tissue and cartilage = provisional callus. By the end of week 1, calcium is deposited in the cartilage, and osteoblasts start to produce a seam of osteoid across the fracture. Most of the new bone formation so far has been subperiosteal, but now endochondral ossification is established and adds to the new bone. The callus calcifies and the ends unite with bony callus

Question: What is Kyphosis (type of spinal disorder?)
OptionA: A form of spinal arthritis, chiefly affecting young males
OptionD: A painful condition of the spine resulting from the degeneration of the intervertebral discs

Question: Aperture at Level T10 of diaphragm transmits the esophagus along with which other nerve/nerves?
OptionB: anterior and posterior trunks of the vagus nerves
Explanation:
Vena caval hiatus (vena caval foramen)
Lies in the central tendon of the diaphragm at the level of T8 and transmits the IVC and occasionally the phrenic nerve.
2. Esophageal hiatus
Lies in the muscular part of the diaphragm (right crus) at the level of T10 and transmits the esophagus and anterior and posterior trunks of the vagus nerves.
3. Aortic hiatus
Lies behind or between two crura at the level of T12 and transmits the aorta, thoracic duct, azygos vein, an occasionally greater splanchnic nerve.

Question: Which of the following Respiratory exchange ratios indicate that fat is the predominant fuel used?
Explanation:
An RER of 0.70 indicates that fat is the predominant fuel source, RER of 0.85 suggests a mix of fat and carbohydrates, and a value of 1.00 or above is indicative of carbohydrate being the predominant fuel source

 

At a high intensity the main source of energy is carbohydrate and at a low intensity, fat is the predominate source. As there is a limit to the amount of carbohydrate that can be stored in the muscles, high intensity work can only be sustained for short periods. We have large stores of fat so low intensity work can be maintained for long periods.

 

A value greater than 1.0 indicates anaerobic respiration due to more CO 2 being produced than O 2 consumed.

Which of the following is an INCORRECT statement regarding the roles of cytokines in the immune response?
OptionB: A cell not directly affected can be stimulated by a cytokine to produce more
OptionD: Range of molecules specific to immune responses
OptionE: Molecule used to communicate/illicit a response between paracrine and endocrine cells
Explanation:
Cytokine

• Hormones; molecule used to communicate/illicit a reaction between (paracrine) and on (autocrine) cells • Range of molecules specific to immune responses

• Transported by diffusion and so all cells can receive them (even those not involved in immune response) • Neurotransmitters are hormones specific to neuronal communication

• Any cells can release a cytokine

• If any cell is affected by bacteria/virus/trauma they must communicate this

• Other cells must aid in overcoming this event/relay communication

• Therefore, a cell not directly affected can be stimulated by a cytokine to produce more cytokines. This is an amplification process

Question: Which of the following best describes Mode of action of Salbutamol?
Explanation:
SALBUTAMOL short-duration bronchodilator for acute episodes (attacks) / exacerbation of asthma or COPD

IPRATROPIUM short-duration bronchodilator for acute episodes (attacks) / exacerbations of asthma or COPD

FLUTICASONE potent anti-inflammatory steroid drug may be used in conjunction with above or below drugs

SALMETEROL long-duration bronchodilator for moderate to severe asthma management

TIOTROPIUM long-duration bronchodilator for COPD management

 

SALBUTAMOL & SALMETEROL: selective beta-2 adrenoceptor agonists.
(Activation of beta-2 GPCR in bronchial tissue causes cAMP-mediated bronchial smooth muscle cell relaxation which dilates the bronchi and facilitates air-flow)

FLUTICASONE: steroid forms complex with glucocorticoid receptor which then acts as transcriptional regulator to (strongly) reduce inflammation
(Glucocorticoids transcriptionally UP-regulate anti-inflammatory proteins and DOWN-regulate inflammatory mediators)

IPRATROPIUM & TIOTROPIUM: muscarinic (mostly M3) acetylcholine receptor antagonists
(Blockade of M3 ACh receptors on bronchial smooth muscle cells leads to reduced cGMP and smooth muscle cell relaxation with subsequent dilation of the bronchi)

Question: Which of the following is False about pulmonary surfactant?
OptionB: Causes a greater increase in the compliance of small alveoli
OptionC: Causes a greater reduction in the surface tension of big alveoli
OptionD: Infant respiratory distress syndrome (IRDS) is caused by lack of surfactant, commonly suffered by premature babies born before 28–32 weeks of gestation
OptionE: Main lipid component of surfactant is dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine (DPPC)
Explanation:
Surfactant increases the compliance AND reduces the surface tension of smaller alveoli more than the bigger alveoli because, as the alveoli increase in size, the surfactant becomes more spread out over the surface of the liquid, so its effects are reduced.

Surfactants reduce surface tension more readily when the alveoli is smaller because surfactants are more concentrated. 

 

Without surfactant there is a high surface tension in the alveoli because of air-liquid interface in the alveoli (alveoli are lined with a monomolecular layer of liquid because of high permeability). 

This is reduced by the pulmonary surfactant dipalmitoyl phosphatidylcholine (DPPC) secreted by lung type 2 alveolar cells

Question:
Gina is a 20 year old woman who is visiting the sexual health clinic with what she suspects is an STI. A quick history reveals that Gina has a relatively new boyfriend and that they have never used condoms together. She says that she has pain when she urinates and has found pale white discharge which is sometimes spotted with blood in her knickers. However her boyfriend doesn't seem to have any symptoms.

 

What STI does Gina have?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E - Chlamydia.

 

Chlamydia is the most common STI – forming 46% of new cases in England in 2015, and the ‘peak age’ at which chlamydia is most common is 20. Reported incidence is higher in females than males, potentially due to more screening in women.

 

It is caused by chlamydia trachomatis, an obligate intracellular, motile, gram negative bacteria.

 

Chlamydia is often ‘silent’ or asymptomatic (causes no symptoms), which is a problem as it can be passed on unknowingly.

 

However chlamydia does have signs and symptoms in some people.
Males: proctitis and epididymitis (inflammation of the prostate and testicles) - pain and swelling in the testicles, discharge from the penis.
Females: cervicitis, white/yellow discharge from the vagina, pain in the tummy, bleeding during or after sex, and bleeding between periods.
Both genders: urethritis, pain when urinating, discharge from the rectum 

Chlamydia can also affect newborns, and may cause pneumonia and conjunctivitis.

 

Of the other options the potentially confusing choices were Gonorrhoea and Trichomoniasis, which both also cause vaginal discharge and painful urination. However in these cases the discharge would be different - purulent and green/yellow in Gonorrhoea and green, frothy and fishy-smelling in Trichomoniasis.

Question: Which of the following forms the medial border of the Hasselbach's triangle?

A young mother comes into your practice regarding her 2 week year old son. The skin around his eyes is inflamed and the covered in sores indicative of conjunctivitis. You suspect that this is a vertically transmitted infection. After taking a history from the mother, she explains that 5 years ago she tested positive for an STI. She has subsequently forgotten the name of the infection, but she describes having had painful lesions on her external genitalia, flu like symptoms and slight dysuria. Which is the most LIKELY causative agent?
Explanation:
The symptoms the mother described were indicative of the genital Herpes. There are two types of Herpes virus, HSV1 and HSV2. Generally, HSV1 is associated with symptoms above the waste, whereas HSV2 is associated with symptoms below. Although there is cross over, I did specify the most 'likely' virus. Since the baby had to pass through vagina during birth, it is most likely to be HSV2. 

 

Once infected, a person can have a dormant form of the virus reside in either the trigeminal ganglia or their sacral ganglia. This virus can flare up after various triggers such as viral infection, stress etc. 

 

Other STIs can cause conjunctivitis due to vertical transmission. Before delivery, the mother should be cleared from the infectious agent with antibiotics (if bacterial) or a Caesarean section maybe required to avoid transmission.

Gemeprost is also used to terminate pregnancies. It is a methyl ester analogue of PGE1 and is used with mifepristone. It decreases obstetric bleeding by causing vasoconstriction

Question:
Km is the Michaelis equilibrium constant. It represents the substrate concentration when the reaction proceeds at half of the maximum velocity. Km is a measure of the affinity of the enzyme to the substrate.

 

What does a high Km value mean in terms of the affinity of the enzyme to the substrate?
OptionA: The enzyme has a high affinity for the substrate.
OptionB: The enzyme has a low affinity for the substrate.
OptionC: The enzyme has no affinity for the substrate.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

A lower Km value means that the enzyme has a higher affinity for the substrate, and so binds to it more tightly.
A higher Km value means that the enzyme has a lower affinity for the substrate, and so binds to it less tightly.

Question: If a person has referred pain in the centre of their upper back, what organ is most likely to be causing it?
Explanation:
The liver, gall bladder and spleen normally all give referred pain to the region of skin roughly over the area of the organ.

The diaphragm often causes referred pain over the right shoulder into the back.

Question:
A right sided psoas sign is elicited by performing the psoas test by passively extending the thigh of a patient lying on his side with knees extended, or asking the patient to actively flex his thigh at the hip. If abdominal pain results, it is a "positive psoas sign". The pain results because the psoas borders the peritoneal cavity, so stretching (by hyperextension at the hip) or contraction (by flexion of the hip) of the muscles causes friction against nearby inflamed tissues.

 

In which of the following conditions are you most likely to see a positive right psoas sign?
Explanation: The right iliopsoas muscle lies under the appendix when the patient is supine, so a positive psoas sign on the right may suggest appendicitis.

Question: Philadelphia chromosome is an example of reciprocal translocation. Which chromosomes are involved?

Reciprocal translocation is the exchange of material between non-homologue chromosomes.

Question: The muscles of the anterior forearm are flexors, and primarily innervated by the median nerve. Which of these muscles is not innervated by the median nerve?
Explanation:
A-D are from the first layer of muscles, whilst E is from the second layer. D is correct and is innervated by the ulnar nerve. 

 

The medial part of flexor digitorum profundus is also innervated by the ulnar nerve. The rest of the muscles in the anterior forearm are innervated by the median nerve (note that flexor pollicis longus and pronator quadratus are innervated by the anterior interosseous nerve; a branch of the median nerve).

Question: What is the Arterial supply of Large Intestine?
Explanation:
Cecum is part of midgut (Superior Mesenteric)

Ascending colon and proximal 2/3 of the transverse colon – derived from the midgut (Superior Mesenteric)

Question:
The area of the colon supplied by the left colic artery (branch of inferior mesenteric artery) overlaps with the middle colic artery (a branch of the superior mesenteric artery), forming the__________________

 

This artery maintains the blood supply in the colon even when one of the great vessels is occluded:

Roots: C6 – T1. (Also contains fibres from C5 in some individuals).

Motor Functions: Innervates most of the flexor muscles in the forearm, the thenar muscles, and the two lateral lumbricals that move the index and middle fingers.

Sensory Functions: Gives off the palmar cutaneous branch, which innervates the lateral part of the palm, and the digital cutaneous branch, which innervates the lateral three and a half fingers on the anterior (palmar) surface of the hand.

 

 

To which of the following branches of the brachial plexus does the above description belong to?
Explanation:
Musculocutaneous Nerve

 

Roots: C5, C6, C7.

Motor Functions: Innervates the brachialis, biceps brachii and coracobrachialis muscles.

Sensory Functions: Gives off the lateral cutaneous branch of the forearm, which innervates the lateral half of the anterior forearm, and a small lateral portion of the posterior forearm.

 

Axillary Nerve

 

Roots: C5 and C6.

Motor Functions: Innervates the teres minor and deltoid muscles.

Sensory Functions: Gives off the superior lateral cutaneous nerve of arm, which innervates the inferior region of the deltoid (“regimental badge area”)

 

Radial Nerve

 

Roots: C5-C8 and T1.

Motor Functions: Innervates the triceps brachii, and the extensor muscles in the posterior compartment of the forearm.

Sensory Functions: Innervates the posterior aspect of the arm and forearm, and the posterior, lateral aspect of the hand

 

Ulnar Nerve

 

Roots: C8 and T1.

Motor Functions: Innervates the muscles of the hand (apart from the thenar muscles and two lateral lumbricals), flexor carpi ulnaris and medial half of flexor digitorum profundus.

Sensory Functions: Innervates the anterior and posterior surfaces of the medial one and half fingers, and associated palm area.

 

Source: Teach Me Anatomy: Brachial Plexus

Question: What is the common attachment of rotator cuff muscles?
Explanation:
Supraspinatus

Attachments: Originates from the supraspinous fossa of the scapula, attaches to the greater tubercle of the humerus.

Infraspinatus

Attachments: Originates from the infraspinous fossa of the scapula, attaches to the greater tubercle of the humerus.

Subscapularis

Attachments: Originates from the subscapular fossa, on the costal surface of the scapula. It attaches to the lesser tubercle of the humerus.

Teres Minor
Attachments: Originates from the posterior surface of the scapula, adjacent to its lateral border. It attaches to the greater tubercle of the humerus.

 

Radial Nerve passes  in the radial groove of humerus and axillary nerve wraps around the surgical neck of the humerus

Question: In parasympathetic neurones which of the following is correct?

Question: Which of the following is an adverse effect of using bisphosphonates as secondary prevention in osteoporosis?
Explanation:
Bisphosphonates (e.g. alendronate) are given to post menopausal women with a fracture history.

They bind to calcium and mimic pyrophosphate

This result in bone resorption inhibition, and apoptosis of osteoclasts.

Side effects include jaw osteonecrosis and bisphosphonate fractures.

 

MI is a risk factor in the use of Strontium, which increases bone deposition and decreases resorption.

 

B and D are made up.

 

Other secondary prevention measures include 

- SERMS (e.g. raloxifine) - a selective oestrogen receptor modulator

- PTH

- Calcium and Vit D

- HRT as oestrogen increases osteoblast:osteoclast ratio by inhibiting RANKL release and osteoclast maturation
Tags: Bone, Bone Health, Bone Remodelling, Bones

Question: Which hormone responds to a decrease in plasma calcium?
Explanation:
PTH increases in response to a decrease in plasma calcium which - 

 

Increases Ca2+ reabsorption by the kidneys and bone.

Question:
Daisy is a 5 year old girl who has recently been suffering with intermittent attacks of wheezing and shortness of breath, especially when she is playing outside. Her mother takes her to the GP, who diagnoses her with acute asthma. The GP prescribes her a bronchodilator which is to be inhaled.

 

Which bronchodilator is the GP most likely to prescribe?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

 

Salbutamol is a short duration B2-adrenoreceptor antagonist bronchodilator and Salmeterol is a long duration B2-adrenoreceptor antagonist. These work by activating B2-adrenoreceptors, which inactivate myosin light chain kinase (MLCK) and decrease the intracellular calcium levels in smooth muscle cells, which means that cross bridges cannot form between myosin and actin and therefore muscle contraction cannot take place.

 

Tiotropium is a long-duration muscarinic receptor antagonist and Ipratroprium is a short action muscarinic receptor antagonist. These work by preventing the binding of Acetylcholine to muscarinic receptors (primarily the M3 receptor) which prevents the increase of intracellular cGMP in smooth muscle which prevents muscle contraction.

 

Both types of bronchodilator are used to treat asthma and COPD, however B2-adrenoreceptor agonists are mainly for asthma, and muscarinic receptor antagonists are mainly for COPD.

 

Fluticasone is not a bronchodilator at all, but is a glucocorticoid steroid which reduces inflammation by the up-regulation of anti-inflammatory proteins, and the down-regulation of anti-inflammatory mediators (e.g. TH2 cytokines). These are often used with bronchodilators.

 

Because Daisy is only suffering from intermittent attacks of asthma she needs a short duration bronchodilator, and as B2-adrenoreceptors agonists are more often used for asthma this is the best choice.

Question: How is pulmonary blood pressure measured?
OptionA: It is taken as a percentage of the systemic blood pressure.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

Systemic blood pressure can be easily and non-invasively measured using a sphygmomanometer.


In comparison, pulmonary pressure is measured using right heart catheterisation, using a swan ganz catheter. This is much more invasive.It involves a thin tube which has a ‘balloon’ or pressure transducer on the end. This is inserted into the internal jugular or femoral vein, and advanced into the pulmonary artery via the right side of the heart. Here the mean pulmonary artery pressure can be measured in situ.

Question:
Isolated systolic hypertension, an elevation in systolic but not diastolic pressure, is the most prevalent type of hypertension in those aged 50 or over.

The increase in blood pressure with age is mostly associated with structural changes in the arteries and especially with large artery stiffness.

It is known from various studies that rising blood pressure is associated with increased cardiovascular risk. 

 

 

In the elderly, the most powerful predictor of risk is _____________due to decreased diastolic and increased systolic blood pressure
Explanation:
With ageing there is reduction is Cardiac Output

There is reduction in the ejection fraction because Ventricles are not as efficient in contracting

There is reduction in the sympathetic response because the autonomic nervous system degradation

There is increase in pulse pressure because there is increase in End systolic pressure and reduction in end diastolic pressure, therefore, the difference between them increases (Pulse pressure is the difference between the systolic and diastolic pressure readings.)

 

Really good website that shows how to take and calculate Pulse Pressure

 

We learnt about pulse pressure in PCS: Modifying Heart Rate 

 

Extra:

The changes in the cardiovascular system associated with aging are a decrease in elasticity and an increase in stiffness of the arterial system. This results in increased afterload on the left ventricle, an increase in systolic blood pressure, and left ventricular hypertrophy, as well as other changes in the left ventricular wall that prolong relaxation of the left ventricle in diastole. There is a dropout of atrial pacemaker cells resulting in a decrease in intrinsic heart rate. With fibrosis of the cardiac skeleton there is calcification at the base of the aortic valve and damage to the His bundle as it perforates the right fibrous trigone. Finally there is decreased responsiveness to beta adrenergic receptor stimulation, a decreased reactivity to baroreceptors and chemoreceptors, and an increase in circulating catecholamines. These changes set the stage for isolated systolic hypertension, diastolic dysfunction and heart failure, atrioventricular conduction defects, and aortic valve calcification, all diseases seen in the elderly.

Question: You're walking past your favourite burrito restaurant when you realise you've started dribbling a little as you start dreaming about burritos. You start to think about the increase in parasympathetic activity, which increases the secretion rate of saliva from the salivary glands. Which of the following statements is true about an increased rate at which it is secreted and flows along the salivary ducts?
OptionA: There is more time for reabsorption of electrolytes
OptionB: Increase in Na+, HCO3-, and Cl- content
OptionD: Saliva becomes further away from being iso-osmotic
OptionE: No effect on increased rate of saliva secretion and flow
Explanation: The final electrolyte content of saliva depends upon the rate at which it is secreted and flows along the salivary ducts. As flow rate increases, there is less time for the reabsorption of electrolytes and the salivary content of sodium, bicarbonate and chloride increases, while there is a small drop in the potassium content. Note that saliva becomes nearer iso-osmotic

During an injury there is oedema at the site. This is because there is increases in vascular permeability which allows the White Blood cells to exit the blood vessel as exudates.

Explanation:

CAMs: Transmigration

Important:

- TNF alpha and IL-1

Question: Which of these series of statements best describes the events that take place during ovulation?
OptionA:
By the end of the preovulatory stage, the volume of follicular fluid has increased significantly, and the oocyte remains attached to the outer rim of granulosa cells by only a thin stalk. 


Oestrogen causes the cells of the stalk to dissociate, and the follicle ruptures.

 
At ovulation, the follicular fluid flows out onto the surface of the ovary, carrying the secondary oocyte and a few surrounding cells.


The egg mass is then swept up into the fallopian tube by currents set up by the movements of fimbriae on the ostium.
OptionB:
By the end of the preovulatory stage, the volume of follicular fluid has increased significantly, and the oocyte remains attached to the outer rim of granulosa cells by only a thin stalk. 


LH and FSH cause the cells of the stalk to dissociate, and the follicle ruptures. 


At ovulation, the follicular fluid flows into the infundibulum of the fallopian tube, carrying the secondary oocyte and a few surrounding cells. 


The egg mass is then swept up into the fallopian tube by currents set up by the movements of fimbriae on the ostium.
OptionC:
By the end of the preovulatory stage, the volume of follicular fluid has increased significantly, and the oocyte remains attached to the outer rim of granulosa cells by only a thin stalk. 

Progesterone and oestrogen cause the cells of the stalk to dissociate, and the follicle ruptures. 

At ovulation, the follicular fluid flows out onto the surface of the ovary, carrying the secondary oocyte and a few surrounding cells. 

The egg mass is then swept up into the fallopian tube by currents set up by the movements of fimbriae on the ostium.
OptionD:
By the end of the preovulatory stage, the volume of follicular fluid has increased significantly, and the oocyte remains attached to the outer rim of granulosa cells by only a thin stalk. 


LH and FSH cause the cells of the stalk to dissociate, and the follicle ruptures. 


At ovulation, the follicular fluid flows out onto the surface of the ovary, carrying the secondary oocyte and a few surrounding cells. 


The egg mass is then swept up into the fallopian tube by currents set up by the movements of fimbriae on the ostium.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

This question was designed to highlight the hormonal control of ovulation (contributed to by FSH and especially LH) and the fact that when the oocyte is ovulated, it is not released directly into the uterine tube, but instead onto the surface of the ovary, from where the fimbriae act to move it along the uterine tubes.
Tags: Ovarian Cycle, Case 2, Reproductive hormones, Reproductive system, menstrual cycle

Question: Which of these statements is true?
OptionA: Androgens such as testosterone are released by the anterior pituitary gland, and gonadotrophins such as FSH and LH are released by the testes.
OptionB: Androgens such as FSH and LH are released by the testes, and gonadotrophins such as testosterone are released by the anterior pituitary gland.
OptionC: Androgens such as testosterone are released by the testes, and gonadotrophins such as FSH and LH are released by the posterior pituitary gland.
OptionD: Androgens such as testosterone are released by the testes, and gonadotrophins such as FSH and LH are released by the anterior pituitary gland.
OptionE: Androgens such as testosterone are released by the adrenal gland, and gonadotrophins such as FSH and LH are released by the anterior pituitary gland.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D: androgens such as testosterone are released by the testes, and gonadotrophins such as FSH and LH are released by the anterior pituitary gland.

 

While E is partially correct, as the adrenal gland does secrete some weak androgens e.g. androstenedione and DHEA, the example given was testosterone and so the best answer was D.
Tags: Case 2, Hormones, Puberty, Reproductive hormones, Reproductive system

Question: 25 year old Mr X arrives at the GUM clinic. He is worried about a painless lesion on his penis that he noticed two days previously. A venereal disease research laboratory test (VDRL) is carried out. In this test, extract of an ox's heart is used as it reacts with an antibody produced by a patient with a certain sexually transmitted infection. The test was positive. What is the likely diagnosis and what microorganism is likely to have caused it?
Explanation:
A painless lesion on the tip or shaft of a penis is characteristic of syphilis. It is called a chancre. It typically occurs 3 weeks after infection by the traponema pallidum bacterium. A VDRL test will be positive in a patient with syphilis as ox heart extract is mistaken by antibodies produced in response to traponema pallidum infection as the traponema pallidum infection. 

 

Chlamydia is caused by chlamydia tracomatis.

Gonorrhoea is cause by neisseria gonorrhoeae.

Clostrium difficile is a species of bacteria that causes diarrhoea. It is unrelated to gonorrhoea.

OptionC: Histamines act on H1 receptors to inhibit release of PYY

Gastrin also acts on the H2 receptors of parietal cells to cause acid secretion.

Question:
An elderly lady with bronchiectasis comes to see you. She has noticed that she has green sputum and says she gets infections much more often than she used to.

     

 

Why do bronchiectasis patients get regular infections?
OptionA: Mucus is trapped in outpouchings and bacteria can grow
OptionB: Innate immune system is overwhelmed by the bacterium Staphylococcus bronchiecta
OptionC: Mucus is held in the lung due to gravity
OptionD: Constant coughing causes tears in the bronchial lining, leading to infection
OptionE: Not enough mucus is produced to protect against infection
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. Bronchiectasis is permanent widening of the bronchioles and bronchi. This widening can cause small pockets to form called 'outpouchings'. Once mucus becomes trapped in an outpouching, it is difficult to remove.

 

Any pathogens that are caught in this outpouching are equally hard to remove, resulting in infection. In addition to the outpouchings, the mucociliary escalator is faulty, so mucus is harder to remove throughout the lung. 


Answer C probably has some truth in it too, but A is the Single Best Answer.

Question:
Mrs Johnson is a worried mother who has rushed into A&E with her 7 year old child Toby, who is unconscious. She explains to the doctor that Toby has had flu-like symptoms for the past 2 weeks, and that his health has got worse in the last few days with a developing fever, vomiting and hallucinations. Further questioning reveals that Mrs Johnson has been giving her son painkillers for his symptoms, from the family's 'painkiller tub' - a box of mixed, unlabelled painkillers.

 

What is the most likely diagnosis for Toby?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A - Reye's syndrome.

 

Reye's syndrome is a condition where children develop liver disease, which leads to encephalopathy (brain dysfunction). It is often caused by aspirin use in children, especially following viral illness such as influenza or chicken pox.

 

 

In Toby's case, I believe that Reye's syndrome is the most likely diagnosis because he has both fever as well as hallucinations/unconsciousness which suggests brain damage. Moreover, it is likely that he has been exposed to aspirin from the mysterious 'painkiller box'.

Question: Which of the following is a DNA virus?
Explanation: Hep A, C, D and E are all RNA viruses, only hep B is an RNA virus

Question: Approximately 75% of lymph from the breast drains into the _______________ so can be biopsied if breast cancer is suspected.
Explanation:
Axilla:

 

Lymph Node Biopsy

Approximately 75% of lymph from the breast drains into the axilla lymph nodes, so can be biopsied if breast cancer is suspected. If breast cancer is confirmed, the axillary nodes may need to be removed to prevent the cancer spreading. This is known as axillary clearance. During this procedure, the long thoracic nerve may become damaged, resulting in winged scapula.

 

Anatomical Snuffbox:

Carpal scaphoid fractures occur fairly frequently. The most commonly described mechanism of injury is a fall on an extended wrist, which creates an axial as well as extension force to the scaphoid bone. There is tenderness on palapting in the anatomical snuffbox. It is a medical emergency because this fracture can lead to avascular necrosis of the proximal part of the bone.

 

Cubital fossa:

  • The cubital fossa is an area of transition between the anatomical arm and the forearm. It is located as a depression on the anterior surface of the elbow joint. The contents are: brachial artery, biceps tendon, radial nerve and median nerve. 
  • The brachial pulse can be felt by palpating immediately medial to the biceps tendon in the cubital fossa. When measuring blood pressure, this is also the location in which the stethoscope must be placed, to hear the korotkoff sounds. 
  • The median cubital vein is located superficially within the roof of the cubital fossa. It connects the basilic and cephalic veins, and can be accessed easily – this makes it a common site for venepuncture.

 

Carpal Tunnel:

  • The carpal tunnel is a narrow passageway found on the anterior portion of the wrist. It serves as the entrance to the palm for several tendons and the median nerve. Other contents of the carpal tunnel are the tendons of flexor pollicis longus, flexor digitorum profundus and flexor digitorum superficialis.  
  • Compression of the median nerve within the carpal tunnel can cause carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS). It is the most common mononeuropathy and can be caused by thickened ligaments and tendon sheaths. Its aetiology is, however, most often idiopathic. If left untreated, CTS can cause weakness and atrophy of the thenar muscles.

 

Popliteal fossa: 

 

  • The popliteal fossa is a diamond shaped area found on the posterior side of the knee. It is the main path in which structures move from the thigh to the leg. The contents include: Popliteal artery, Popliteal vein, Tibial nerve and Common fibular nerve. 
  • An aneurysm is a dilation of an artery, which is greater than 50% of the normal diameter. The popliteal fascia (the roof of the popliteal fossa) is tough and non-extensible, and so an aneurysm of the popliteal artery has consequences for the other contents of the popliteal fossa.
  • The tibial nerve is particularly susceptible to compression from the popliteal artery.
Tags: Anatomy, Axilla, Cubital Fossa, Popliteal Fossa

Question: Which of these cytokines does not promote inflammation?
Explanation:
IL-10 is the correct answer: it is an anti-inflammatory cytokine. 

 

IL-6 stimulates the differentiation of monocytes into macrophages, due to the fact it is an analogue of macrophage-colony stimulating factor (M-CSF), and exaggerates the immune response.

 

TNF-alpha has a number of  pro-inflammatory effects:

  • increases phagocytosis by macrophages
  • increases the production of inflammatory cytokines
  • increases neutrophil activity
  • increases adhesion on endothelial cells for immune cell chemotaxis
  • increases cell retraction

HIF (released in hypoxic states to prevent necrosis) stimulates the chemotaxis of monocytes, and the proliferation of endothelial cells and fibroblasts. 

 

IL-8 is responsible for chemotaxis of neutrophils (it is neutrophil-specific).

Question: Which spinal pathway is also known as 'the pyramidal tract', due to the decussation of fibres occurring at structures known as the pyramids?
Explanation:
The corticospinal tract is also known as the pyramidal tract because most fibres decussate at the pyramids, in the medulla. These fibres are responsible for motor control of limb muscles. The other fibres, responsible for motor control of axial muscles, remain on the same side of the brainstem until they decussate in the anterior white commissure in the spinal cord. 

 

In the dorsal column pathway, decussation also occurs in the medulla, but not at the pyramids. 

 

The spinothalamic (which ascends to the thalamus) and spinoreticular (which ascends to the reticular formation in the brainstem) tracts decussate in the spinal cord. 

 

Lissauer's tract is the ascent or descent 1 or 2 spinal levels by the sensory neurones in the spinothalamic tract, before the fibres decussate.
Tags: Somatic Nervous System, Nerves, Nervous system, Neurology, Case 1

Question: What stimulates a sudden spike in LH levels in the follicular phase of the menstrual cycle?
Explanation:
Initially, when oestrogen levels are low, oestrogen inhibits the production of LH and FSH from the anterior pituitary gland, by a negative feedback system. However, more oestrogen is secreted from the Graafian follicle and when this oestrogen reaches a threshold level, the anterior pituitary is stimulated to secrete lots of LH and FSH, causing a sudden spike. 

 

Progesterone levels are still low as the corpus luteum has not been formed, and levels of progesterone don't affect this sudden LH surge.

Question: The macula densa is part of the juxtaglomerular apparatus of the kidney. Where in the kidney is it found?
OptionB: Ascending limb of the loop of Henle
OptionC: Descending limb of the loop of Henle
Explanation: The macula densa is found in the distal convoluted tubule of the nephron. It is responsible for controlling blood pressure and the concentration of sodium ions in the blood.

Question: How does histamine stimulate secretion of HCl in the stomach?
OptionA: Histamine activates the Gs subunit, which stimulates adenylyl cyclase to convert ATP to cAMP. cAMP activates protein kinase A, which increases secretion of HCl from parietal cells.
OptionB: Histamine activates the Gq subunit, which stimulates adenylyl cyclase to convert ATP to cAMP. cAMP activates protein kinase A, which increases secretion of HCl from parietal cells.
OptionC: Histamine activates the Gq subunit, which stimulates phospholipase C to cleave PIP2 into IP3 and DAG. IP3 stimulates the release of calcium from the SR. Calcium ions and DAG activates protein kinase C, which causes activation of the proton pump to increase HCl secretion from chief cells.
OptionD: Histamine activates the Gq subunit, which stimulates phospholipase C to cleave PIP2 into IP3 and DAG. IP3 stimulates the release of calcium from the SR. Calcium ions and DAG activates protein kinase C, which causes activation of the proton pump to increase HCl secretion from parietal cells.
OptionE: Histamine activates the Gs subunit, which stimulates phospholipase C to cleave PIP2 into IP3 and DAG. IP3 stimulates the release of calcium from the SR. Calcium ions and DAG activates protein kinase C, which causes activation of the proton pump to increase HCl secretion from parietal cells.
Explanation:
Histamine activates the Gs subunit, which stimulates adenylyl cyclase to convert ATP to cAMP. cAMP activates protein kinase A, which increases secretion of HCl from parietal cells.

 

Gastrin and acetylcholine activate the Gq subunit, which stimulates phospholipase C to cleave PIP2 into IP3 and DAG. IP3 stimulates the release of calcium from the SR. Calcium ions and DAG activates protein kinase C, which causes activation of the proton pump to increase HCl secretion from parietal cells.

 

Somatostatin and prostaglandin activate the Gi subunit, which inhibits adenylyl cyclase from converting ATP to cAMP. cAMP is inhibited from activating protein kinase A, which normally increases secretion of HCl from parietal cells. This means HCl secretion is reduced.
Tags: Digestion, Digestion and Absorption, Stomach, Case 3

Question: A patient is chronically infected with hepatitis B. What will this patient's hepatitis B blood test results show?
OptionA:
Positive HBsAg (surface antigen)

Positive anti-HBcAg (core antibody)

Positive IgM anti-HBc (core IgM antibody)

Negative anti-HBs (surface antibody)
Explanation:
B: correct answer - it shows a patient chronically infected with hepatitis B. 

  • HBsAg is positive because the active virus is present in the body.
  • anti-HBc and anti-HBs are positive because the body has produced antibodies to fight against the full virus (which has both core and surface antigens).
  • IgM anti-HBc is negative because IgM is the first antibody produced so it is only present in acute infection. 

A: shows a patient acutely infected with hepatitis B. 

  • HBsAg is present because the full virus is active in the patient. 
  • anti-HBs and anti-HBc are present because the body has produced antibodies to fight the virus. 
  • IgM anti-HBc is positive because it is an acute infection. 

C: shows a patient who is immune as a result of previous natural infection by the full virus.

  • HBsAg is negative because the patient is not infected at the time of the blood test so the full virus is not active in the body so the antigen on the surface of the virus isn't present. 
  • anti-HBs and anti-HBc are positive because the body produced antibodies in the past to fight the full infection, so they have remained in the body and the patient is now immune. 

D: shows a patient who is immune as a result of hepatitis B vaccination.

  • HBsAg is negative because the patient is not currently infected so the virus is not active in the body and the antigen isn't present. 
  • anti-HBc is negative because the patient has never been exposed to the full virus (only the inactive form in the vaccine) so the body hasn't had to produce antibodies against the core antigen.
  • However, the inactive virus in the vaccination does have HBsAg (surface antigens) on it, meaning the body has been exposed to the surface antigen and has produced surface antibodies against it. 

E: shows a patient who has never been exposed to the virus, so is negative for everything, but is susceptible (they are not immune). 

 

This is the picture I used to help me write the question:

I found this topic really difficult but it was covered pretty well in the immunology revision sessions, so hope this has helped a bit!

Question:
Sally is a 27 year old woman who has come into the GP presenting with a dysuria, a raised temperature and lower abdominal pain. The GP suspects that she has a lower tract UTI. Sally has never had a UTI before.

 

What is the next step the GP should take to confirm a diagnosis of a UTI?
OptionA: Take a urine sample and conduct sensitivity testing, to find the most effective antibiotic treatment for the UTI.
OptionB: Carry out an ultrasound to check for inflammation of the bladder or kidneys.
OptionC: Take a urine sample and carry out urinalysis.
OptionD: Take a urine sample and send it off to the lab to culture.
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

 

Urinalysis is the standard practice for diagnosing UTIs:

  • It involves dipping a diagnostic stick into urine.
  • It indicates the proportions of constituents such as proteins, or if there is blood present in the urine.
  • It is easy, economical and quick.
  • If there is a positive assessment of infection, it is treated with the most applicable antibiotics.

A urine culture is only used in ‘complicated’ UTIs - if there is:

  • Impaired renal function.
  • An abnormal urinary tract (e.g. renal calculus (kidney stones)).
  • A suspected UTI associated with haematuria (RBCs in the urine).
  • Recurrent UTIs.
  • In pregnancy – before and after empirical antibiotic treatment

Sensitivity testing is used to find the most effective antibiotic treatment for the UTI. It is only used if the current treatments are not effective.

 

An ultrasound may identify inflammation of the bladder or kidneys, however it would not be useful in terms of diagnosing a UTI.

Question: Linoleic acid, one of the essential fatty acids, is an omega-6 fatty acid. What does omega-6 mean?
OptionA: The only carbon-carbon double bond is 6 carbons away from the methyl end of the fatty acid chain.
OptionB: The only carbon-carbon double bond is 6 carbons away from the carboxyl end of the fatty acid chain.
OptionC: The final carbon-carbon double bond is 6 carbons away from the methyl end of the fatty acid chain.
OptionD: The final carbon-carbon double bond is 6 carbons away from the carboxyl end of the fatty acid chain.
OptionE: There are 6 carbon-carbon double bonds in the fatty acid chain.
Explanation: Omega-6 means the final carbon-carbon double bond is 6 carbons away from the methyl end of the fatty acid chain. It doesn't tell you anything about the total number of carbon-carbon double bonds in the chain.

Question:
One effect of Statins is that they inhibit HMG-CoA-reductase which is the first enzyme in the synthesis of cholesterol. 

 

What is the other main function of Statins?
Explanation:
Mechanism of Action of Statins:

 

  • Statins reduce LDL cholesterol (or "bad" cholesterol) by inhibiting an enzyme called HMG-CoA reductase. This enzyme normally regulates cholesterol synthesis in the liver; and when the enzyme is inhibited, the production of LDL receptors on the surface of the cells is increased, and these extra receptors remove more cholesterol from the blood stream.
  • Statins typically reduce LDL cholesterol by about 25-40%; they also reduce triglycerides (human fats), while raising HDL cholesterol (or "good" cholesterol) by a small amount. Hence, the total cholesterol level is reduced.

Question: Ischaemic heart disease occurs when there is an inequality between oxygen supply and demand by the myocardium, resulting in reduced oxygen reaching myocytes. Which of these does not lead to a reduced supply of oxygen to the myocardium?
Explanation:
Although all of these conditions can lead to ishchaemic heart disease, Paget's disease is the correct answer. Paget's disease causes excessive production of bone (which contains blood vessels). This means the heart has more blood vessels to supply blood to and the heart has to work harder, meaning it has higher oxygen demand. However, it does not cause the supply of oxygen to the myocardium to be reduced, which all the others do. 

  • Anaemia is reduced levels of iron in the blood - less haemoglobin means less oxygen is transported to the heart. 
  • Prinzmetal's angina is chest pain at rest caused by vasoconstriction of the coronary arteries - there is less blood flow through the coronary arteries so less oxygen reaches the cardiac myocytes. 
  • Tachydysrhythmia - the heart is not beating efficiently so less blood is being pumped out with each contraction and less blood is reaching the heart. 
  • Aortic valve stenosis - the aortic valve is hardened so less blood is pumped out of the heart with each contraction, meaning oxygen supply is less efficient.

Question: A pathophysiological shunt can be formed if there is oedema in the alveoli which prevents gas exchange across the membrane. What would the ventilation:perfusion (V:Q) ratio be in an area of the lung where there is oedema?
Explanation:
The V:Q ratio in this area would be 1 because there is good blood flow to the area but no air flow (as air cannot pass through the fluid). 

 

If there was good air flow but no blood flow, the V:Q ratio would be infinity. 

 

Most efficient gas exchange takes place when ventilation and perfusion are matched, so the V:Q ratio is 1.

Question: how do adrenaline and noradrenaline increase force of contraction and reduce the time of contraction of the heart?
OptionC: binds to beta adrenergic receptors to activate cAMP pathway. this causes phosphorylation of phospholamban and voltage gated Ca channels.
OptionD: binds to beta adrenergic receptors to activate cGMP pathway. this activates phospholamban and voltage gated Ca channels.
OptionE: decreases the calcium in the cells to increase contraction
Explanation: adrenaline and noradrenaline bind to beta adrenergic receptors which activate cAMP second messenger system. this then causes phosphorylation of phospholamban and voltage gated calcium channels via pkA. from this there is increased intracellular calcium which causes increased frorce of contraction and calcium is removed from the cytosol faster meaning calcium and troponin time is shorter leading to decreased duration of contraction.

Question: Bohr shift describes the shift of the oxygen-haemoglobin curve to the right, which indicates increased release of oxygen from haemoglobin. Which of these changes would not promote oxygen release and cause Bohr shift of the oxygen-haemoglobin curve?
Explanation:
Increasing pH would not promote oxygen release - reducing pH promotes oxygen release and causes the Bohr shift because the concentration of hydrogen ions increases. Hydrogen ions alter amino acid residues to reduce the affinity of deoxyheamoglobin for oxygen, so more oxygen is released from haemoglobin. 

 

Increasing temperature denatures the bond between oxygen and haemoglobin, which promotes the release of oxygen. 

 

Increasing partial pressure of carbon dioxide increases the concentration of hydrogen ions, which in turn promotes oxygen release. 

 

2,3-BPG is an enzyme which binds to deoxyhaemoglobin and reduces its affinity for oxygen.

Question:
These have a diploid number of chromosomes (46) and undergo the first stage of meiosis

Which of the following cells best fits the description above?
Explanation:
Spermatogonia
Undifferentiated germ cells. They undergo mitosis over and over, leading to an unlimited amount of sperm potentially being made. Occasionally though, one is differentiated into a…
Primary spermatocyte
These have a diploid number of chromosomes (46). This undergoes meiosis, eventually leading to 4 haploid spermatids produced from each primary spermatocyte. The first stage makes two…
Secondary spermatocytes
These have a haploid number of chromosomes (23). They go through the final stage meiosis (which is basically mitosis), to form…
Spermatids
These haploid cells undergo differentiation (change of shape, including addition of the flagellum tail thing) to form…
Spermatozoa
 Once made, the sperm pass through the efferent ducts into the epididymis, where the fluid is removed from the solution, leading to much more concentrated sperm. They wait at the end of the epididymis near the vas deferens.

Question: Which of the following is not a sign of an upper motor neurone lesion?
Explanation:
A: pyramidal pattern of weakness is where in the upper limb there is weakness in the extensors, and in the lower limb there is weakness in the flexors

B: hyperreflexia is increased reflexes. This is caused by reduced background inhibitory signals from upper motor neurones on lower motor neurones.

C: the normal plantar reflex would be flexion (foot downwards). A positive Babinski's sign is where there is instead extension (foot upwards). Note a positive Babinski's sign is normal in infants

D: clonus is a series of involuntary rapid muscle contractions in response to muscle stretching and is typically tested at the ankle

E: fasiculations are not a sign of an upper motor neurone lesion but of a lower motor neurone lesion. They are involuntary muscle twitches caused by spontaneous action potentials generated by the lower motor neurone

Question: Which of the following best describes the function of 2,3-diphosphoglycerate?
OptionB: Increases Oxygen liberation from Hb in the tissues
OptionC: Shifts the Hb-Oxygen disassociation curve to the left
OptionD: Increases Hb affinity for CO2 and H+ ions
Explanation:
The oxygen affinity of hemoglobin is regulated by 2,3-DPG, a simple molecule produced by the red cell when it metabolizes glucose.

When the availability of oxygen to tissues is reduced, the red cell responds by synthesizing more 2,3-DPG, a process that occurs over a period of hours to days.

 

- The effect of 2,3-DPG is to reduce the oxygen affinity of hemoglobin.

-  2,3-DPG increases liberation of oxygen in the tissues because it is produced in response to low oxygen in the tissues.

- By doing this it shifts the Hb-Oxygen disassociation curve to the right

- It has no overall effect on the Hb affinity for the CO2 and H+

Question:
Carbon dioxide, a potentially toxic metabolite is transported in blood in different forms.

Which of the following best describes the most common form of Carbon dioxide that is transported in blood.
Explanation:
Carbon dioxide is transported through the bloodstream either dissolved in blood, bound the hemoglobin, or converted to bicarbonate ions.

 

The majority (85%) of carbon dioxide travels in the blood stream as bicarbonate ions. The reaction that describes the formation of bicarbonate ions in the blood is:

CO2 + H2O → H2CO3 → H+ + HCO3–

This means that carbon dioxide reacts with water to form carbonic acid, which dissociates in solution to form hydrogen ions and bicarbonate ions.

Question:
Since citrus fruits are rich in vitamin C, British sailors were given limes to combat scurvy on long ocean voyages; hence, they were called "limeys"

 

What is the mechanism of action of Vitamin C in combating Scurvy?
OptionA: Proline is reduced to form deoxyproline, which adds cross links to the collagen fibres
OptionB: Proline is hydroxylated ,forming hydroxyproline (Hyp), which stabilizes the secondary structure of collagen due to the strong electronegative effects of oxygen
OptionC: Steroid hormones, which stops the collagen synthesis, are hydroxylated at various ring positions , conjugated with sulfate or glucuronic acid and excreted in the urine
OptionD: Esterase enzymes are activated by hydroxylation which increases the production of collagen
Explanation:
• Hydroxyproline is necessary for the construction of the body's major structural protein, collagen.
  • Defects in collagen synthesis lead to easy bruising, internal bleeding, breakdown of connective tissue of the ligaments and tendons, and increased risk to blood vessel damage.
  • Increased spill of hydroxyproline in the urine is generally associated with breakdown of connective tissue due to disease process and may also be a manifestation of vitamin C deficiency
  • Hydroxyproline's immediate precursor is proline.
  • The conversion of proline to hydroxyproline requires vitamin C (ascorbic acid). Vitamin C deficiency results in the poor conversion of proline to hydroxyproline
