Question:
David, a 37 year old man, visits his GP surgery. He explains that he is suffering from indigestion, and that he gets pain in his lower chest after eating and an uncomfortable sense of fullness. 

The GP diagnoses him with dyspepsia, and advises him to take some over the counter antacids. He also takes a blood sample to test for anaemia.

David asks if he needs an endoscopy, but the GP says that it is not necessary as David is not displaying any red flag symptoms.

 

Which of the following is NOT a red flag symptom of Dyspepsia?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.  Persistent vomiting would be a red flat symptom, however a few instances of nausea/vomiting is not a concern.

 

It is important that doctors are rational when ordering investigations, because not everybody who has dyspepsia will need an endoscopy.. The NICE guidelines take into account the age of the patient, and the symptoms they present with. Most people can be treated empirically – i.e. prescribed drugs based on experience and observation  However endoscopies are advised for people with alarm or ‘red flag’ symptoms.

 

Red flag symptoms include: GI Bleeding (Haematemesis/Malaena), Iron Deficiency Anaemia, Unintentional Weight Loss, Dysphagia, Persistent Vomiting, Epigastric Mass, >55 with persistent / recent onset dyspepsia

Question: One of the important roles of the liver is to metabolise drugs and toxins. Which of the following describes phase II metabolism?
OptionA: Creates a chemically reactive group on the drug to facilitate further metabolic processing
OptionB: Can activate the therapeutic activity of 'pro-drugs' but it can have a very unwanted toxic effect too
OptionC: The drug is firstly de-activated and secondly made water soluble
OptionE: The enzymes reactions include oxidation, reduction, de-esterification and isomerisation (and many more)
Explanation:
C is the correct answer. All other answers are true of phase I metabolism 

 

Phase I metabolism
Creates or exposes a chemical reactive group on the drug to facilitate further metabolic processing in Phase II.
Phase I-mediated enzymes reactions include: oxidation, reduction, de-esterification, isomerisation (plus many more..)
Can activate the therapeutic activity of ‘pro-drugs’ but it can have a very unwanted toxic effect too


Phase II metabolism
The drug (or intermediate metabolite generated from Phase I) can now be a) de-activated and b) made water soluble by Phase II enzymes, in advance of either renal or hepatobiliary excretion
Is made water-soluble typically by replacing the drug’s pharmacophoric regions with a sugar or sulphate group

Question: The most significant family of phase I enzymes are cytochrome P450 enzymes. Which of the following best descries how they modify drugs?
Explanation:
Cytochrome P450 enzymes

  • The most significant family of Phase I enzymes
  • Responsible for oxidative modification in advance of Phase II
  • ‘On-demand’ enzymes, which are induced only when the drug/toxin they metabolise is detected
  • The active site is catalytic haem iron that facilitates the oxygenation of the drug molecule
  • Why such a big family? Different drugs and substrate specificity/ Also, they are involved the internally biochemically activated molecules the body has produced
Tags: Drug Metabolism, Pharmacology, enzymes, Case 3, Liver

Question:
You're in Tesco Extra restocking your cupboards after the Easter holidays. You hear someone across the aisle from you coughing and spluttering. You notice their sputum is a yellow-green colour before you quickly leave the aisle, remembering that yellow-green sputum is a sign of infection. 

 

     

 

What is the cause of this yellow-green colour?
OptionA: Bilirubin and biliverdin is present in the sputum
OptionB: Gram positive bacteria have a yellow-green appearance
OptionC: Cells infected with a viral infection become yellow-green
OptionD: Enzymes for phagocytosis released by macrophages are yellow-green
OptionE: Neutrophils release yellow-green enzymes during an infection
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. Neutrophils release myeloperoxidase upon degranulation, which contains a haem group. This causes the yellow-green appearance of the sputum during an infection. 

 

The stem for this question came from one of the patients I spoke to on placement. She had bronchiectasis and found that people would be repulsed by her constant coughs, and even grocery shopping had become more difficult for her.

Question:
What does this describe:

 

 Na+ channels are inactivated and no matter what stimulus is applied they will not re-open to allow Na+ in & depolarise the membrane to the threshold of an action potential.
Explanation:
Depolarisation:

When the cell membranes are stimulated, there is a change in the permeability of the membrane to sodium ions (Na+).
The membrane becomes more permeable to Na+, sodium ions diffuse into the cell down a concentration gradient. The entry of Na+ disturbs the resting potential and causes the inside of the cell to become more positive relative to the outside. As the outside of the cell has become more positive than the inside of the cell, the membrane is now DEPOLARISED.
When enough sodium ions enter the cell to depolarise the membrane to a critical level (threshold level) an action potential arises which generates an impulse.

 

Throughout depolarisation, the Na+ continues to rush inside until the action potential reaches its peak and the sodium gates close.
If the depolarisation is not great enough to reach threshold, then an action potential and hence an impulse are not produced.
This is called the All-or-None Principle.

 

After depolarization potassium (K+) moves out through the voltage gated K+ channels restoring the inside to a negative voltage
This is called repolarization

 

Repolarization leads to a voltage below the resting potential, called hyperpolarization
Now neuron cannot produce a new action potential. It must return a resting state.This is the refractory period

 

There are two types of refractory period:
Absolute Refractory Period – Na+ channels are inactivated and no matter what stimulus is applied they will not re-open to allow Na+ in & depolarise the membrane to the threshold of an action potential. 

 

Relative Refractory Period - Some of the Na+ channels have re-opened but the threshold is higher than normal making it more difficult for the activated Na+ channels to raise the membrane potential to the threshold of excitation.

Explanation:

D is the correct answer. When trying to remember what activates each pathway I use the following memory aid:

 

-Classical period is known as antiquity which sounds like antibody.

-Lectin sounds like leptin. Leptin produces fat cells, mannose is a sugar. 

-The alternative pathway is Indie. Indie people are evident by what they wear on their surface.

Question: A patient presents with difficulty performing external rotation and abduction of the arm. Which nerve is damaged?
Explanation: The patient has damaged his axillary nerve as this is affecting the Teres Minor muscle (responsible for external rotation) and the Deltoids (responsible for abduction)

The tibial nerve innervate the muscles responsible for plantarflexing and inverting the foot, therefore with its absence, the foot appears dorsiflexed and everted. It's neurotome is the sole of the foot hence the loss of sensation

Question:
A 57 year old man comes into your practice complaining of cholic pain in his right hypochondriac region. He says that this pain has been present for several months now and is exacerbated by the consumption of fatty food. The man appears pyrexic and palpation of his abdomen reveals Murphey's sign, that is pain upon inspiration when a hand in placed under the costal margin. You suspect chronic cholecystitis. A cholecystectomy is conducted and a histological sample is taken. The slide reveals that the chronic inflammation changed the architecture of the mucosa of the gallbladder, which of the following is most likely to be the slide taken from the histological sample. 

 

Image depicting a cholecystectomy
Explanation:
A- Depicts healthy gallbladder mucosa.

B- Healthy human liver.

C-This depicts the mucosa found in chronic cholecystitis. The large space is a Rokitansky–Aschoff sinus, also entrapped epithelial crypts. This is evident as the crypt as penetrated muscular layer.

D-This image depicts the mucosa of a small intestine, this is evident by the long villi lined in goblet cells for mucus secretion.

E- This is gastric antrum mucosa. The arrow is pointing towards the characteristic gastric pit. Gastric juice is secreted from gastric glands, which are located in narrow tube like structures called gastric pits. Gastric juice contains hydrochloric acid, pepsinogen and mucus in a healthy adult. Hydrochloric acid is secreted by parietal cells, pepsinogen is secreted by gastric chief cells and mucus is secreted by mucus neck cells.

Question:
A case-controlled clinical trail has shows that clopidogrel is beneficial in reducing risk of infarction recurrence in MI patients.

 

 

The researchers decided to determine the number needed to treat to prevent 1 infarction. What is the best estimate for this determined value?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D.

 

First I'll explain the table. This shows that 420 MI patients were given a placebo (the equivalent of no treatment) and that 190 of them went on to have another infarction. It also shows that 390 MI patients were given clopidogrel (an anti-platelet drug) and that only 130 of them went on to have another infarction.

 

Number needed to treat is a value which is used to measure the effectiveness of a treatment or healthcare intervention. It is the average number of people who would need to be treated to prevent one additional bad outcome. The ideal number would be 1 - everyone that is treated is helped. The higher the number the less effective the treatment.

 

NNT equals 1 divided by the Absolute Risk Reduction (1/ARR). Therefore to work out NNT we first have to work out ARR.

 

The placebo absolute risk = 190/420 = 0.452 (3dp)

The clopidogrel absolute risk = 130/390 = 0.333 (3dp).

Absolute risk reduction = placebo absolute risk - clopidogrel absolute risk = 0.452 - 0.333 = 0.119 (3dp).

 

Therefore, because NNT = 1/ARR, NNT = 1/0.119 = 8.4 

 

Number needed to treat has to be an integer (i.e. a whole number). Normally 8.4 would be rounded down to 8, however in number needed to treat you always round up. This is because the idea is that if you treat 8 people, you won't necessarily prevent a Infarction recurrence, but if you treat 9 people then you definitely will have prevented an infarction recurrence.

 

Therefore the answer is 9.

 

If this is confusing look at the Q1 video in the Case 4 evidence based medicine/Numeracy folder on learning central - it is explained a lot more clearly there than I can explain it!

Question: Which of the following statements is not a function/innervation of the facial nerve (VII)?

There are four muscles of mastication – the masseter, temporalis, medial pterygoid and lateral pterygoid.

Embryologically, the muscles of mastication develop from the first pharyngeal arch. Consequently they are innervated by a branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V), the mandibular nerve.

Sensory: None.
Special Sensory: Provides special taste sensation to the anterior 2/3 of the tongue.
Parasympathetic

Supplies many of the glands of the head and neck, including:

  • Submandibular and sublingual salivary glands.
  • Nasal, palatine and pharyngeal mucous glands.
  • Lacrimal glands.

Question:
Mr L. Ung has come to his GP complaining of breathlessness and a productive cough with white sputum. He said he has been repainting his new restaurant with money earned from chimney sweeping. He enjoys the occasional Cuban cigar. His GP sent him for a spirometry test, and his results are below.

 

FEV1/FVC:     0.65

 

After being given salbutamol, his FEV1 increased.

 

What may this indicate?
Explanation:
The FEV1/FVC ratio is less than 0.70, suggesting obstructive lung disease. From the options, this would either be COPD or asthma. After salbutamol, FEV1 increased, showing reversibility. In restrictive lung disease, like pulmonary fibrosis, the FEV1 and FVC are equally reduced, so the FEV1/FVC ratio stays roughly normal.

 

 

  • Asthma is an obstructive lung disease, as the airways become narrowed due to bronchospasm, which usually occurs as a response to an allergen. In asthma (during non-flare-up periods), sputum is generally clear or white.
  • Bronchiectasis refers to permanently dilated airways, and is usually not diagnosed using spirometry.

 

Other notes:

  • Chemicals, like paints or solvents, can emit volatile organic compounds and other toxic compounds, which have been linked to disease.(http://www.lung.org/our-initiatives/healthy-air/indoor/indoor-air-pollutants/building-paint-products.html)

Question: In normal health, what is the main method the body utilises to prevent albumin from being excreted as urine?
OptionA: Aldosterone is bound to sodium pumps on the basement membrane that block aldosterone entry
OptionB: It is too large to pass through the gaps between the fenestrations of the capillary endothelium
OptionD: Basement membrane is negatively charged. Albumin is also negatively charged (and also too big) and hence cannot pass through this barrier
OptionE: It is actively reabsorbed in the collecting duct
Explanation: Although a tiny bit of albumin passes into the glomerular filtrate and is reabsorbed by endocytosis in the PCT (answer C), the vast majority of albumin is prevented from entering the glomerulus via the negative charge of the basement membrane and albumin's negative charge and large size itself.

Question: What type of transporter is the SGLT-1?
Explanation:
A: Uniporters transport only one molecule in one direction. For example, in adipose tissue and striated muscle there are GLUT-4 uniporters.

B: Aquaporins are solely water channels.

C: Symporters transport two or more molecules in the same direction. For example, the SGLT-1 (sodium dependant glucose co-transporter) located in intestinal mucosa.

D: Antiporters transport two or more molecules but in different directions. For example, NHE-1 (for pH maintenance, H+ ions out, Na+ ions in).

E: Made up.

Question: Epithelia is important for lining and covering the exterior surfaces of the body, internal cavities and body tubes. What type of epithelium is found lining the fallopian (uterine tubes)?
Explanation:

B: Stratified squamous epithelium (non-keratinised type) is located in the oesophagus, cheeks and vagina amongst other locations. Stratified squamous epithelium (keratinised type) forms the epidermis of the skin.

C: Non-ciliated simple columnar epithelium is mainly found lining the digestive tract.

D: Simple cuboidal epithelium is located in nephrons and in the smaller ducts of some glands.

E: Ciliated simple columnar epithelium is found in the upper respiratory tract, uterus and fallopian tubes.

 

For completion:

-Transitional epithelium is located in the bladder (urinary), ureters and part of the urethra.

-Stratified cuboidal epithelium is found in larger ducts of glands (like the salivary glands).

Question: Which of these enzyme is not a rate limiting step in glycolysis?

Question:
Pearl is a 20 year old woman who comes into the GP requesting the combined oral contraceptive pill. She has never been on the pill before. The GP asks her a few questions to determine whether the combined pill is the most suitable for her.

 

Which of the following is NOT a contra-indication of the combined oral contraceptive pill?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B.

 

Contra-indications of the combined oral contraceptive pill include: pregnancy, pre-existing cardiovascular condition, obese, hypercholesterolaemic, smoker over 40, 'oestrogen-sensitive' breast/bowel cancer, liver cirrhosis.

 

The COCP can also have an effect on blood pressure, and can cause it to rise slightly. This can be a problem in patients with hypertension, but not those with hypotension.

 

The reason that the COCP can have these contra-indications is because the oestrogen in the pill has effects on the coagulation pathway and can increase the number of blood clotting factors. In susceptible patients, this can cause side effects such as thrombo-embolic strokes which are potentially life threatening.

 

Other risk factors include smoking, alcohol, cardiovascular risk factors and family history.

 

For people with these contra-indications/risk factors, it is recommended that the progesterone only pill (POP) be prescribed instead of the combined pill.

 

(Dr Coffey's "Drugs used as contraceptives" Lecture - Case 2)

Question: Which of the following digestive hormones stimulates appetite?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C - Orexin.

 

All of the other hormones listed supress appetite.

 

Leptin - known as the 'satiety hormone'. Supresses appetite and makes you feel full. Secreted by adipocytes, therefore levels of leptin are proportional to fat mass.

 

Ghrelin - A hormone which also stimulates appetite. It is mainly released from the stomach when there are low blood glucose levels. It also stimulates the release of growth hormone form the anterior pituitary gland.

 

Orexin - Stimulatesappetite and increases craving for food, especially high fat food. Released from the lateral hypothalamus when there are low blood glucose levels.

 

CCK - Supresses appetite and stimulates the digestion of fats and proteins. Secreted from I cells in the duodenum in response to the presence of fats. It also stimulates bile release from the gall bladder, increases pancreatic secretions and slows the emptying of the stomach which increases the feeling of fullness.

 

PYY- Reduces appetite. Released from L cells in the lower small intestine due to high fat content following a meal. Inhibits gut motility, which increases satiety.

 

(From the Regulation of Digestion and Appetite tutorial - PCS 2)

Question: after removing a tourniquet, a kind of intrinsic regulation of blood vessels takes place. which type is this?
Explanation:
The aim of autoregulation is to maintain a constant blood flow despite changes in pressure in the blood vessels. so if there is a decrease in pressure there will be decreased blood flow. To try to compensate, the blood vessel dilates meaning there is reduced resistance which in turn increases the blood flow back to a more normal state. 

 

active hyperaemia- this is when there is back up of metabolites due to increased exercise etc. this means there is then dilation of the blood vessels to increase blood flow to get rid of the metabolites or by-products from the area. 

 

Reactive hyperaemia occurs after a period of ischaemia e.g. after use of a tourniquet. after a period of ischaemia, there is reduced blood flow and the buildup of metabolites so after the period of ischaemia has finished there is increased blood flow to get rid of metabolites and vasodilation in order to restore the blood flow back to the normal level.

Neuropathic pain describes modified pain responses that are because of altered neuronal properties rather than an unusual stimulus.

 

One type of neuropathic pain is hyperalgesia; which of the following is the best definition of hyperalgesia?

OptionC: exaggeration or amplification of an already painful stimulus

E is lancinating pain, characterised by tearing, cutting or stabbing pain.

Question:
A cell-cell junction that seals cells together in an epithelium in a way that prevents even small molecules from leaking from one side of the sheet to the other. Junctional proteins include occludins and claudins. An example of this cell-cell junction can be found in the Blood-brain barrier.

 

To which of the following cell-cell junction does the above description belong to?
Explanation:
Gap Junctions: Gap junctions are clusters of intercellular channels that allow direct diffusion of ions and small molecules between adjacent cells. A collection of connexins present.

 

Adherencs: Adherens junctions are involved in a number of critical functions, including providing additional structural support. For example, they hold cardiac muscle cells tightly together as the heart expands and contracts.
Adherens junctions are built primarily from cadherins, whose extracellular segments bind to each other and whose intracellular segments bind to catenins. Catenins are connected to actin filaments.

 

Desmosomes are molecular complexes of cell adhesion proteins and linking proteins that attach the cell surface adhesion proteins to intracellular keratin cytoskeletal filaments.

 

Anchoring junctions: Desmosomes, hemidesmosomes and adherens junctions are part of anchoring junctions.

Question: Name the area of the brain that is responsible for language production; damage to this area results in productive aphasia.
Explanation:
Broca's Area (Language production)
Broca's area, located in the frontal lobe of the brain, is linked to speech production, and recent studies have shown that it also plays a significant role in language comprehension. Broca's area works in conjunction with working memory to allow a person to use verbal expression and spoken words. Damage to Broca's area can result in productive aphasia (also known as Broca's aphasia), or an inability to speak. Patients with Broca's can often still understand language, but they cannot speak fluently.

Wernicke's Area (language comprehension)
Wernicke's area, located in the cerebral cortex, is the part of the brain involved in understanding written and spoken language. Damage to this area results in receptive aphasia (also called Wernicke's aphasia). This type of aphasia manifests itself as a loss of comprehension, so sometimes while the patient can apparently still speak, their language is nonsensical and incomprehensible.

 

Primary visual cortex = first cortical region to receive information from the eyes 

Primary somateosensory region = first region of brain to receive info from receptors in skin and muscle

Primary auditory cortex = first cortical region to get info back from ears.

Question:
What is the confluence of arteries at the base of the brain formed  which is formed by two group of arteries - the internal carotid arteries and two vertebral arteries.and has the major branches: anterior, middle and posterior cerebral arteries?

This allows equalization of blood flow between the left and right cerebral hemispheres, and can allow anastomotic circulation if parts are occluded.
Explanation:
The circle of Willis is a ring of interconnecting arteries located at the base of the brain around the optic chiasm , infundibulum of the pituitary stalk and the hypothalamus. It provides blood to the brain and neighbouring structures.

 

Clinical relevance:

 

Thrombosis in the anterior cerebral artery (beyond the anterior communicating artery): This will lead to paralysis or weakness of muscles of the leg and foot of the opposite side (that is, complete contralateral hemiplegia and hemianaesthesia – leg, arm and face).

 

Thrombosis in the middle cerebral artery: This causes hemiplegia and loss of sensations on the opposite half of the body, affecting the face and arms the most. Also, Broca's and Wernicke's area are affected as well. Cerebral oedema may also result, causing compression of the optic radiation leading to homonymous hemianopia on the opposite side. Hearing may also be affected, but this may be compensated by the opposite hemisphere.

 

Thrombosis in the posterior cerebral artery: This condition leads mainly to visual effects causing contralateral hemianopia (homonymous hemianopia)

 

KenHub

Question: Which of the following does NOT have nociceptors?
Explanation:
Brain does not contain any nociceptors; so how do people get headaches? Is brain aching?

 

However, the brain contains layers of coverings, blood vessels, the scalp and some muscles. All of these other structures have pain receptors. The coverings of the brain are called meninges and consist of the dura, arachnoid and pia. The dura in particular has a lot of pain receptors and may be responsible for many headaches. The patient usually doesn't report any pain when you drill a hole in their skull. However, they start to report dull pain or headache when you stimulate or touch the dura.

OptionA: Allows the brain to float – almost weightless
OptionD: Allows communication between the right and left hemisphere of the brain
Explanation:
Functions of CSF (A, B , C and E):

Allows the brain to float – almost weightless
Mechanical protection from injury
Provides chemical stability for the brain
Protects against ischaemia

 

Function of Corpus Collusum (D) :

The corpus callosum is a thick band of nerve fibers that divides the cerebral cortex lobes into left and right hemispheres. It connects the left and right sides of the brain allowing for communication between both hemispheres.

Explanation:
The limbic system, located just beneath the cerebrum on both sides of the thalamus, is not only responsible for our emotional lives but also many higher mental functions, such as learning and formation of memories.


The primary structures within the limbic system include the amygdala, hippocampus, thalamus, hypothalamus, basal ganglia, and cingulate gyrus.

  • The amygdala is the emotion center of the brain, while the hippocampus plays an essential role in the formation of new memories about past experiences.
  • The thalamus and hypothalamus are associated with changes in emotional reactivity.
  • The cingulate gyrus coordinates smells and sights with pleasant memories, induces an emotional reaction to pain, and helps regulate aggressive behavior.
  • The basal ganglia is a group of nuclei lying deep in the subcortical white matter of the frontal lobes; its functions include organizing motor behavior and coordinating rule-based, habit learning.

Question: The ________________ is a C-shaped bundle of nerve fibers in the brain that acts as the major output tract of the hippocampus.
Explanation:
The brainstem consists of the medulla oblongata, pons, and midbrain:

 

pons
Contains nuclei that relay signals from the forebrain to the cerebellum, along with nuclei that deal primarily with sleep, respiration, swallowing, bladder control, hearing, equilibrium, taste, eye movement, facial expressions, facial sensation, and posture.

midbrain
Associated with vision, hearing, motor control, sleep and wake cycles, alertness, and temperature regulation.

medulla
The lower half of the brainstem that contains the cardiac, respiratory, vomiting, and vasomotor centers and regulates autonomic, involuntary functions such as breathing, heart rate, and blood pressure.

 

Insula: is a portion of the cerebral cortex folded deep within the lateral sulcus (the fissure separating the temporal lobe from the parietal and frontal lobes). The insulae are believed to be involved in consciousness and play a role in diverse functions usually linked to emotion or the regulation of the body's homeostasis.

Question:
Alzheimer's disease, vascular and mixed dementia are the three commonest forms of dementia affecting the elderly. There is evidence that the excitatory activity of L-glutamate plays a role in the pathogenesis of Alzheimer's disease and in the damage from an ischaemic stroke.

 

antagonist to N-Methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) type receptors, such as________________may prevent excitatory amino acid neurotoxicity
Explanation:
Pharmacology Light Bulb Case 6:

 

DONEPEZIL, GALANTAMINE & RIVASTIGMINE: are all reversible acetylcholine esterase inhibitors.
 In Alzhemier's Disease patients you want to prolong the half life of ACh to improve cognition. 

 

MEMANTINE: NMDA receptor antagonist & nAChR antagonist.
Glutamatergic excitotoxicity (causing neuronal death) can be mediated through pathological NMDA receptor activation. Suppressing this activity with memantine can be a (limited) therapeutic option in advanced AD patients.
Blockade of nAChR as a therapeutic option sounds counter-intuitive because the ACh improves cogintion, but paradoxically, the brain up-regulates nAChR in the presence of memantine to counteract its blockade, which enhances ACh-mediated neurotransmission.

Question: Which area of the brain is the primary visual cortex located?
Explanation: The primary visual cortex (V1) is located within the occipital lobe and hence its cortical association area is responsible for vision.

Question: Rachel is up for a new job promotion. In order to get in with the boss, she starts attending smoking breaks where it appears all of the big decisions are made. As she spends increasing amount of time inhaling the toxic cigarette smoke, she swears she can feel her epithelium changing to fit that of her smoke-loving colleagues. Following chronic smoke exposure, respiratory epithelium may undergo metaplasia to which epithelium type?
Explanation: Cigarette smoke is toxic to the respiratory epithelium and stimulates metaplasia, which is the changing of one fully differentiated epithelium to another fully differentiated epithelium. Respiratory epithelium most often changes to stratified squamous (non-keratinised), similar to that found in the mouth and upper oesophagus. This is a pre-malignant change and this may facilitate transformation into squamous cell carcinoma - the most common form of lung cancer.

Question:
A patient comes into your clinic, having found and tested a bottle of eye drops from their medicine cabinet. They are not sure what was in the drops, as the label had been removed, but hoped it would ease the irritation they were experiencing.

 

When you look at them, their eye looks like this: 

 

When you test their corneal reflex, they do not blink immediately. 

What have they put in their eye?
Explanation:
Phenylephrine
• Adrenoceptor agonist acts on SNS
• Causes mydriasis (dilation) of pupil + peripheral vasoconstriction (--> whitening of sclera)

Tetracaine
• Local anaesthetic, works by blocking VG Na+ channels in nerve axons
• Causes loss of corneal reflex

Cocaine
• Local anaesthetic + sympathomimetic
• Causes mydriasis, peripheral vasoconstriction (--> whitening of sclera) + loss of corneal reflex

Tropicamide
• mACh receptor antagonist that blocks PS impulses
• Paralyses pupil constrictor response + ciliary muscle
• Because of the paralysis of the ciliary muscle, the lens can no longer be adjusted to focus on close objects --> cycloplegia

Pilocarpine
• mAch receptor agonist that causes marked pupil constrictor muscle contraction (miosis)
• This process also acts to 'pull open' the canal of Schlemm
• The eye also becomes bloodshot
Tags: Drugs in eye practical, Drugs in eyes, Eyes, PCS3

Question: A 15 year old patient comes into A and E suffering with meningitis. Inflammation of the meninges can lead to the opening of the blood-brain barrier. This can be useful in treating meningitis as it allows for antibiotics to pass into the CSF and reach therapeutic levels. Glial cells form the support network for the neurones of the central nervous system. The following histological image depicts a blood vessel in the CNS being surrounded by a 'blood-brain barrier' formed of tight junctions between cells. What type of cell is being pointed to in the image which is forming this blood brain barrier?
Explanation:
Microglia

 

Microglia are the brain’s immune cells, serving to protect it against injury and disease. Microglia identify when something has gone wrong and initiate a response that removes the toxic agent and/or clears away the dead cells. Thus microglia are the brain’s protectors. However, the situation may be different in neurodegenerative disorders such as Alzheimer’s disease—there is evidence that microglia may become hyperactivated, promoting neuroinflammation that can lead to the characteristic toxic protein deposits seen in Alzheimer’s (amyloid plaques and neurofibrillary tangles). Finally, recent work shows that microglia play a role in the developing brain. Normally, far more synapses are created than are needed, with only the strongest, most important ones surviving. Microglia directly contribute to this synaptic ‘pruning’ process by eating up the synapses tagged as unnecessary.

 

Astrocytes

 

Astrocytes are star-shaped cells that maintain a neuron’s working environment. They do this by controlling the levels of neurotransmitter around synapses, controlling the concentrations of important ions like potassium, and providing metabolic support.

But astrocytes don’t just maintain the environment around synapses. An active area of research addresses how astrocytes modulate how neurons communicate. Because astrocytes have the ability to sense neurotransmitter levels in synapses, and can respond by releasing molecules that directly influence neuronal activity, astrocytes are increasingly seen as important for modifying synapses.

The blood–brain barrier is composed of high-density cells restricting passage of substances from the bloodstream much more than do the endothelial cells in capillaries elsewhere in the body. Astrocyte cell projections called astrocytic feet (also known as "glia limitans") surround the endothelial cells of the BBB, providing biochemical support to those cells.

 

Oligodendrocytes

 

Oligodendrocytes provide support to axons of neurons in the central nervous system, particularly those that travel long distances within the brain. They produce a fatty substance called myelin, which is wrapped around axons as a layer of insulation. Similar in function to insulation layers around power cables, the myelin sheath allows electrical messages to travel faster awhite matter—the white is the myelin wrapped around axons. Multiple sclerosis is caused by a loss of the myelin sheath around neurons.

 

Ependymal cells

 

Ependymal cells line the spinal cord and ventricles of the brain. They are involved in creating cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).


Radial glia

 

Radial glial cells are progenitor cells that can generate neurons, astrocytes and oligodendrocytes.

Question: A patient comes into your practice regarding an acute onset of vision loss. Later diagnosis lead you to suspect that the patient has ocular ischemic syndrome. Further investigations reveal that this has been caused by a thromboembolism in the ophthalmic artery. The ophthalmic artery is a division of what artery?
Explanation: This case is an example of how ocular ischaemia syndrome might present. However, occlusion of the ophthalmic artery may be asymptomatic. The arrangement of the brain's arteries into the circle of Willis creates redundancy (analogous to engineered redundancy) for collateral circulation in the cerebral circulation. If one part of the circle becomes blocked or narrowed (stenosed) or one of the arteries supplying the circle is blocked or narrowed, blood flow from the other blood vessels can often preserve the cerebral perfusion well enough to avoid the symptoms of ischemia.

Question: Jonathon falls over and cuts himself when at the park. After a couple of days he notices the wound is not healing as quickly as it should, and doesn't look great. He goes to the doctor who tells him he has critical colonisation of the wound. What does this include?

Question: Excitation moves from endocardium to epicardium. Net wave is moving from midline apex towards the left side (towards positive amplifier). Which part of a heartbeat shown on an ECG is best described by this?
Explanation:
P-wave = Excitation wave moves from SAN over the atria walls from right side to left side (towards positive amplifier)

Q-wave = Excitation wave invades septum. Since left ventricle wall has more mass, net wave is approaching midline septum from the left side (away from positive amplifier)

R-wave = : Excitation moves from endocardium to epicardium. Net wave is moving from midline apex towards the left side (towards positive amplifier)

S-wave = Excitation moves from apex to base of ventricles. Net wave is upwards (away from positive amplifier)

T-wave = Repolarisation wave moves upwards from apex to base of ventricles. Repolarisation is opposite of excitation (depolarisation). Net negative wave is moving upwards; net positive wave is moving downwards (towards positive amplifier)

Question: In which part of the nephron does phosphoric acid presence block reabsorption of phosphate?
Explanation:
Phorphoric acid presence in the urine, acts as a buffer to prevent the urine from becoming too acidic, and thus preventing it having too great a H+ concentration for the collecting duct to pump against (under stimulus of either aldosterone, acidaemia or hypokalaemia.

Blocking reabsorption of phosphate in the proximal tubule, provides a greater amount of buffer in the distal tubule and collecting duct.

Question: What is the main buffer in the kidney for the excretion of H+ in the distal tubule?
Explanation:
Phosphate is main buffer for excretion of H+ (in distal tubule). Increased HPO42- (in kidneys), this can then accept extra H+ in urine.

Ammonium can also buffer H+ (becomes H2PO4-)

Question: Mr Jones, who is 57 years old, experiences a tight, crushing pain in his chest whilst walking to the shops. He goes to see his GP who prescribes him ivabradine. Which of the following options best describe this drug's mode of action?
OptionA: Cross the cell membrane of cardiac cells and bind to L-type voltage-gated  calcium channels, induing a conformational change
OptionB: Dose dependently inhibits the mixed Na+/K+ inward ion current that constitutes the 'funny current' in the SA node. This decreases pacemaker automaticity
OptionC: Stimulates gyanylyl cyclises to increase cGMP, which decreases Ca2+ entry into the vascular smooth muscle cells
OptionD: Activates K+ ATP channel effluxes, hyper polarising cells and thus preventing voltage-gated Ca2+ channel activity
OptionE: Competitive inhibitor of beta-adrenoreceptors, preventing the binding of the agonists noradrenaline and adrenaline
Explanation:
A- Prevents Ca2+ entry
E.g. Verapamil

B- Ivabradine. It's a rate limiter.


C- Organic nitrates E.g. isosorbide mononitrate and glyceryl trinitrate. These are vasodilators.
Nicorandil also does this

 

D- Nicorandil. It's a vasodilator

 

E- Beta blockers. Has a negative chronotropic and negative inotropic effect, decreasing cardiac output and hence oxygen demand
E.g. Atenolol
Tags: Drugs, Drugs for Heart, Heart, Pharmacology, Case 4

Question: An 85 year old gentleman has been brought by their daughter into your surgery complaining of Anterograde amnesia (difficulty in forming new memories). Which part of brain is mostly responsible for forming new and episodic memories?
Explanation:
Psychologists and neuroscientists dispute the precise role of the hippocampus, but generally agree that it plays an essential role in the formation of new memories about past experiences. Some researchers consider the hippocampus to be responsible for general declarative memory (memories that can be explicitly verbalized, such as memory of facts and episodic memory).

 

Damage to the hippocampus usually results in profound difficulties in forming new memories (anterograde amnesia), and may also affect access to memories formed prior to the damage (retrograde amnesia). Although the retrograde effect normally extends some years prior to the brain damage, in some cases older memories remain intact; this leads to the idea that over time the hippocampus becomes less important in the storage of memory.

 

Striatum and Cerebellum : Learning new motor skills

 

Amygdala: emotion centre

 

Hypothalamus: changes in emotional activity. Hypothalamus' primary function is homeostasis, which is to maintain the body's status quo system-wide. Hypothalamic hormones include thyrotropin-releasing, gonadotropin-releasing, growth hormone-releasing, corticotrophin-releasing, somatostatin, and dopamine hormones.

Question:

Explanation:
The correct answer is E. Enkephalins, along with endorphins and dynorphins, are peptide opioids. Produced in the PAG, they bind to opioid receptors on neurones, reducing the amount of pain felt. 

Interestingly, small amounts of codeine and morphine are naturally produced within the body. They bind to the same receptors and have the same effect.

Question:
During WW1, head injuries due to shrapnel wounds led the warring powers to develop helmets for their troops in the trenches. It ascends superiorly in the basilar sulcus ventral to the pons and divides at the ponto-mesencephalic junction into the paired posterior cerebral arteries close to the pituitary stalk.

Question: Which of the following membranes in the cochlea separates two liquid-filled tubes that run along the coil of the cochlea, the scala media (endolymph) and the scala tympani (perilymph). It  is involved in holding and moving the stereocillia back and forth.
Explanation:
A base for the sensory cells: 
The basilar membrane is also the base for the sensory cells of hearing, the hair cells that are equipped with "Stereocilia". There are approximately 15,000 hair cells in each human ear . This function as base of the sensory cells gave the basilar membrane its name, and it is again present in all land vertebrates. Due to its location, the basilar membrane places the hair cells in a position where they are adjacent to both the endolymph and the perilymph, which is a precondition of hair cell function.  Thus, when the basilar membrane moves up and down, the hair cells move up and down. The hair cells have projections at their top called stereocilia.

 

 

blue = perilymph

green = endolymph

Question: The _______________ is a complex epithelial structure composed of various cell types, produces endolymph and releases it into the cochlea.
Explanation:
stria vascularis: It produces endolymph for the scala media, one of the three fluid-filled compartments of the cochlea.

 

The eardrum or tympanic membrane separates the external auditory canal from the middle ear which communicates with the nasopharynx via the Eustachian tube . The oval window and the round window  separate the middle and inner ears. The ossicular chain: malleus (1), incus (2) and stapes (3) links the eardrum to the oval window. The surface ratio of eardrum to oval window (20/1) allows an adequate energy transfer of the sound pressure between the air and the fluids of the inner ear. The middle ear can be considered as an impedance adapter - without it about 98% of energy would be reflected back.

The nucleus proprius makes up the bulk of the dorsal horn, and is activated with fine touch and pressure with nucleus dorsalis.

Question: What is the resting potential of the organ of Corti relative to the surrounding tissue called. It is a positive 80 mV DC voltage seen in the endolymphatic space of the cochlea and is generated at the stria vascularis.
Explanation:
Summating Potential – Change of EP in response to sound stimulation (DC current). It is mainly a reflection of Inner hair cells (3,500 hair cells pitch determination) activity
Action Potential – Is the result of synchronous activity of the auditory nerve fibers. All or none response of auditory nerve fibers

Cochlear Microphonic - Alternating currents due to hair cell depolarization. Closely resembles the sound stimulus, and mainly originates from the Outer hair cells (12,000 cochlear amplifier) .

 

To find out more about Cochlear microphonic, Inner Hair cells and Outer hair cells refer to slides 23-25 in Hearing and the Ear lecture on Wednesday 10th May.

- Decrease in NaCl solution 

- Vasoconstriction in the afferent arteriole and vasodilation in the efferent arteriole

Explanation: The lateral sulcus (also called Sylvian fissure or lateral fissure) is one of the most prominent structures of the human brain.

Question: Which of the following Cranial Nerves do NOT emerge from the Medulla Oblongata in the brainstem?
Explanation:
The middle four cranial nerves originate from the pons:

  • trigeminal nerve (CN V)
  • abducens nerve (CN VI)
  • facial nerve (CN VII)
  • vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII)

The final four cranial nerves originate from the medulla oblongata:

 

  • glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX)
  • vagus nerve (CN X)
  • accessory nerve (CN XI)
  • hypoglossal nerve (CN XII)

The third and fourth cranial nerves originate from the midbrain: oculomotor nerve (CN III) trochlear nerve (CN IV)

Question: The _________________ is one of a pair of arteries on the brain that supplies oxygenated blood to most midline portions of the frontal lobes and superior medial parietal lobes. Therefore these arteries supply the areas of the brain responsible for sensation and movement of the feet because feet are most medial in both motor and sensory homunculus.
Explanation:
Middle Cerebral arteries : supply the lateral part of the brain like auditory cortex, hand movements and face sensation and movements

Posterior Cerebral arteries: supply the Primary visual cortex

Question: Cytochrome p450 enzymes are the most significant family of Phase I 'functionalisation' enzymes - they are responsible for which type of metabolism?
Explanation:
CYP enzymes carry out oxidative metabolism - and as a side note, the four types of reaction carried out by any Phase I enzymes are i) oxidation, ii) reduction, iii) de-esterification and iv) isomerisation (so esterification isn't a correct answer for any Phase I enzyme action).

 

 

See the Case 3 lecture by Dr Coffey on hepatic drug metabolism for more information on the cytochrome p450 family of enzymes.

Question: You are an F1 on placement in A&E when Mrs. M is rushed in suffering from severe septic shock. You think back to your time in med school and remember which drug administration is quickest. How do you administrate antibiotics to Mrs. M?

Intramuscularly: takes 0.5- 1 hour

Intrathecal administration (injection into spinal canal) is generally used less as it causes fits

Question: Penicillin is a common antibiotic that targets cell wall-synthesis. However, Penicillin has some ADRs (adverse drug reactions) such as allergic reactions thats means other antibiotics are used. What is the most common clinical alternative?

Mr Smith comes into your practice with his wife, and as the consultation progresses you notice a distinct yellow tinge to the whites of his eyes. When you ask to examine him his wife says she thought they'd turned yellow but that he wouldn't believe her or do anything about it.

 

The yellow colouration is probably caused by jaundice - but there are many types of jaundice and lots of causes for each of the different types. One cause of jaundice is pre-hepatic unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia - which of the following is a cause of this type of jaundice?
Explanation:
The answer is B, though all the answers are potential causes of a type of jaundice via hyperbilirubinaemia:

 

A: hepatic, unconjugated

B: pre-hepatic, unconjugated

C: hepatic, conjugated

D: post-hepatic, conjugated

E: hepatic, conjugated

 

Other causes of the same category of jaundice - pre-hepatic (and therefore unconjugated) hyperbilirubinaemia - include:

• Haemolysis (e.g.) Rhesus incompatibility at birth
• Autoimmune (rather than drug-induced) haemolytic anaemia
• Defects in RBC membranes
• Defects in haemoglobin production
• Defects of RBC metabolism

 

For more information on the causes of the various types of jaundice see the practical/workshop notes on liver disease and serum bilirubin.

Explanation: Vitamin K is needed to make 2, 7, 9 and 10

Question: Pemphigus is an autoimmune disease that results in blistering. It affects the skin and mucous membrane. What does it target?
Explanation: It attacks desmoglein which acts as a glue that attaches adjacent epidermal cells via the gap junctions. As a result of attach this 'glue' the epidermis sloughs off and causes blisters.

Question:
Warfarin was first used in 1948 as a rat poison. Since then it has become one of the most important drugs in modern medicine.

 

It indirectly stops the clotting cascade from functioning. 

 

 

Which clotting factors are affected by warfarin?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. Warfarin inhibits vitamin K, so anything that vitamin K synthesises will be affected by warfarin.

 

I remember this with a silly song "2, 7, 9, 10, Vitamin K; That's what we have learned today". 

 

(All of the other answers are made up)

Question: 65 year old Mr Dawson comes into your practice having just returned from a 2 week cruise where he crossed the Atlantic with his wife. The man complained of being 'sea sick' the entire time, a symptom which has gone on to persist for several days since returning to land. He can't walk in a straight line, complains of a head ache in the back of his head and frequently vomits. He is also hypertensive and on warfarin. You suspect that there has been a cerebellar haemorrhage resulting in a loss of control of balance. What functional division of the cerebellum is responsible for this?
Explanation:
Cerebrocerebellum – the largest division, formed by the lateral hemispheres. It is involved in planning movements and motor learning. It receives inputs from the cerebral cortex and pontine nuclei, and sends outputs to the thalamus and red nucleus. This area also regulates coordination of muscle activation and is important in visually guided movements.


Spinocerebellum – comprised of the vermis and intermediate zone of the cerebellar hemispheres. It is involved in regulating body movements by allowing for error correction. It also receives proprioceptive information.


Vestibulocerebellum – the functional equivalent to the flocculonodular lobe. It is involved in controlling balance and ocular reflexes, mainly fixation on a target. It receives inputs from the vestibular system, and sends outputs back to the vestibular nuclei.

 

D and E are made up.

Question: The left recurrent laryngeal nerve is found in the thorax as it loops behind the aorta. From which nerve does it originate?
Explanation: this nerve branches off of the vagus nerve ( left to be specific). This is a strange bit of anatomy as the nerve that supplies the larynx takes a very long winded path.

Question:
You're at a Snarky Puppy concert reminiscing the sounds that you heard on your gap year abroad. The funky bass pounds through your chest and you remember that loud concerts can cause hearing damage. 

 

    

 

What is the loudest volume likely to be heard at a concert?
Explanation: The correct answer is E. The loudest noise is likely to reach up to 140 dB, louder than a police siren. The average noise will be closer to 105 dB.
Tags: Ear Pathologies, Hearing, Hearing and Ear, Case 6

Question: Doorman Walder is brought into your practice regarding a potential brain lesion. As a child Walder was thought to have been kicked in the head by a horse. As such the only word that he is able to say is 'Hodor'. He otherwise appears to have comprehension of language, but just isn't able to express himself in a condition known as expressive aphasia. Which of the following regions is responsible for language expression in the brain?
Explanation:
Wernicke's area is the region responsible for the comprehension of language. Those with a lesion on this area are able to speak fluently, but they are unable to comprehend language. Often just forming meaningless sentences.

 

The prefrontal cortex is thought to be the area associated with executive function and behaviour moderation.

 

Broca's area is the area associated with expression of language. Expressive aphasia is also known as Broca's aphasia.

 

 

Hippocampus is said to be involved with the consolidation of short term memory into long term memory.

 

The spinocerebellum. Coordinates limb movements by receiving proprioception, visual and auditory input.
Tags: Brain, Case 6, Psychology, Regions of Brain

Question: A professional guitarist has noticed that he is finding it difficult to play his instrument and read his music at the same time. 'It's like I don't know where my fingers are on the fret board' he explains. Further exploration reveals that a plaque has formed in his posterior spinal artery resulting in ischaemia in the posterior columns of the spinal cord. You explain to him that this 'posterior cord syndrome' has resulted in a loss of proprioception and fine touch, hence why he is struggling to play the guitar. Which of the following dorsal columns is responsible for sending ascending fibres to the medulla regarding proprioception/fine touch for the upper limb?
Explanation:
Fasiculus cuneatus- Proprioception/fine touch for the upper limb. 

 

Fasiculus gracilis- Proprioception/fine touch for the lower limb, memory aid (the gracilis is a muscle of the thigh).

 

Spinothalamic tract- is a sensory pathway from the skin to the thalamus

 

Spinocerebellar tract- This tract conveys information to the cerebellum about lengthand tension of muscle fibers

 

Corticospinal tract- Anterior Corticospinal Tract responsible for the control of the proximal musculature.

Lateral Corticospinal Tract responsible for the control of the distal musculature fine control of movements of the hand

Roger Bannister completed the first recorded 4-minute mile in 1954 (no. 329 in the photo below)

 

 

When the heart works harder there is an increase in blood flow via the coronary arteries. Below are values for normal coronary flow, and during vigorous exercise (during a race, for example). Which pair is correct?

Question:
As the exam season gets underway, you start to notice your Instagram feed filling up with 'summer throwback' photos. Your friend Oscar is posting about his trip to Aiya Napa last year, captioning his photo "Best summer of my life!"

 

You know that Oscar is experiencing episodic memory. 

 

    

 

Which larger category of memories are episodic memories?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. Declarative memory is split into semantic and episodic memories. It is defined as "memory with a conscious recall".

 

A, B and C are the three components of working memory, which is short term. 

E is long term memory, but without conscious recall. This includes procedural memory (eg. muscle-memory) and classically conditioned memory (eg. phobias).

Question:
Your elderly neighbour has started to complain that when they do the gardening or are going up a hill they often have to take a break - they can feel a tight, crushing pain in their chest for a few minutes. They're always relieved when it goes away, but it sounds like they have stable angina. Stable angina can be managed acutely or prophylactically, via different drugs with different actions.

 

Which of the following stable angina drugs does not involve manipulation of Ca2+ channels?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A: beta-adrenoceptor antagonists. Though some of the other drugs mentioned have more than a simple effect on Ca2+ channels, manipulation of the channels features in their methods of action.

 

A - Beta-adrenoceptor antagonists ('beta blockers'): one of the most common prophylactic stable angina drugs. Has negative ionotropic and chronotropic effects by preventing the action of adrenaline/noradrenaline. That stops the increase of supply/demand to the heart and therefore decrease the chance of exertional ischaemia.

 

B - Nicorandil: a vasodilator that stimulates guanylyl cyclase to increase levels of cGMP and decrease Ca2+ entry into vascular smooth muscle cells

 

C - Organic nitrate spray: there are various steps to NO spray activity:

i) activation of guanylyl cyclase in the vascular smooth muscle cells

ii) increased cGMP activating protein kinase G

iii) protein kinase G activity preventing Ca2+ entry into smooth muscle cells

iv) lack of Ca2+ entry allowing the coronary vessels to dilate

 

NB: nitrate spray is the only acute treatment covered here - all the rest are prophylactic.

 

D - Calcium channel blockers (CCB's): says it all the name to be honest. L-type voltage gated channels usually allow Ca2+ entry but are blocked and the Ca2+ entry therefore regulated.

 

 

 

Another treatment option (prophylactic) in stable angina is ivabridine. Ivabridine is a rate limiter with an effect on mixed Na+/K+ channels in the SA node. It alters the 'funny current' and decreases pacemaker automaticity.

 

For any more information on this see Dr Coffey's lecture on management of patients with stable angina.

Question: MHC (major histocompatibility complex) or HLA (human leukocyte antigen) diversity involves multiple genes (primarily three MHC Class I genes, A, B, and C and three MHC Class II genes, DQ, DP and DR) on which human chromosome?
Explanation:
MHC or HLA diversity involves multiple genes (primarily three MHC Class I genes, A, B, and C and three MHC Class II genes, DQ, DP and DR) on human chromosome 6 whereby extensive variation or polymorphism is found at each MHC gene in Man.

 

MHC genes are the most polymorphic genes in our genome-each allelic variant of each MHC protein differs the others by up to 20 amino acids.

 

(This info + more can be found on the extra info version of the PCS2 applied immunology tutorial booklet)

Question: what cytokines are released by endothelial cells?
OptionA: TNF-alpha, IL-1B, IL-6, IL-8, IL-10, HIF, VEGF
OptionC: TNF-alpha, IL-1B, IL-2, IL-6, IL-10, HIF, VEGF
Explanation:
A = Monocytes/macrophages

B = Endothelial cells (and T cells)

C = Fibroblasts

 

Information from Acute Immunology recap plenary in Case 1.

 

Extra information:

 

  • In response to HIF (hypoxia-inducible factor) there needs to be an increased blood supply to the region, which can be brought about by TNFa, to produce the new vascular bed (neovascularisation).
  • Vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), originally known as vascular permeability factor (VPF), is a signal protein produced by cells that stimulates vasculogenesis and angiogenesis

Question: What do T-helper cells require for activation?
Explanation: T-helper cells activate other effector cells/T-cytotoxic/B cells/macrophages. Requires peptide antigens with MHC II for activation.

Question:
You're sat in Bute park, enjoying the sun at a picnic with your friends. However, you're annoyed at the flies surrounding you and hovering over your fruit salad. The flies clearly feel that they are deficient in your food.

What are flies deficient in Toll susceptible to?
Explanation: TLRs are part of an evolutionary conserved systemm. Flies deficient in Toll are susceptible to fungal infections- by virtue of failing to express AMP's (antimicrobial peptides), including drosomycin.

Question: What do the consequences of systemic bacterial infection by gram negative bacteria include?
Explanation:
Gram -ve bacteria has a lipopolysaccharide layer (as opposed to thick proteoglycan), so can penetrate cell walls more easily, and get into cells without initiating an immune response. 

Therefore more likely to lead to sepsis (causing low blood pressure and abnormalities in cellular metabolism) than infection with a gram +ve bacteria.

Question: Which of the following is NOT part of inflammatory mechanism of COPD?
OptionA: Macrophage activation which leads to release of cytokines that recruit neutrophils and monocytes which differentiate into more macrophages and release more cytokines. Macrophage also activates proteases (MMP and elastases which breaks the elastic walls of the alveoli).
OptionB: Epithelial cells activation release more fibroblasts which release collagen and forms scar tissue, leading to airway obstruction
OptionC: CD4+ Th2-cell activation and expansion which recruit Eosinophils (which releases cytotoxic proteins) and B cells to secrete IgE.
OptionD: CD8+ cytotoxic T-cell Recruitment which leads to alveolar destruction
OptionE: Damage to mucociliary escalator, which increases the susceptibility to infection.
Explanation: C : Atopic Asthma

Question:
Toll like receptors are being targeted therapeutically in the form of new vaccination adjuvants (enhances the body's immune response) or with inhibitors that are designed to be anti-inflammatory. 

Imiquimoid is a new drug used to treat genital warts. What is it's mechanism of action?
Explanation:
Imiquimoid is found to be antiviral and used to treat genital warts. Stimulates TLR-7. 

 

(Applied immunology tutorial)

Question: Which of the following best describes the anti-inflammatory therapeutics in COPD?
Explanation:
A= Asthma

B=  Anti-oxidants e.g. glutathione and Anti-proteases e.g. α-1-antitrypsin .  Host tissues use anti-oxidants and anti-proteases to prevent tissue damage

C= Cystic Fibrosis

D=  COPD

E= made up

 

Source: Inflammation and Lung Disease Plenary

Question:
TNF-alpha is able to act upon the local endothelium to make it leaky, thereby allowing the entry of blood plasma containing complement proteins.

TNF-alpha release also results in the upregulation of adhesion receptors on the endothelial cell, what is this purpose?
OptionB: Decreases the susceptibility to bacterial infection, and can lead to cell lysis
OptionC: Permits the binding and extravasation of blood neutrophils
OptionD: Allows binding and activation of PRR's, including the toll-like receptors
Explanation:
The resulting oedema and entry of neutrophils contributes to an inflammatory state. The complement activation product C5a also contributes to this inflammation.

 

(Rest of the answers just made up from other molecules and actions of the membrane attack complex and the basis of inflammation).

Question:
Mrs Harrison is a 64-year-old caucasian woman that presents at your GP practice with skeletal weakness and instability. She is a known smoker and has visited your practice in the past for advice on how to manage symptoms of menopause. 

 

Due to her decrease in height since her initial appointment, you decide to carry out a DEXA test. Her T-score is -1.5.

 

What is her likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Despite symptoms and risk factors associated to Osteoporosis, Mrs Harrison is likely to be suffering from osteopaenia due to her T-score.

 

Osteopaenia is defined as an abnormally low protein and mineral content within bones at a less severe level than osteoporosis. 

 

T-score between -1 and -2.5 = osteopaenia

T-score below -2.5 = osteoporosis.

Question: A tendon exhibits elasticity. This graph represents a hysteresis loop and the elongation of a tendon is affected by the load, but why doesn't the tendon have the same amount of stretching as recoil?
OptionA: There is metaplasia of the elastic fibres when a tendon is stretched
OptionC: Elastic recoil takes less energy than stretching

Question: Which of the following is NOT  a form on Enthesopathies that affects the enthesis in tendons?
Explanation:
Enthesis is the connective tissue between tendons and bones of which there are two types:

- Fibrous 

-Fibrocartilaginous 

They create a smooth attachment from soft to hard bone by the insertion of the tendon fibres at right angles. Hence an enthesopathy refers to a disorder involving the attachment of a tendon or ligament to a bone.

OptionA: von willebrand factor, factor V and XII
Explanation:
A) Alpha granules

B) Delta granules

3) Lambda granules

Question: which of the following is a polymorphonuclear leukocyte

Meet Billy, he had a nasty accident with a chain saw and badly cut his arm. Billy is a clevel fellow and began to wonder about the maturation phase of wound healing as he watched his own wound heal

 

But what happens in the maturation phase?
OptionA: Fibroblasts are recruited to the site of injury which recruit more oxygen to supply the area with nutrients
OptionB: Epithelium forms in the process called epithelization
OptionC: Collagen type III fibres are converted to type I collagen fibres and the collagen becomes increasingly organised
OptionD: Neutrophils are recruited to the site followed by macrophages
Explanation: The maturation phase usually takes place between 21 days- 2 years and involves the remodelling of the collagen fibres as well as a reduction in cellular activity and an increase in oxygen levels.

Question: What is the function of a Th-17 helper cell?
OptionA: Rlease IFN and cytokines that activates macrophages and B-cells
OptionB: Release IL-4,5 & 13 to cause mast cell activation and IgE production
OptionC: Release cytokines 17 and 22 that cause neutrophil and monocyte activation for inflammation

Which cyclin exists in the highest concentration during the G1 phase of the cell cycle?
Explanation:
G1 - Cyclin D

Tags: PCS 2, PCS2, Cell Cycle, Cell replication

Question:
Your grandfather comes to you for health advice, assuming that you can sort out all of his problems. He just vomited, and noticed large amounts of blood in his vomit.

 

He is in a lot of pain and is very pale and lightheaded. He doesn't drink alcohol and hadn't vomited in years until just now. You know he is overweight and has diabetes. 

 

    

 

What is your grandfather most likely to have presented with?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. Your grandfather likely has ruptured oesophageal varices and needs urgent hospital treatment.

 

Oesophageal varices are caused by portal hypertension, usually as a result of cirrhosis. Your grandfather's cirrhosis is due to Non-Alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease, which has obesity and diabetes as risk factors. Cirrhosis increases the resistance for the portal vein, so back-pressure builds and the small veins in the oesophagus become stretched and pressurised.

 

If these varices rupture, it can be very dangerous. 

 

A: Oesophageal cancer is likely to be less painful and suddenly onset. It is more likely to cause dysphagia and extended heartburn. 

B: Correct

C: Mallory-Weiss tears can appear very similar to ruptured varices, but are less serious. They are a result of persistent vomiting, usually due to alcohol consumption. Because your grandfather has only vomited once, it is unlikely to be a Mallory-Weiss tear. 
D & E: The anaemia that your grandfather has presented with it normocytic anaemia. The blood cells themselves do not have a pathology, but there is significant blood loss causing the pallor and lightheadedness.
Tags: Alcohol, Anaemia, Oesophagus anatomy, Blood, Case 3

Question:
Jennifer is a 40 year old lady who visits your GP surgery complaining of pain in a strange place. 

She has recently had gallstones and is concerned that she may have another problem because of the new pain. You reassure her that the pain is a complication of the gallstones, and should eventually disappear on its own. 

    


Where is Jennifer likely to be experiencing pain?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. The gallbladder has increased in size and pressed on the diaphragm, causing an infection and referred pain in the C5 region. This includes the right shoulder tip. 

 

A: This can be a referral of pain due to angina or an MI. 

B: Referred pain from the stomach can act here.

C: Loin to groin pain is often due to the kidney or ureter.

D: Correct

E: Right Iliac Fossa pain is commonly due to appendicitis.

Question:
The compound bilirubin is named as a combination of "bili-" and "ruber", meaning "The red substance in bile". It is, however, yellow. It is responsible for jaundice as well as the yellow coloration of bruises. Bilirubin is produced when certain cells are broken down at the end of their lifespan. 

 

    

 

Which cells break down to eventually produce bilirubin?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. Erythrocytes, or red blood cells, release haemoglobin when they are broken down. Haem proteins are salvaged and are catabolised into porphyrin, then biliverdin and eventually bilirubin. 

 

None of the other cells listed contain haemoglobin.
Tags: Bilirubin, Case 3, Cell Specialisation, Cells, Cellular Function

Question:
Vitamin B3, also known as Niacin, is important in hydrogen transfer in oxidation phosphorylation as it forms NAD/NAPD

 

Deficiency of B3 results in which condition?
Explanation:
A) Pellegra- Pellagra is a vitamin deficiency disease most frequently caused by a chronic lack of niacin. It is classically described by "the four Ds": diarrhea, dermatitis, dementia, death. It develops according to several mechanisms, classically as a result of niacin (vitamin B3) deficiency, which results in decreased NAD production.

 

B)Korsakoffs- . Korsakoff syndrome is a chronic memory disorder caused by severe deficiency of thiamine (vitamin B-1). Korsakoff syndrome is most commonly caused by alcohol misuse, but certain other conditions also can cause the syndrome.It is a manifestation of Wernicke's encephalopathy observed in long-term abusers of alcohol

 

C) Nyctalopia-  Night blindness (nyctalopia) is the inability to see well at night or in poor light and is often because of a vitamin A deficiency 

 

D) Abetalipoproteinemia- Abetalipoproteinemia, or Bassen-Kornzweig syndrome, is a rare autosomal recessive disorder that interferes with the normal absorption of fat and fat-soluble vitamins from food

 

E) ariboflavinosis-  a deficiency disease due to inadequate intake of riboflavin and characterized by sores on the mouth

Question: In digestion and absorption, fat soluble vitamins are processed similarly to fats, whereas water soluble vitamins (not including B12) use diffusion or carrier mediated transport. Which of the following is a water soluble vitamin?
Explanation:
Fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, K – use same pathway as fat absorption

Water-soluble vitamins – use diffusion or carrier mediated transport

Eg Vit B1 (thiamine) & Vit C (ascorbic acid) use Na+-dependent carriers

Question: How do endogenous opioids, such as endorphins, modulate pain?
OptionB: They induce the release of inhibitory neurotransmitters such as acetylcholine
OptionC: They block the post synaptic receptors of the pain neuron
OptionD: They prevent the release of excitatory neurotransmitters such as substance P
Explanation: Opioids bind to their receptors and prevent substance P release. Substance P is an excitatory neurotransmitter which, with glutamate, transmits pain information to the CNS.

Question: Which area of the brain is involved in declarative memory and not non-declarative memory?
Explanation:
It is the medial temporal lobe which is involved in declarative memory, specifically episodic (personal episodes in time and space).

Both declarative and non-declarative come under long term memory.

In hippocampal amnesia it is usually the declarative memory which is affected, whilst the non-declarative is spared.

There is a really good summary table showing this at the end of the Dr Thanasi Hassoulas memory lecture.

Question: Which of the following is not an adaptation to aid absorption In the GI system?
Explanation:
To aid in digestion and absorption, the small intestine mucosa is highly folded

  • Large circular folds called plicae circulares , most numerous in the upper part of the small intestine
  • Smaller folds called villi, which are finger like mucosal projections, about 1mm long.
  • The lining columnar epithelial cells have fine projections on their apical surfaces called microvilli.

The gastric rugae allow for stretch of the stomach allowing for churning of the food as well as absortion of some substances such as alcohol.

 

Between the villi there are crypts, called crypts of Lieberkuhn, which extend down to the muscularis mucosae. These crypts are short glands.
Tags: Digestion, Digestion and Absorption, PCS 2, PCS2, Cell Specialisation

Question: What is the endothelium?
OptionC: Epithelial cells which line the blood vessels.
OptionD: A single layer of epithelial cells which lines the heart, blood vessels and lymphatic vessels.
Explanation:
The SBA is D.

All other answers are correct, but do not contain enough detail.

 

(Source: Case 4 Endothelial Cell Function lecture)

Question:
Mary comes into your GP practice complaining of shoulder pain and on examination she is unable to shrug her shoulders. 

 

which nerve is most likely to be damaged?
Explanation: Axillary nerve damage leads to the wasting away of the deltoid muscle which means an individual is unable to shrug there shoulders and they cannot abduct there arm beyond 15 degrees.

Question: Which of the following is Not a disease caused by prions?
Explanation:
Bovine spongiform encephalopathy - Bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), commonly known as mad cow disease, is a transmissible spongiform encephalopathy and fatal neurodegenerative disease in cattle that causes a spongiform degeneration of the brain and spinal cord

 

Creutzfedtl-jakobs disease- Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease (CJD) is an incurable, and universally fatal neurodegenerative disease in humans. CJD is at times called the human form of mad cow disease (bovine spongiform encephalopathy or BSE) but only Variant Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease (vCJD) is acquired from BSE

 

Scrapie- Scrapie is a fatal, degenerative disease that affects the nervous systems of sheep and goats. It is one of several transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs), which are related to bovine spongiform encephalopathy 

 

Mucocutaneous candidiasis-  Chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis (CMC) refers to a heterogeneous group of disorders characterized by recurrent or persistent superficial infections of the skin, mucous membranes, and nails with Candida organisms, usually Candida albicans.

Question: Which of the following is not an essential amino acid?
Explanation: Essential fatty acids are ones that cannot be made by the body so must come from food, there are 9

Question: Which of these is not an immune privileged site?
Explanation:
Immune privileged sites are parts of the body that are able to tolerate antigens without eliciting an inflammatory immune response.

They include the brain, placenta, eye and testis.

 

The prostate is a difficult target for antibiotics, but is not an immune privileged site.

 

- Antibiotic lecture.

Question: What are tropic hormones?
OptionA: Hormones which act directly on tissues, e.g. Growth Hormone
OptionB: Hormones which are secreted from the posterior pituitary gland.
OptionC: Hormones which stimulate other endocrine glands to secrete hormones, e.g. FSH
OptionD: Hormones which are only secreted from the pituitary gland.
Explanation:
The anterior pituitary gland secretes both tropic and non-tropic hormones.
Tropic hormones stimulate other endocrine glands to secrete hormones.
The anterior pituitary gland secretes 4 tropic hormones.
These can be remembered by the acronym FLAT: Follicle-stimulating hormone, Luteinising hormone, Adrenocorticotropic Hormone and Thyroid Stimulating hormone.
Non-tropic hormones act directly on tissues.
These include 2 non-tropic hormones which can be remembered by the acronym PeG: - Prolactin acts direct on mammary glands. - Growth hormone acts direct on bones, skeletal muscle and liver.

The Renal artery drains into the abdominal aorta at L1/L2

 

The uterine artery/ testicular artery passes over the ureter. Bridgeover troubledwater.

Explanation: The gubernaculum has two vestigial remnants in females, the ovarian ligament and the round ligament of the uterus (ligamentum teres uteri) which respectively serve to support the ovaries and uterus in the pelvis.

Question: How does penicillin work?
OptionA: It inhibits the penicillin Binding Protein which is involved in the crosslinking of the peptidoglycan cell wall
OptionB: It activates macrophages to phagocytose the pathogen
OptionC: It directly breaks down the NAM and NAG components of the cell wall
OptionD: Penicillin contains the penicillin binding protein which digests the peptidoglycan cell wall
OptionE: Penicillin penetrates the bacterial cell wall and inhibits protien synthesis
Explanation:
A is correct

 

B - Nope

 

C - NAM and NAG are components of the peptidoglycan cell wall, but the penicillin prevents the CROSSLINKING of individual NAM and NAG chains as opposed to breaking down the NAM and NAG

 

D = The Penicilin Binding Protein is the protein that the BACTERIA has which catalyses the crosslinking within the peptidolglycan cell wall. Penicillin actually INHIBITS this protein

 

E = Nope. Penicillin cannot penetrate the cell membrane --> it is polar

The brachial artery gives rise to the _______________: the deep artery of the arm. It travels along the posterior surface of the humerus, running in the radial groove
Explanation:
• The brachial artery gives rise to the profunda brachii – the deep artery of the arm. It travels along the posterior surface of the humerus, running in the radial groove
  • The brachial artery descends down the arm immediately posterior to the median nerve. As it crosses the cubital fossa, underneath the brachialis muscle, the brachial artery terminates by bifurcating into the radial and ulnar arteries.
  • In the hand, the ulnar and radial arteries interconnect to form two arches, from which branches to the digits emerge.

Question: Which of the following is NOT a partition of dura mater ?
Explanation:
Dural partitions separate different parts of the brain. They are formed when the internal meningeal layer of the dura mater folds away from the external periosteal layer. There are several dural partitions within the cranial cavity and they include:

  • Falx cerebri
  • Tentorium cerebelli
  • Falx cerebelli
  • Diaphragma sellae

Question: Which of the following is the least common cause of Amnesia?
Explanation:
Post_menopause: Even though it is the lest likely cause of amnesia, it is still important. The hippocampus is known to be directly affected by estrogen. estrogen increases “synaptic density” — the number of connections to other nerve cells — in the hippocampus especially.

 

HIV: Difficulties with memory, thinking and reasoning (aspects of cognition) are common with HIV, but they are usually mild and dementia is much rarer. Before the use of antiretroviral drugs (medication that helps to control HIV), around 20-30 per cent of people with advanced HIV infection previously developed dementia. This figure has now decreased to around 2 per cent

 

Alcohol: Alcohol-related brain damage (ARBD) is a brain disorder caused by regularly drinking too much alcohol over several years. The term ARBD covers several different conditions including Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome and alcoholic dementia. None of these is actually a dementia, but they may share similar symptoms. However, in contrast to common causes of dementia such as Alzheimer's disease, most people with ARBD who receive good support and remain alcohol-free make a full or partial recovery. In addition, there is a good possibility that their condition will not worsen.

 

Alzheimer's disease is the most common cause of dementia. The word dementia describes a set of symptoms that can include memory loss and difficulties with thinking, problem-solving or language. These symptoms occur when the brain is damaged by certain diseases, including Alzheimer's disease. Alzheimer's is a progressive disease. This means that gradually, over time, more parts of the brain are damaged. As this happens, more symptoms develop. They also become more severe.

 

Temporal Lobe Surgery: Henry Molaison 

 

 

 other common causes are:

 

stroke

certain medications

tumors

seizures

 

http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/amnesia/basics/causes/con-20033182
