Question:
A 19-year-old medical student presents with pain and swelling at the base of his right thumb. He reports an amorous encounter on a MedSoc social with a fellow medical student, with whom he returned to his halls of residence. Due to the narrow beds, alcohol excess and obscure mid-coital positioning he fell onto his extended wrist, which resulted in severe pain.  

There is exquisite tenderness on palpation of the anatomical snuff box of his right wrist. He is told by the doctor that his wrist x-ray shows a fracture of a carpal bone.

 

Which bone is most likely to be fractured?
Explanation:
The scaphoid is the most commonly fractured carpal bone. The usual mechanism of injury is a fall onto an extended wrist, typical history and examination findings include: pain and swelling at the base of the thumb and tenderness on palpation of the anatomical snuff box*.

 

The history of presenting complaint in this question is reminiscent of a mnemonic for remembering the carpal bones: Some Lovers Try Positions That They Can't Handle  = Scaphoid Lunate Triquetrum Pisiform Trapezium Trapezoid Capitate Hamate. 

 

*the anatomical snuff box is the depression between the extensor pollicis longus and extensor pollicis brevis tendons at the base of the thumb. This recess is so named for it's use of holding snuff (ground tobacco) prior to nasal insufflation. 

 

Jason

Question:
You are presented with a patient that has suffered from a direct blow to the middle part of the lateral side of his left leg. His X-rays show a midshaft fibula fracture of the left leg. He's unable to evert his lef foot and also complains about loss of sensation over the dorsum of the foot with the exception of the area between the great/first toe and second toe (first web space/ interdigital cleft) and the lateral side of the fifth digit. 

What nerve has been injured?
Explanation:
The answer is Superficial Fibular nerve. Here's why:

 

 

The 1st hint was the inability to evert the foot. The muscles responsible for foot eversion are: Fibularis longus and Fibularis brevis. These two muscles are supplied by the superficial fibular nerve. At this point you might be thinking "Hold on! What about Fibularis tertius?!" Well fibularis tertius only aids in the everting of the foot. It's primary function is ankle dorsiflexion (it's supplied by deep fibular nerve).

 

The 2nd hint is the loss of sensation. So it says he lost sensation over the dorsum of his left foot with the exception of the lateral side of the fifth digit and the first interdigital cleft. The first interdigital cleft is supplied by the deep fibular nerve and the lateral side of the fifth digit is supplied by the sural nerve. The rest (i.e. majority of dosrum surface) is supplied by the superficial fibular nerve, so here again you should be thinking "something's wrong with the superficial nerve."  (this link shows you the foot dermatomes, in case you're a bit lost: http://www.frca.co.uk/images/lowerlimb-fig8-small.jpg)

 

Now you can look back at the fact that his fracture is located at the midshaft of his fibula; what runs close along it there? The superficial fibular nerve!

 

Here's another link that talks a bit about superficial fibular nerve and potential damage: http://teachmeanatomy.info/lower-limb/nerves/superficial-fibular-nerve/

 

Another way of working this out is by ruling out answers:

1) The medial plantar, is a the larger branch of the tibial nerve, while the later plantar is the smaller branch. they both supply the skin of the plantar surface of the foot. Just look at their name: medial plantar, lateral plantar. The patient however suffers from loss of sensation on the dorsal surface!

2) As for the Saphenous nerve, it supplies the skin on the medial side of the foot as far as the head of the first metatarsal. It has no contribution to foot eversion. So it can't be this nerve.

3) Deep Fibular nerve doesn't contribute to foot eversion, but dorsiflexion and extension of the toes. It also supplies the skin at the first interdigital cleft, an area that the patient hasn't lost sensation in. So again it can't be this nerve.

 This leaves us with superficial fibular nerve as the only answer :)

 

*Additional info:

Something you might find interesting is that the deep fibular nerve injury causes a foot drop!
Tags: Foot, Anatomy, Innervation, Innervations, Lower Limb

Question: Which two complement proteins are largely responsible for mast cell degranulation in the process of acute inflammation?
Explanation: When complement C3b binds to a microbial surface, it can join  with other complement (i.e factor Bb  in the alternative pathway) to form  a C3 convertase, converting more C3 into C3a and C3b. When the C3b binds another complement, C5 then the C3 convertase is able to cleave C5 into C5a and C5b. The C3a and C5a then go on to cause Mast Cell degranulation.

Question: The function of the anterior cruciate ligament is ?
OptionA: To prevent external rotation of the leg.
OptionB: To prevent internal rotation of the leg.
Explanation: The anterior cruciate ligament attaches the anterior part of the tibial plateau to the femur. It therefore prevents anterior tibial translation. If the anterior cruciate ligament is damaged a positive anterior drawer test is seen. This is where the tibia is pulled forward anteriorly with the knee fully flexed. In a positive test a greater range of movement in this plane is observed.

Question: Why is prothrombin a better measure of liver failure than albumin?
OptionA: Because prothrombin has a higher molecular weight (in daltons).
OptionB: Because prothrombin has a shorter half life.
OptionC: Because the liver synthesises more prothrombin than albumin.
OptionD: Because the albumin is "busy" trying to transport the unconjugated bilirubin into the liver.
OptionE: Because the albumin can be redistributed into the extracellular space during infection.
Explanation: The answer is B. The half life of albumin is 20-25 days compared to Prothrombin which is around 60 hours. This means that with an acute liver problem the albumin concentration is still normal as the half life is so long. However, with an acute liver disease the prothrombin levels with be noticeably lower sooner as the liver can't produce the clotting factor and the molecules that were already in the system start to reach their half life sooner.

Question: What represents atrial repolarisation in a normal ECG (recorded with the limb leads)?
OptionD: It isn't - it's actually masked by the QRS complex
Explanation:
The P wave reflects the atrial depolarisation, QRS complex corresponds to ventricular depolarisation and the T wave is the ventricular repolarisation.

Atrial repolarisation occurs during the ventricular depolarisation, and is therefore masked by the QRS complex.

      Human Physiology, Pocock and Richards, 4th Ed., pp. 394
Tags: The ECG, Cardiology, Cardiovascular Physiology, Heart, Human physiology

Question: Asking a patient to shrug their shoulders against resistance as part of a cranial nerve examination is testing which cranial nerve?
Explanation: Asking the patient to shrug against resistance is testing the trapezius muscle which is innervated by the accessory nerve. Another test would be to ask the patient to turn their head against resistance as this tests the Sternocleidomastoid muscle which is again innervated by the accessory nerve.

Question: Timothy is 16 years old, he visits his GP to discuss treatment for his acne vulgaris. Which structure, labelled 'A' in the diagram, is responsible for Timothy's condition?
Explanation:
"Sebaceous glands are compound alveolar glands based on their histology. Sebaceous glands are holocrine glands based on what they secrete, because they secrete entire cells! Once a cell is secreted, it finds itself in a pore, no longer surrounded by its normal environment. The new environment is disturbing to the cell, so it lyses and its contents leak out. This leaked out mixture of cell contents, cell membranes, and disruptive environment fluids (a fatty mixture) is then called sebum, and it is what gets to the surface of the skin.

Sebaceous glands secrete their sebum into hair follicles. The sebum then escapes to the surface of the skin through the same route that the hair uses-- out the follicle. This oily fluid on our skin helps to further protect our skin, coating it with a hydrophobic armor to keep out water and maintain our internal fluids.

Pimples and acne are troubles of the sebaceous glands. These occur when the sebaceous glands get clogged, by either sebum or cells, as too much secretion occurs."

 

http://faculty.stcc.edu/AandP/AP/AP1pages/Units1to4/skin/skin2.htm

Question:
A patient with a pituitary adenoma has bitemporal hemianopia.

 

 

Which structure is the tumour likely to be compressing to cause this?

One of the adductor group of muscles in the leg is relatively weak and can be removed without noticeable loss of its function in the leg. For this reason this muscle, or part of it, can be removed and used to replace a damaged forearm muscle or a non functioning external anal sphincter among other things. This muscle is supplied by the obturator nerve and is the only adductor in the medial compartment that assists in medial rotation. It is the only adductor that does not attach to the femur. What muscle is this?
Explanation:
Sartorius is not an adductor. It is an anterior compartment muscles that assists in abduction. 

Obturator Externus is not an adductor although it is in the medial compartment. 

Adductor Brevis and adductor longus are both adductors but neither is involved in medial rotation and both attach to the femur.

Question:
Trevor is diagnosed with Marfan syndrome. The doctor explains that Marfan syndrome is caused by a defective gene encoding the protein fibrillin. Fibrillin co-polymerises with elastin to form elastic fibres in connective tissue. 

 

Which structure is most likely to cause Trevor problems?
Explanation: The walls of major blood vessels contain elastic connective tissue to help recoil. Patients with Marfan syndrome are unable to form normal elastic fibres causing weakening of aortic walls; this can lead to conditions such as aortic dissection, aortic regurgitation and aortic aneurysm.

Question:
Calcium is removed from heart muscle cells against its concentration gradient using the Na+/Ca2+ antiport exchanger; this is an example of secondary active transport powered by Na+ (i.e. sodium moves into the cell, down its concentration gradient. This powers the movement of calcium out of the cell, against its concentration gradient).

 

Polly is prescribed digoxin. Digoxin is steroid molecule which inhibits the Na+/K+-ATPase antiport exchanger. 

 

What is the most likely effect of digoxin on Polly's heart?
Explanation:
Digoxin is used to treat atrial fibrillation 

 

If the Na+/K+-ATPase pump is inhibited then Na+ can't be pumped out of the cell.

 

This leads to an intracellular build up of sodium.

 

This means the concentration gradient of sodium used to pump calcium out of the heart cell is dissipated. 

 

Since calcium cannot be removed from the cell by secondary active transport, it builds up inside the cell. This means more calcium binds to troponin and facilitates cardiac muscle contraction.

Question: Samantha is a first year medical student on placement at a local eye clinic. At the start of the day she notices David in the waiting room who is shown below. From initial inspection, Samantha suspects that David has...
Explanation:
From the picture we can see that David has:

 

- a dilated pupil in his right eye.

- ptosis of his right eyelid.

- a depressed, abducted, laterally rotated right pupil.

 

This combination of signs suggests that he has occulomotor nerve palsy (CN III palsy) for the following reasons:

 

First, the occulomotor nerve has sympathetic fibres which innervate the levator palpebrae superiosis muscle responsible for raising the eyelid. If thiere is a lesion to this nerve, ptosis will occur due to unopposed action of the orbicularis occuli muscle innervated by the facial nerve (CN VII). 

 

The occulomotor nerve also supplies parasympathetic fibres to the pupillary sphincter muscle which constricts the pupil. If there is a lesion to CN III, the unopposed action of sympathetic fibres to the pupillary dilator muscle will cause the pupil to dilate.

 

Thirdly, the occulomotor nerve innervates superior rectus, medial rectus, inferior rectus and inferior oblique. If there is a lesion to this nerve then there will be unopposed action to superior oblique (innervated by CN IV) and lateral rectus (innervated by CN VI). As a result the pupil will be abducted, depressed and laterally rotated.

 

*Note: although answer E is also correct, since this is the single best answer, answer B is better since it explains all of the signs.

Question: Niall wakes up after a big night at the LASH and feels very dehydrated. The secretion of which hormone will most likely be increased as a result of Niall's dehydration?
Explanation:
• ADH is the right answer- it is secreted by the posterior pituitary gland in response to increased plasma osmolality- i.e plasma being more concentrated
  • ADH is responsible for increasing the permeability of the last third of the distal tubule and the whole of the collecting duct to water, therefore more water is reabsorbed
  • Aldosterone secretion is regulated by the macula densa; aldosterone increases reabsorption of sodium 
  • ANP is secreted by atrial myocytes and is responsible for increasing sodium excretion and causing dilatation of the renal afferent and efferent arterioles, thus augmenting renal blood flow and GFR. ANP inhibits the formation of aldosterone and secretion of ADH

Question: Mr Smith has come in to his GP surgery for an annual check up. After taking a thorough history and completing a chest examination it is thought that he is suffering from mitral valve stenosis. Where would this be best heard upon auscultation?
Explanation:
The auscultatory areas are:

 

Aortic Valve = Parasternal Right 2nd intercostal space.

Pulmonary Valve = Parasternal Left 2nd intercostal space.

Tricuspid Valve = Parasternal Left 4th Intercostal space

Mitral Valve = Midclavicular Line Left 5th intercostal space

Question: Which nerve of the brachial plexus illustrated below, is most likely to be damaged by a fracture to the neck of the humerus?
Explanation: The answer is 12, the Axillary nerve which is most likely damaged in a fracture of this kind.

Question:
A surgeon is performing a cholecystectomy and accidentally tears the cystic artery, which causes uncontrolled bleeding. To reduce the bleeding she places her index finger inside the omental bursa (through the omental foramen) and her thumb on it's anterior surface and compresses the vessels in between. 

 

Which vessel is the surgeon most likely compressing to control the bleeding?
Explanation: This is known as the Pringle manoeuvre, named after James Pringle. The cystic artery is a branch of the right hepatic artery which is a branch of the (common) hepatic artery. Therefore by compressing the hepatic artery in anterior aspect of the omental foramen (AKA foramen of Winslow) the surgeon is able to stop blood flow to the cystic artery.

Question: A patient has pain in the epigastric region. The patient tells you that it is a chronic condition. He has lost his appetite and lost weight. He drank alcohol last night which exacerbated the pain. He was recently diagnosed with diabetes and has come in today looking slightly jaundiced. What is the mostly likely diagnosis?
Explanation: Chronic pancreatitis is normally alcohol related (60-80%). It can causes episodic or unremitting pain. The pain can be exacerbated by alcohol. When abdo pain is present anorexia and weight loss are common. Due to exocrine/ endocrine insufficiency malabsorption and diabetes may be present. The fibrosed head of the pancreas can also obstruct the common bile duct and result in jaundice.

Question: Which number on this pressure-volume loop represents the closure of the aortic valve?
Explanation:
1 = mitral valve closure.

2 = aortic valve opens. 

3 = aortic valve closes.

4 = mitral valve opens.

Question: A child weighs 34 pounds requires and intramuscular injection of a drug. The paediatric form of the drug is supplied in an ampoule containing 2mg in 1mL sterile saline. The label states that the required dose is 1mg per kg body weight (1kg = 2.2 pounds). What volume (to the nearest 0.1mL) should be injected?
Explanation:
The mass of the child is 15.45kg which means that he needs 15.45 mg of the drug.

This is divided by 2 as there are 2mg of drug per 1ml --> 7.7mg needed.

 

From: Additional maths example questions C21 2013-14 document.

Question: A patient is referred to you from his GP. He is a 39 year old non smoker that the GP suspects of having COPD. When you take the patient's history you find out that the patient has a productive cough and produces sputum daily and has been suffering from these symptoms for years. His reports frequent exacerbations. He says that he always quite breathless and occasionally coughs up blood. You suspect that the patient is not suffering from COPD and carry out a chest Xray and high resolution CT. Although the Xray is abnormal it is only with the CT that you confirm your diagnosis. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Bronchiectasis presents with a cough that normally produces sputum daily. There is often breathlessness, haemoptysis occurs in half of patients and chest pain in some. This condition should be suspected in patients that produce daily sputum, those of a young age at presentation, symptoms over many years, non smokers and those thought to COPD who don't smoke or have frequent exacerbations. 

 

A - Pneumonia wouldn't cause symptoms for years

C- TB symptoms: productive cough, weight loss, fatigue, fever, night sweats and haemoptysis. TB has these systemic effects (fever, night sweats which are worse at night) that bronchiectasis doesn't except in exacerbation. 

D- PF would result in a dry cough

E- Emphysema is included in COPD

Question: Which cells are responsible for myelinating neurons in the central nervous system?
Explanation: Oligodendrocytes are the equivalent of Schwann cells in the CNS, they are responsible for providing myelin insulation. However unlike Schwann cells each oligodendrocyte is capable of myelinating multiple axons.
Tags: Anatomy, Case 6, Central Nervous System, neuroscience

Question: From the ovary to uterus, which of the following options correctly describes the ordered arrangement of the sections of uterine/Fallopian tube?
Explanation:
1. Infundibulum- funnel shaped opening which collects oocytes using ciliated fimbrae
  2. Ampulla- widest section and the normal site of fertilization
  3. Isthmus- connects ampulla to uterine section
  4. Uterine- lined with ciliated and secretory cells which act to waft the oocyte and deliver nutrients

Question: The angiotensis-renin system is used to regulate BP and Na+ concentration in the blood. Which of these statements it true?
OptionA: Angiotensin I is converted to Angiotensin II in the kidney by Renin
OptionB: Angiotensin I is converted to Angiotensin II by ACE in the kidney
OptionC: Angiotensinogen is converted to angiontensin I by ACE in the lungs
OptionD: Angiotensin I is converted to Angiotensin II by ACE in the lungs
OptionE: Angiotensinogen is converted to Angiontensin II by Renin in the lungs
Explanation:
Renin is produced in the kidney through renal sympathetic activity, decreased blood pressure detected in the renal system at the juxtaglomerular cells or through decreased Na+ delivery to the macula densa. Angiotensinogen is converted to angiotensin I by renin, AI has no biological function and serves as a precursor for AII. AI converted to AII by ACE, angiotensin converting enzyme, primarily found in the lung.

 

A - Incorrect as it is by ACE in the lungs


B - Incorrect, takes place in the lung

 

C - Incorrect, converted by Renin

 

D - Correct! Well done, gold star for you!

 

E - Angiotensinogen is converted to Angiotensin I by Renin

Question: Political party leader, Nigal Forage*, may be suffering from the early stages of dementia. Which of the following is a symptom of this condition?
OptionA: Memory loss, such as about what he has said in previous interviews
OptionB: Problems with language, finding trouble to find the right word to call someone or how to describe a country.
OptionC: Disorientation to time and place, seemingly believing he is 100 years in the past
Explanation:
*name changed to avoid leaking personal details of patient

 

All of the above is the correct answer, early symptoms of dementia include:

Memory loss

Difficulty performing familiar tasks

Problems with language

Disorientation to time and place

Poor or decreased judgement

Problems with keeping track of things

Misplacing things

Changes in mood or behaviour

Changes in personality

Loss of initiative

Question:
The comic book hero, The Flash, is able to run at super speed and for very long distances. However, the average comic book reader (Figure 1.) is less gifted and will usually have to stop running due to a build up of lactic acid in the muscles. Carbon dioxide is another biproduct of respiration that builds up in the circulation causing a change in the Haemoglobin Dissocation Curve. What is this change?

 

(Figure 1. Artistic interpretation of Comic Book reader)
Explanation: The curve will shift to the right, meaning that at any given pO2 there is an increased amount of dissociation meaning that muscles are supplied with as much oxygen as possible and CO2 is removed, maintaining aerobic respiration for as long as possible!

Question: It's a cold friday evening in an A&E department, you're the only doctor in the hospital and you're finishing a 250 hour shift. A patient comes in with a suspected occlusion of a cerebral artery. They present with a numbness and paralysis in their left leg and foot. Which cerebral artery is likely to be occluded?
Explanation:
It is the anterior artery as it supplies the medial aspects of the parietal and frontal lobes which includes the leg motor area of the cerebral cortex. It is the right sided artery as the motor areas act contralaterally i.e. the right area controls the left leg. 

 

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_cerebral_artery

Stepping on Lego (Figure 1.) is widely considered the most painful experience in the world, though to understand why it hurts so much, first we need to understand nociception. What are the fibres that are responsible for the initial sharp pain sensation, and what are their characteristics?

 

(Figure 1. Blue piece of Lego)
OptionA:
Alpha fibres

 Simple naked nerve ending
 Low threshold mechanoreceptor
 Responds to light mechanical stimulus
 Thinly myelinated axon
OptionB:
Alpha fibres

 Simple naked nerve ending

 High threshold mechanoreceptor
 Responds to intense mechanical stimulus
 Thickly myelinated axon
OptionC:
Alpha fibres

 Simple naked nerve ending
 High threshold mechanoreceptor
 Responds to intense mechanical stimulus
 Thinly myelinated axon
OptionD:
C fibres

Question:
Still mourning his bad luck in bacterial Heaven, Billy the Bacterium is suddenly approached by a (similarly dead) lady bacterium!

 

Belinda the Bacterium: "Hey baby. I was just minding my own business when out of nowhere I got killed by the complement system! No antibodies or MBL bound to me. What do you think happened?"

 

Belinda the Bacterium: "Oh and by the way, nice flagellum!"

 

What should Billy do?
OptionA: Impress Belinda by explaining that the alternative complement pathway occurred, due to the spontaneous formation of a membrane attack complex, leading to her untimely demise.
OptionB: Impress Belinda by explaining that the alternative complement pathway occurred, due to the spontaneous activation of MASP-1 and MASP-2, leading to her untimely demise.
OptionC: Impress Belinda by explaining that the alternative complement pathway occurred, due to the spontaneous activation of C1q, leading to her untimely demise.
OptionD: Impress Belinda by explaining that the alternative complement pathway occurred, due to the spontaneous formation of C3a and C3b from C3, leading to her untimely demise.
OptionE: Impress Belinda by making a lame joke, thanking her for her "complement".
Explanation: The alternative complement cascade activates when C3a and C3b spontaneously form from C3. This happens most quickly at the surfaces of invading bacteria and fungi. Host cells can prevent this at their surfaces.

Question:
A new way of diagnosing a disease is being tested. Scientists want to assess its validity by working out its specificity and sensitivity. 

 

180 people were tested using this new diagnostic method. Of these 60 tested positive and of these 60, 37 had the disease that was being tested for. In the whole sample of 180 people, 48 had the disease that was being tested for. 

 

What is the sensitivity of this new method of diagnosis?
Explanation:
Sensitivity = proportion of people with the disease that test positive for it. 

 

Sensitivity = (number of people with positive test result that have the disease) / (total number of patients in the sample that have the disease)

 

Sensitivity = 37/48 = 0.77

Question:
During an infection by a bunch of nasty viruses, one brave little somatic cell (amongst the many others) was targeted, but decided to face them head-on, by ingesting and processing the viruses. It managed to produce some viral fragments, but was still infected and knew it had to die, so now, it wants to attract a cytotoxic T cell to assist in its suicide.

 

HOWEVER, being an inexperienced little cell, it's kind of clueless about how to achieve so. It's panicking and needs advice immediately, what would you recommend it to do?

 

#cellwelfareisimportant
OptionA: Express integrin receptors complexed with the viral fragments on its surface.
OptionB: Secrete the viral fragments and also chemoattractants to signal cytotoxic T cells to come.
OptionC: Express MHC I molecules complexed with the viral fragments on its surface.
OptionD: Express MHC II molecules complexed with the viral fragments on its surface.
OptionE: Any of the above will do, as T cytotoxic cells can recognise the viral fragments through its pattern recognition receptors.
Explanation:
A - the concept of expressing the viral fragment in some way is correct. However, integrins are mostly functional as cell-to-cell or cell-to-ECM adhesion molecules and definitely not T-cytotoxic cell specific receptors.

 

B - This would be the case for attracting leukocytes to the site of inflammation/infection by endothelial cells and the such, not in this case.

 

C - CORRECT ANSWER: cytotoxic T cells recognise MHC-I:peptide complexes on target cells through its T-cell-receptor and CD8 receptor complex. This interaction will activate cytotoxic T cells to induce the granzyme/perforin pathway, or the death receptor pathway that results in the apoptosis of the target (infected) cell.

 

D - MHC II are (almost) exclusively expressed on antigen-presenting cells, not infected target cells. Plus, cytotoxic T cells don't recognise these receptors and their complexes!

 

E - no way if you want to specifically attract those cytotoxic T cells! Plus, pattern recognition receptors are unique receptors expressed by the cells of the innate immune system, which the T cells are not really specialised to do!
Tags: Adaptive Immunity, T cells, PCS, Cell signalling, Immunology

Question:
Viral hepatitis is a global health problem caused by five different viruses: Hepatitis A, B, C, D and E. Though hepatitis B is not the most common it is sometimes chronic and has a lower rate of resolution than some of the other hepatitis infections.

 

Which of the following is a useful preventative measure against hepatitis B infections?
OptionB: Vaccinating individuals in specifically sewage works and residential institutions
OptionD: Improving food & water hygiene/sanitation and hand washing
Explanation:
The answer is A - HBsAg is an active vaccination against Hepatitis B. HBIG is another valid vaccination but it is passive rather than active, and is more commonly given post-exposure than as a preventative measure.

 

Since Hepatitis B is a blood borne virus the emphasis in prevention should be on i) those coming into contact with blood and ii) any individuals at higher risk of infection:

  • healthcare workers
  • drug users
  • CLD or CKD patients
  • HIV patients
  • those about to travel in higher prevalence areas

Answers B and D are more focused on those coming into contact with food and water borne hepatitis - both Hepatitis A & E are more commonly transmitted this way.

 

For more information see the Case 3 lecture on global perspectives on viral liver disease

- Drooping of his right upper eyelid

- Downward and outward gaze in his right eye

Explanation:
Answer is C as the Oculomotor Nerve supplies the superior, inferior and medial rectus, levator palpebrae superioris and the inferior oblique. It also supplies parasympathetic innervation to ciliary muscles and causes pupil constriction.

- Drooping of his right upper eyelid as the levator palpebrae superioris elevates the upper eye lid

- Left eye looking straight as his lesion is most likely only supplying the right half of his face

 

Ptosis is the clinical name for drooping of the upper eye lid, however because of the other signs that this patient has presented with, oculomotor nerve palsy is the best answer.

Question:
A 48 year old women visits her GP complaining of a fluttery feeling in her chest. The doctor takes a full history and decides to prescribe atenolol (25 mg OD).

One month later the patient comes in for a follow-up and the GP advises that she gradually reduce the dose of atenolol. Why can't she simply stop taking the drug immediately?
OptionA: Atenolol causes bronchoconstriction by blocking beta-2 adrenoreceptors. Stopping the dose suddenly will lead to bronchodilation, rendering the mucociliary escalator dysfunctional. This results in an inability to clear mucus and chronic lower respiratory tract infection.
OptionB: Atenolol increases heart rate. If it is stopped suddenly heart rate will quickly decrease and the patient will go into cardiac arrest.
OptionC:
The body responds to atenolol by up-regulating the number of beta adrenoceptors to
compensate for those that are blocked. Slowly reducing the dose/frequency of taking the drug allows the body to re-equilibrate itself gently and reduces the rebound effects caused by too much adrenaline / noradrenaline binding.
OptionD: The body responds to atenolol by up-regulating the number of L-type calcium channels to compensate for those that are blocked. Slowly reducing the dose/frequency of taking the drug allows the body to re-equilibrate itself gently and reduces the rebound effects caused by too much calcium binding.
Explanation:
The correct answer is C

The body responds to beta blocker drugs by up-regulating the number of beta adrenoceptors to
compensate for those that are blocked. If the atenolol is abruptly stopped it means ALL the receptors are
now available to be activated by adrenaline and noradrenaline which can have a serious rebound effect
for the patient’s original symptoms. Slowly reducing the dose/frequency of taking the drug allows the
body to re-equilibrate itself gently and reduces the rebound effects.

 

Material taken from cardiac drugs workshop, PCS 3.
Tags: Drugs, Drugs for Heart, PCS 3, PCS Unit 3, PCS3

Question: Which one of these is  a pathophysiological factor which will increase afterload?

Question:
An 81-year-old man goes to the GP complaining of his hearing. From the history, you gather that his hearing has been getting worse over the years. Examination with an otoscope reveals nothing abnormal, and the Rinne test gives a positive result for both ears.

 

You suspect sensorineural deafness. 

 

Which of the following is the most likely cause?
OptionA: An acoustic neuroma (leading to compression of the cochlear nerve)
Explanation:
Answer: C Degeneration of the Organ of Corti

Answer A (acoustic neuroma)

An acoustic neuroma (or vestibular schwannoma) is a rare, slow-growing, benign tumour of the vestibular nerve, which can lead to the compression of surrounding structures, including the cochlear nerve. This can therefore present as sensorineural deafness. Although this is also a possibility, it is rarer and likely to present as asymmetric hearing loss (giving a Rinne negative).

 

Answer B (perforated eardrum)

This is unlikely given the gradual onset of the hearing loss. Perforated ear drums may arise from trauma or chronic middle ear disease (ie recurrent infection), and are a type of conductive hearing loss. An examination with an otoscope would pick up on a perforated eardrum.

 

Answer C (degeneration of the Organ of Corti

Also called presbycusis, this is the most common cause of deafness, typically seen in old age. The reasons include loss of outer hair cells, loss of the ganglion cells, strial atrophy, or a mix of these. Environmental loud noises over the years may lead to this (rather than age itself).

 

Answer D (earwax)

Impacted earwax (cerumen) is a type of conductive hearing loss, and would be noticed with the otoscope.

 

Answer E (otosclerosis)

Otosclerosis is a disorder where new bony deposits occur within the ossicles, specifically stapes and the cochlea. The type of hearing loss may therefore be mixed. From the history, it is a possibility, but less likely as otosclerosis is often hereditary.

 

 

Rinne and Weber tests

  • always done together
  • using a tuning fork
  • used to differentiate between conductive and sensorineural deafness
  • Rinne's: normally, the tuning fork will be heard louder if held next to the ear, rather than on the mastoid bone = positive Rinne. If it's louder on the mastoid, this indicates conductive deafness = negative Rinne.
  • Weber's: in someone with normal hearing, the sound would be perceived centrally. If it is heard louder in the right ear, for example, this suggests either conductive hearing loss in the right ear and/or sensorineural loss in the opposite (left) ear.
Tags: Ear, Ear Pathologies, Ear physiology, Organ of Corti, Hearing

Question:
A lady comes into your practice complaining of facial hair starting to grow. You suspect that she may have an enlarged pituitary gland, producing excessive hormones. 

 

She tells you that she has been worried about her sight, and upon examination you find that her field of vision is reduced. 

 

    

   

Which is the most likely visual field of the lady?
OptionA: Bitemporal hemianopia
OptionB: Quadrantanopia
OptionC: Homonymous hemianopia
OptionD: Binasal hemianopia
OptionE: Blind in one eye
Explanation:
The correct answer is A - Bliateral hemianopia. The pituitary tumour presses on the optic chiasm, causing compression of the optic nerve.

 

Light that hits the retina medially has come from a lateral point on the field of vision. Information from the medial retina enters the optic chiasm, so this information will often be lost in a pituitary tumour. 

  

 

B: A lesion in the optic radiation

C: A larger lesion in the optic radiation that stops both branches of the nerve transmitting information.

D: A much rarer condition, a single lesion is very unlikely to cause this. An enlarged 3rd ventricle can compress the sides of the optic chiasm and cause D.

E: Often caused by trauma, or a lesion between the retina and the optic chiasm.
Tags: Nerve, Nerves, Case 6, Cranial Nerves, Vision

Question: Group 10: A woman has just given birth in hospital and is bleeding profusely. She refuses to be operated on by a male doctor, however the only on-call doctor is male. You explain that what she is doing could result in her dying and she clearly understands and is competent. Which of the 5 principles of capacity is most relevant to this situation?
OptionA: 1: 'A person lacks capacity in relation to a matter if at the material time he is unable to make a decision for himself in relation to the matter because of an impairment of, or a disturbance in the functioning of, the mind or brain.'
OptionB: 2: 'A person must be assumed to have capacity unless it is established that he lacks capacity'
OptionC: 3: 'A person is not to be treated as unable to make a decision unless all practicable steps to help him do so have been taken without success'
OptionD: 4: 'A person is not to be treated as unable to make a decision merely because he makes an unwise decision'
OptionE: 5: 'Before the act is done, or the decision is made, regard must be had to whether the purpose for which it is needed can be as effectively achieved in a way that is less restrictive of the person’s rights and freedom of action'
Explanation: The decision is clearly very unwise but as a doctor you are unable to intervene. You cannot infer that she has lost capacity simply because the decision is unwise.

Question: What is the other name for vitamin B12? - Not to be confused with the Hip-Hop band D12.

Question:
You (dan) go to a football match with your lad friends from home to watch your favourite football team Neath FC. One of your friends shouts "NEATH NEATH NEATH" down your ear at the top of your lungs.

The next day you have a ringing and buzzing sensation in your ear. You then wonder why you are struggling to hear at frequency 4kHz. Why is this?

OptionB: it is close to the resonance frequency of the internal auditory canal so it is transmitted most efficiently to the eardrum

OptionD: it is close to the resonance frequency of the middle auditory canal so it is transmitted most efficiently to the eardrum

Explanation: The reason this band is lost is because it is close to the resonance frequency of the external auditory canal so that it is transmitted most efficiently to the eardrum. The mechanism isn’t properly understood.

Question: A lady comes into your clinic complaining of an itching and burning sensation of the genitals. She has a fishy smelling discharge and a 'strawberry cervix'. What is the most likely diagnosis
Explanation:
Stage 2 syphilis: Appearance of non-itchy rashes and sores on mucous membranes, fever, sore throat, patchy hair loss, headaches, weight loss, muscle aches, fatigue, swollen lymph glands

 

Chlamydia: Can be asymptomatic. can have a burning sensation when seeing (dysuria) and white discharge

 

Herpes: cold sores on genital region or face 

 

Gonorrhoea: urethritis, increased vaginal discharge, increased bleeding. Can cause Pelvic inflammatory disease

Question: Mr Jones is an 68 year old man who is visiting the GP with his son. His son is concerned that his father is becoming more forgetful and 'just hasn't been himself lately'. While taking his history, the GP discovers that Mr Jones had a stroke 6 months ago and has a strong family history of hypertension. What is the most likely cause of Mr Jones' presentation?
Explanation: The most correct answer is C- Vascular dementia. This is due to his vascular history of a past stroke as well as a family history of hypertension which are both risk factors for vascular dementia.

Question: An increase in Km while Vmax stays the same indicates what type of enzymatic inhibition?
Explanation: Competitive: Km increases as more substrate is needed to bind to the active sites (which are also competed for by the inhibitor). Unlike uncompetitive inhibition, increasing substrate concentration eventually overrides the effect of the competitive inhibitor.

Question: Gaucher's syndrome involves a mutation in the housekeeping gene coding for?
Explanation: Mutation in lysosomal glucocerebrosidase reduces its ability to break down glucocerebroside in RBC and WBC membranes so it accumulates, causing liver impairment, anaemia and neurological symptoms.

Question: What antibiotic is contra-indicated in children with growing bones?
Explanation: Oxytetracycline is a tetracycline antibiotic which chelates Ca2+ and deposits it in growing bones of children causing deformities.

Question: What antibiotic is associated with ototoxicity?

Question: Which of the following is not an effect of Angiotensin II release?

Question: Which of the following is not a sign of an Lower motor neurone lesion?
Which part of the brain generates the pattern/ rhythm of respiration?
Explanation:
The initial rhythm for breathing rate is generated in the medulla. This can then be modified by the higher centres of the brain which are under voluntary control. The higher centres send signals to the pons, which then can modify the rhythm that the medulla has generated. 

 

The breathing rate can be also be modified by signals from the peripheral chemoreceptors located in the aorta and the carotid bodies. 

 

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9j6BpanhpKY&t=309s - This video explains it quite nicely.

Question: What enzyme synthesises Acetylcholine?

Question: One late evening a year 1 medic was trawling through peerwise to get ahead for exams.  They came across numerous phd level questions and began to feel frustrated.  Rather than complaining in a more conventional manner, they decided to write a question of their own in a passive aggressive manner.

Question: 68 year old Mr Watson smokes regularly and has a history of unstable angina and high blood pressure. He suffered a stroke three months ago due to partial occlusion to his left middle cerebral artery. He has come to hospital as an outpatient to discuss the lasting effects of the stroke. Which of the following is an unlikely symptom?
OptionA: Inability to exert control over the movement (ataxia) of the right (contralateral) arm
OptionE: Aphasia (inability or impaired ability to produce or understand speech)
Explanation:
MCA is the most common site of ischemic stroke.

 

Middle cerebral artery supplies most of the sensory and motor gyri as well as Wernicke's are and Broca's area. Therefore ischemia of these parts of the brain can effect speech and motor and sensory function. (Lower limb function is more likely to be spared due to dual supply with anterior cerebral artery)

  • These effects are contralateral as the ischemia causes an upper motor neurone lesion before the corticospinal tract has decussated in the pyramids of the medulla 

 

The hippocampus in the medial temporal lobe is responsible for episodic memory and is supplied by the posterior cerebral artery.

Question: Complement activation consists of 3 pathways, one of which is the classical pathway. What is the trigger that activates this classical pathway?

Auto-activation is what activates the alternative pathway.

Question:
You are listening to Prince 'Kiss' through your Dr Dre beats (at a correct volume) and realise you can't hear his sweet sweet falcetto. 

Which frequency is the first to go in age related hearing loss?

Alan is one of your patients that you know has liver cirrhosis. You decide to examine him for a checkup and find that he has a palpable spleen. 


    
Why does splenomegaly occur in patients with liver cirrhosis?
OptionA: Fewer blood cells are filtered by the liver so the spleen compensates by increasing in size.
OptionB: Cirrhosis increases the risk of cancer occurring, which is commonly in the spleen.
OptionC: Cirrhosis has many of the same risk factors as thrombosis. Clots can form in the splenic vein and cause back pressure.

Explanation:
The correct answer is D. Portal hypertension means blood is at a higher pressure in the spleen and it increases in size. 

 

A, B, C and E are all made up.

Question: Which component of the SNARE complex is calcium sensitive?
Explanation:
Synaptotagmin is calcium sensitive. When calcium ions flood of the Smooth ER after an action potential reaches the presynaptic neurone, synaptotagmin causes the fusion of the vesicles to the membrane.

 

The other parts of the SNARE complex essentially hold the vesicles in place before an action potential reaches the synapse

Syncope is the act of fainting, vasovagal relates to the baroreceptor reflex that involves the integration of blood pressure with the nervous system.

Because the syncope (fainting) is caused by a sudden drop in blood pressure, C is the right answer, VASOVAGAL SYNCOPE.

Question: Philadelphia chromosome is a very important chromosomal defect, known to be present in >90% of chronic myeloid leukaemia cases. It is caused by the reciprocal translocation of which two chromosomes?

Reciprocal translocation is the exchange of material between non-homologous chromosomes. Philadelphia chromosome is made when this exchange occurs between chromosome 9 and chromosome 22.

Question:
You meet Dominic, a neurological patient. He can raise his eyebrows but has no nasolabial fold on the left side. He also shows significant mouth drooping on the left.

 

You recognise his condition as a facial nerve palsy. 

         

 

Which lesion is most likely to be causing Dominic's symptoms?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. A contralateral UMN will cause the lower 2/3 of the face to lose motor control, but not the upper 1/3. 

A: Bell's palsy is complete paralysis of half of the face. 

C: A left upper motor neurone lesion would have no effect, as the right can compensate. 

D: LMNs on the right would affect the right side of the face, as they have already decussated. 

E: A left LMN lesion would result in Bell's Palsy. The full face would be affected and Dominic would not be able to raise his eyebrows.

Question: Which mineral in high doses reduces the amount of copper which can be absorbed by the body?

Question:
Your little brother asks you to help him with his physics homework setting up an electrical circuit in series and parallel. This makes you think about the circulatory system and its structure.

 

You remember that while capillaries are in parallel to the 'circuit', the lungs are in series, making them susceptible to emboli. If a pulmonary embolism does occur, you know that the V:Q ratio will be abnormal.

 

  

 

What is the expected V:Q ratio when a pulmonary embolism has taken place?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. There is no perfusion due to a complete blockage, so dividing by zero gives infinity. 

 

A: Zero represents no air entering the lungs while perfusion is present, for example drowning.

C: One is a perfectly efficient ratio. 

B and D are intermediate values that I made up.
Tags: Case 5, Respiration, Respiratory, Respiratory Failure, Respiratory system

Question: Parasympathetic innervation of the eye causes...
OptionE: Contraction of the ciliary muscles which in turn tenses the suspensory ligaments, causing a short and fat lens
Explanation:
Radial muscles are innervated by Sympathetic fibres and cause pupil dilation

 

Parasympathetic innervation can also cause contraction of the ciliary muscles however this relaxes the suspensory ligaments, allowing the lens to become short and fat to focus on nearer objects

Question: What is tachyphylaxis?
Explanation:
Tachyphylaxis is a pharmacological term used to describe a drug's loss of potency.

It is often associated with long term (chronic) use that leads to an increased tolerance.


Example (management of stable angina)

Organic nitrates such as isosorbide mononitrate and glyceryl trinitrate are reduced to produce nitric oxide which induces vasodilation and therefore alleviates angina symptoms. Long-term use induces oxidative stress leading to subsequent bodily tolerance (and endothelial dysfunction) and therefore poorer therapeutic effect.

 

I believe this is also associated with cocaine use, the tachyphylaxis would result in users requiring higher doses with every use to achieve the same effect as previously ('chasing the high').

Question:
One of your patients, Jenny, has picked up a urinary tract infection while at hospital. You are worried that it is a complicated UTI because Jenny has a catheter inserted. You send away for a culture to determine the specific strain of organism causing Jenny's UTI. 

     

 

Which is the most common cause of a UTI?

Question: What is responsible for the brown pigment in poo?
Explanation:
Conjugated bilirubin in the intestine is oxdised by bacteria to urobilinogen. This is colourless. Urobilinogen is then further oxidsied to form stercobilin which is responsibile for the brown pigment.

 

If there is post-hepatic jaundice (obstructive) which prevents the conjugated bilirubin from reaching the intestine, this causes pale stools.

Question: Where is the macula densa found?
Explanation:
In the kidney, the macula densa is an area of closely packed specialized cells lining the wall of the cortical thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle, at the transition to the distal convoluted tubule.

 

The cells of the macula densa are sensitive to the concentration of sodium chloride in the distal convoluted tubule . A decrease in sodium chloride concentration initiates a signal from the macula densa that has two effects:

(1) it decreases resistance to blood flow in the afferent arterioles, which raises glomerular hydrostatic pressure and helps return GFR toward normal

(2) it increases renin release from the juxtaglomerular cells of the afferent and efferent arterioles, which are the major storage sites for renin

Question: Where is aldosterone produced?
Explanation:
Adrenal Medulla- produces adrenaline and noradrenaline 

Zona fasciculata- produces glucocorticoids such as Cortisol

Anterior Pituitary gland- produces FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Prolactin, Growth Hormone 

Posterior Pituitary gland- produced Oxytocin and ADH

Question: After having worked super hard all day you decide to go for a run in Bute park. All is going well until you go over on your ankle and have to hobble back to Taly. You are in pain, your ankle is swelling and you're frantically search through your draws for an anti-inflammatory drug. You eventually find some aspirin. What is the mode of action of Aspirin?

OptionB: It competes with arachidonic acid for the COX domain irreversibly
OptionE: It affects the perioxidase domain of PGHS2/3
Explanation:
A- ibuprofen 

E- paracetamol

Question: What is the function of the thalamus?
OptionA: Links the nervous and endocrine systems via the pituitary gland, controlling temperature, sleep, thirst and circadian rhythms.
OptionB: Produces melatonin from serotonin, involved in circadian rhythms.
OptionC: Processes and relays sensory information and is involved in wakefulness.
OptionD: Controls vision, hearing, temperature, sleep/awake state and motor control.
OptionE: Controls blood pressure, breathing and heart rate
Explanation:
The thalamus processes and relays sensory information (including pain) and is involved in wakefulness.

 

The hypothalamus links the nervous and endocrine systems via the pituitary gland, controlling temperature, sleep, thirst and circadian rhythms. It also secretes hormones.

The pineal gland produces melatonin from serotonin and is involved in circadian rhythms and sleep patterns.

The midbrain controls blood pressure, breathing and heart rate (ANS functions) as it contains the respiratory, cardiac and vomiting centres.

Question: You are working on A & E when an incident on an industrial site results in numerous casualties all suffering from similar wounds. As part of your treatment, you administer codeine to each of the patients in order to set them on the 'pain pyramid'. However, to your surprise, some of the patients demand stronger pain killers and are clearly in agony, whereas others are happy enough with the codeine you gave them initially. Which of the following best explains this?
OptionA: There will be individual variation in metabolism due to the different BMIs of the patients.
OptionB: The metabolism of the codeine is being altered by other drugs present in the system.
OptionC: Codeine is metabolised to morphine by the CYP2D6 enzyme. Expression of this the 2D6 gene varies between individuals and as such metabolism of this drug varies.
OptionD: Excretion of the drug varies between individuals.
OptionE: Absorption rates of the codeine may vary dependent upon the individual.
Explanation:
C- is correct, in the core formulary on learning central mentions in the MOA of opiates that genetic variation between individuals will affect the efficacy of codeine in certain individuals. Something to consider when in clinical practice. https://learningcentral.cf.ac.uk/bbcswebdav/pid-4216675-dt-content-rid-7361012_2/courses/1617-MEDIC-YR1-ADMIN/CORE%20FORMULARY%20August%202016%20%28final%29.pdf

 

The other options raise some interesting points. For a drug to reach a therapeutic dose you must consider the concentration of the drug in the individual. You will need to adjust the dose administered depending on the mass of the person. Factors affecting drug metabolism will also impact its efficacy, not only genetic, but also other drugs being metabolised as well as the state of the liver. However in this scenario, a clinician would account for body mass when administering the drug, hence A is discounted.   

 

Excretion of a drug by the time a drug is excreted, it has already been metabolised, therefore the rate of excretion shouldn't impact the therapeutic efficacy. Hence D is discounted. 

 

Absorption is also important for bio-availability, depending on the route of absorption will determine how much of the active drug enters the system. Again however, if the concentrations are the same, the time taken for maximum bioavailability might vary but not the therapeutic efficacy. Therefore E is discounted. 

 

Drugs can interfere the metabolism of one another when taken at the same time. However, in clinical practice, when taking a history of a patient it is important to check drug history for such contraindications. Although it is possible that some of the patients may be on other drugs which are interfering with the metabolism of codeine, it is less likely. 

 

On balance, this is an SBA and C provides the best explanation
Tags: PCS 3, PCS Unit 3, Case 1, PCS3, Pharmacology

Question: What innervates the sublingular gland?
OptionB: chorda tympani branch of the facial nerve
Explanation: Sublingular and submandibular glands are both innervated by the chorda tympani branch of the facial nerve (answer b), whereas the parotid gland is innervated by the glossopharyngeal PSNS fibres (answer A)

Question: A patient presents with a gram negative bacterial infection having being bitten by a fox in whilst on a walk in the countryside. You decide to target the cell wall of the bacteria by using a beta-lactam antibiotic. This is futile in stemming the infection. You discover that the bacteria produces beta-lactamase, as such you prescribe a different drug. Which of the following would you prescribe?
Explanation: Penicillin is the umbrella name for drugs which act against beta-lactam to interfere with the synthesis of bacterial cell wall peptidoglycan. All of the other options are ineffective due to the beta-lactamase. Co-amoxiclav contains clavulanic acid, this inhibits the action of beta-lactamase allowing for the amoxicillin to perform its usual role. For more information check out the formulary posted in learning central.

Question:
You are guzzling down your 10th VK of the night and take a peek at the ingredients. You notice the obvious culprit for your hangover, ethanol, but there are several other ingredients, one of which is a positive inotropic agent...caffeine. 

 

How does caffeine exert its positive inotropic effects?
OptionE: Increases conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II
Explanation:
Caffeine inhibits phosphodiesterase and so slows the enzymic inactivation of cAMP. 

This leads to the phosphorylation of L-type calcium channels by protein kinase A.

This phosphorylation prolongs the open time of the channels resulting in an increased influx of calcium during the action potential and a stronger concentration.

(Page 385 - Pocock)

Question:
Thinking back to your medic back to school night and you're playing drinking Jenga with you medic family and friends. After calling your mum and telling her you love her in front of everyone, you decide it's time for another drink. Long story short... you have a shot contest with your medic mum and end up in the alcohol treatment centre.

 

Acute alcohol intoxication effects what area of the brain most?
Explanation:
Despite having an impacting on the planning and judgement, alcohol has to largest effect on the cerebellum of movement and coordination.

Question: Which of the following is the correct order for the phases of nociception?
Explanation:
Transduction - exposure to noxious stimulus produces action potential

Transmission - travels along fibres from point of transduction to dorsal horn and subsequently to the brain

Perception - experience of discomfort, pain. Conscious, emotional, and subjective

Modulation - response to pain, facilitation or inhibition of nociceptive input

Question: What action does NO work by in the arterial smooth muscle?
OptionA: activates cAMP, which increases amount of PKA, decreasing calcium - causing relaxation
OptionB: activates cGMP, which increases amount of PKG, decreasing calcum - causing relaxation
OptionC: decreases cAMP, which decreases levels of PKA, increasing calcium - causing relaxation
OptionD: decreases cGMP, ehich decreases levels of PKG, increasing calcium - causing relaxation
OptionE: Activates Phospholipase C ,cleaving PIP2 into DAG and IP3. This causes increase in calcium - causing relaxation
Explanation: NO increases cGMP, which in turn increases the levels of PKG. This causes a decrease in calcium released so causes smoth muscle cells to relax, and causes vasodiation.

Question: What is the role of EDCF - Endothelium derived contracting factors?
OptionC: Produces prostanoids which cause contraction when there is impaired nitric oxide release - causing vasoconstricion
OptionD: Produces prostanoids which causes contraction when there is impaired nitric oxide release - causing vasodilation
Explanation:
Prostanoids including endoperoxides, prostacyclin, thromboxane A(2), and prostaglandin E(2) work to cause vasoconstriction.

 

B is the role of EDRF - endothelium derived relaxing factors

Question:
You are working in the Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast and get asked to screen someone for Hep B. There blood results come back as the following:

  • HbsAg - positive
  • Anti-HBc - positive
  • IgM anti-HBc - positive
  • anti-HBs - negative

What are the results in relation to hep B from these readings?
Explanation:
The presence of IgM shows that this patient is acutely infected instead of chronic.

The presence of the HBsAg shows that the person is infected - as this is the antigen from the invading particle.

The anti-HBc is the antibody for the core antigen and is present

The anti-HBs isn't present and this is the antibody for the antigen they are infected with.

 

<3 SB <3

Question:
PA = pressure in alveoli

Pa = pressure in arteries

Pv = pressure in veins

 

In which zone of the lung is the ratio Pa>PA>Pv?
Explanation:
Zone 1: PA>Pa>Pv

Zone 2: Pa>PA>Pv

Question: A man comes into clinic complaining of a dry and irritating cough. He is a 35 year old male teacher who has never smoked. On examination, he has finger clubbing, rapid and shallow breathing and cyanosis. His FEV:FVC ration is 0.9. What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The clinical symptoms indicate pulmonary fibrosis. The 'dry cough' would remove bronchiectasis from the diagnosis as bronchiectasis patients can produce up to a cup full of mucus daily.

 

Emphysema and Bronchitis would be surprising in a young man who does not smoke and is a teacher.

 

However ALL the alternative options above can be ruled out by the FEV:FVC ratio. <0.8 indicates obstructive disease and >0.8 indicates restrictive lung disease. Pulmonary fibrosis is the only restrictive lung disease in those options.

Question: A patient comes into your practice with a loss in his sense of smell. Further investigation reveals a lesion the DIENCEPHALON. Which of the following best describes the contents of the DIENCEPHALON ?
OptionA: Frontal lobe, parietal lobe, occipital lobe, temporal lobe.
Explanation:
A These are the lobes of the cerebrum. Embryological, this is known as the telencephalon

B These are the structures present in the brain stem. 

C These are the components of the corpus callosum 

D These are the structures of the diencephalon 

E These are the lobes that make up the cerebellum.

Question: A patient comes into your practice complaining of a tingling sensation in his right thumb and index finger. This is something that he has suffered from for nearly a year now. He says that every time he tries to pick something up, he experiences agony. You inspect his hand and observe no outside trauma. Further questioning reveals that he has type 1 diabetes. From this information, which category of pain best describes the symptoms described by this patient?
Explanation:
This is an example of non-nociceptive pain. Nociceptive pain arises from any actual or threatened damage to non-neural tissue and is due to activation of nociceptors. The examination excludes such damage, hence both somatic and visceral pain are ruled out. 

 

The patient describes that this pain has been present for nearly a year, hence this is chronic rather than acute. 

 

Therefore the pain much be neuropathic. Specifically, diabetic neuropathy. This comes about due to excessive glucose concentration in the blood stream, this can result in diabetic microvascular injury involving small blood vessels that supply nerves (vasa nervorum). In this case, the patient has a damaged median nerve. 

 

For more information on the classification of pain, review the 'Physiology and Psychology of Acute Pain and Analgesia 1' from case 1.

Question:
Obama is enjoying his leisurely break from the whitehouse so decide to order a takeaway. He is very hungry and while he impatiently waits for it his tummy rumbles. He is bored so gives it a google and finds that this is due to the action of ghrelin. 

 

 

 

 

What is the release stimuli for ghrelin?
OptionC: A mechanism by the lateral hypothalamus which increases feeding when bored
Explanation: Ghrelin is released from the endocrine cells in mucosa in the stomach, pancreas and small intestines when the body is fasting. It increases appetite by lowering energy expenditure through its action on hypothalamic feeding centers.

Question: Which of the following does not carry a risk of ototoxicity?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B - all the other drugs have the potential (though sometimes is only some individuals or at specific and very high doses) to cause damage to the ear.

 

A: Quinidine is an antimalarial drug which usually carries minimum risk - and ototoxicity from it is usually  reversible.

 

C: Aspirins can cause hearing problems, but only in very high doses (20-30 tablets a day) and is also reversible in effect.

 

D: Ibuprofen can cause ototoxicity but only in those patients which are sensitive - and again, it is reversible.

 

E: Gentamicin is an aminoglycoside antibiotic which can cause much more serious ototoxic effects, sometimes rendering patients completely deaf and leaving them with additional balance problems (from damage to the cells in the vestibular system) - the effects can also (unlike the others here) be irreversible.

 

 

source: Dr Watson's second lecture on the ear during Case 6 (unfortunately the image from his powerpoint with all the drugs doesn't compress well onto peerwise)
Tags: Drugs, Ear, Ear Pathologies, Anti-biotic, NSAIDs

Question: Trisomy 13 is the chromosomal abnormality that leads to which condition?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A.

Down Syndrome is a result of trisomy 21. 

Edwards syndrome is a result of trisomy 18. 

Cri du Chat syndrome is result of 46, XY, del(5p) - deletion of short arm of chromosome 5. 

Turner syndrome is a result of monosomy X.

Question:
There are many '2nd messengers' which are very important in the way cells respond to stimuli and communicate with each other; one of these is PIP3.  

PIP3 is produced by the phosphorylation of PIP2, found in the plasma membrane. What is responsible for the conversion of PIP3 back to its PIP2 form?
Explanation:
The answer is PTEN, which dephosphorylates PIP3 back to PIP2.  

PI3 kinase is the protein responsible for phosphorylating PIP2 to PIP3. 

Protein kinase B is one of the 2 main kinases activated by PIP3, the other being mTOR.  

Phospholipase C is the enzyme responsible for cleaving PIP2 in the plasma membrane to produce IP3 and DAG.  

Protein kinase C is a protein activated by DAG.
Tags: PCS 3, PCS Unit 3, PCS3, Cell Signaling

Question:
Waardenburg Syndrome is a genetic disease that affects ferrets as well as humans. It causes a white 'blaze' marking on the ferret's head, which was selectively bred for.

 

For this reason, many blaze ferrets show abnormal responses to stimuli. 


      


Using your knowledge of Waardenburg syndrome, what symptoms are likely to be seen in blaze ferrets?
OptionA: They don't respond to any visual stimuli.
OptionB: They cannot remember maze patterns that other ferrets can.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. Waardenburg syndrome affects the ability to hear, so many blaze and white headed ferrets are deaf. 

 

A: This option suggests that Waardenburg syndrome causes blindness, which is untrue. It can cause changes in the colour of the eyes, but vision is not affected.

B: This suggests that memory is impaired, but it is not. 

C: As with answer A, apart from the colour of the iris, the eyes tend not to be affected by Waardenberg Syndrome.

E: This is the opposite of the correct answer.
Tags: Ear, Ear Pathologies, Ear physiology, Hearing and Ear, Case 6

Question: "Adrenoceptor agonist that acts on the sympathetic nervous system. Causes mydriasis (dilation of pupil) and peripheral vasoconstriction (which leads to whitening of the sclera)" describes which of the following drugs?
Explanation:
Tetracaine- Local anaesthetic which works by blocking voltage gated Na+ channels. Causes loss of the corneal reflex.

Cocaine- Local anaesthetic and sympathomimetic. Causes mydriasis (dilation of pupil) by preventing noradrenaline re-uptake, peripheral vasoconstriction- whitening of the sclera and loss of corneal reflex.

Tropicamide- mACH receptor antagonist that blocks parasympathetic impulses, paralysing pupil constrictor response and ciliary muscle. (Not actively causing dilation, just preventing constriction)

Pilocarpine- mACH receptor agonist that causes marked pupil constrictor muscle contraction (miosis). It also acts to pull open the canal of Schlemm. Vasodilation of blood vessels gives the eye a blood shot appearance.
Tags: Drugs in eye practical, Drugs in eyes, PCS 3, PCS Unit 3, Pharmacology

OptionD: It sends signals to the hypothalamic feeding centres to suppress release of ghrelin and orexin
OptionE: It binds to ghrelin receptors, directly blocking it's mode of action
Explanation:
A- mechanism of leptin

C is the correct answer- PYY  is released from L cells in the gastric mucosa due to increased feeding and decreases appetite

Up until 1986, when children misbehaved in school, teachers used to be able to hit them on the back of a hand with a ruler.

What is this an example of?
Explanation:
Positive punishment: Giving something undesirable as the behaviour is bad

Negative punishment: Withholding something desirable as behaviour is bad

Positive reinforcement: Giving something desirable as behaviour is good

Negative reinforcement: Withholding something undesirable as behaviour is good

 

I remember these as:

-something is always given in positive

-if it is reinforcement, the behaviour is desirable

 

E is made up

Question: A patient comes into your practice having accidentally caught their hand in a door. As the door was closed, the trauma caused a displacement at the carpometacarpal joint articulating between the trapezium and first metacarpal bone. The nature of this joint allows for movement in two planes. Which of the following best describes this joint?
Explanation:
Pivot- a rounded process of bone fits into a body ligamentous socket, permitting rotation. Eg. atlanto-axial 

Ball and socket- Rounded head into a concavity permitting movement in several axis. E.g. hip 

Plane- Permit gliding. E.g. acromioclavicular.

Hinge- permits flexion and extension. e.g. elbow.

Saddle. Two saddle shaped heads allow for movement in two planes. E.g carpometacarpal 

Condyloid- flexion, extension, abduction, adduction and circumduction. E.g. metacarpophalangeal joint. 

 

For more see Moore's clinical anatomy. p16.
Tags: Bone, PCS 1, PCS Unit 1, PCS-1, Case 1

Question: A 21 year old woman comes into your practice for a routine vaccination before going on holiday to South America for 2 weeks. However, as your patient comes through the door she appears to be in quite some pain. She describes a sharp stabbing pain in her chest upon walking up the stairs. You begin to take a history of the patient to see if you can identify the source of the pain. She has no prior history of asthma and doesn't smoke. You perform a respiratory examination to find that upon auscultation of her thorax, you notice a sound similar to silk being rubbed together. Which of the following is the most likely explanation ?
Explanation:
During inspiration/ expiration the pleurae usually make no sound due to fluid in the pleural cavity providing a frictionless environment. Inflammation of the pleurae makes the surfaces rough resulting in a pleural rub.

 

Pulmonary collapse occurs when a sufficient amount of air enters the pleural cavity resulting in a loose of surface tension between the lung and the thoracic wall. 

 

Chylothorax occurs when lymph from a torn thoracic duct enters the pleural cavity. 

 

Pulmonary fibrosis occurs due to chronic inflammation resulting in the laying down of fibrous tissue. 

 

Pulmonary embolism, where a blood clot enters a pulmonary artery.

Question: Ependymal cells are cells that line the ventricular system in the brain. What type of cell are ependymal cells?
Explanation: Ependymal cells are ciliated cuboidal cells. The choroid plexus contains modified ependymal cells that produce CFS in the lateral ventricle

Question: The corpus callosum serves as a white matter tract which connects the left and right hemisphere. The anterior commissure is an aspect of the corpus callosum which connects which lobes to each other?
Explanation:
The corpus callosum connects the L+R cerebral hemispheres and ensures they don’t act independently. It is a band of white matter.
The anterior commissure is part of the corpus callosum that connects the temporal lobes.

 

The anterior commissure and the corpus callosum together are called the inter-hemispheric commissures.
Splenium is swollen because visual cortex is in occipital lobe.

 

 

Please refer to the anatomy practicals of case 6 for further details.

Question:
A young patient has presented in A&E after taking 10 tablets of 500mg paracetamol. You are concerned that this has caused overproduction of the toxic metabolite NAPBQI responsible for hepatocyte damage.

 

What do you administer to replenish glutathione to conjugate and detoxify the NAPBQI?
Explanation:
E) n-acytyl cystein should be administered intravenously to ensure that the toxic NAPBQI is deactivated. The quicker this can be done the better.

 

 

A) & D) are made up answers

 

B) CYP1A2 enzyme is responsible for the Phase I metabolism of paracetamol to from NAPBQI

 

C) Glucuronic acid is responsible for the conjugation of bilirubin to make it water soluable

Question: You visit a patient in the Coronary Care Unit. He has suffered a STEMI. His 12 lead ECG showed ST elevation in leads V1, V2, V3 and V4. Which coronary artery do you suspect was the site of the clot causing the MI?
Explanation: B is the correct answer. The LAD supplies the anterior and septal section of the heart so a clot resulting in ischemia in that artery could result in an anterior/septal STEMI. This would show ST elevation in leads V1, V2, V3, V4.
Tags: Cardiology, Heart, Coronary arteries, Coronary vessels

Question:
As a first year medical student, you are on your weekly placement and this week have been given the chance to play around with medical pen torches. You decide to shine the torch in the heavy, sleep-deprived eyes of one of your peers and realise that you stimulated the autonomic pupillary light reflex.

The response reminds you that in increased light, the pupil constricts, but it also gets you thinking. As you would expect, you begin to question which nuclei in the brainstem that the signals run to, following the pretectal nuclei in the midbrain. Which nuclei should you be thinking of?
Explanation:
The answer is A. 

Superior salivary nuclei involved in signals along CN VII involved in submandibular and sublingual salivary glands

Inferior salivary nuclei involved in signals along CN IX involved in parotid salivary glands. 

Nucleus ambiguus is involved in motor component of vagus nerve. 

Emboliform nuclei involved in system that regulates precision of limb movements.
Tags: Autonomic Nervous System, PCS 3, PCS Unit 3, PCS3

Question: Which hormone is released by enteroendocrine cells in response to partially digested fats during the intestinal phase?
Explanation:
Gastrin - secreted during the cephalic and gastric phase. It is released from the G cells of the pyloric glands in the pylorus of the stomach. It stimulates the gastric glands to produce hydrochloric acid and pepsinogen.

 

CCK - secreted during the intestinal phase in response to partially digested fats. It is secreted by enteroendocrine cells in the duodenum. It decreases gastric secretions by reducing the parietal cells sensitivity to gastrin.

 

Secretin - secreted during the intestinal phase by S cells in the duodenum. It inhibits the secretion of gastric acid by parietal cells, and it stimulates the production of bicarbonate.

 

Ghrelin - released when there are low blood glucose levels. It stimulate the appetite.

 

PYY - stimulated by high fat content following a meal. It is released from L cells in the lower small intestine. It inhibits gut motility which means that food stays in the stomach for longer, which increases satiety and leads to a decrease in appetite.

which one of these is not an area of narrowing of the ureters?
