Question:
Revision season has messed up your diet and you find yourself severely lacking in fibre. As you sit on the toilet wishing you'd eaten your bran flakes, you tense up your body to exert maximum defecation power. 

 

This action of breathing out against a closed glottis is called a Valsalva manoeuvre. It increases intrathoracic pressure, causing blood pressure to increase.

 

As a compensatory reflex, the heart rate slows.

 

 

What is the name of this compensatory reflex?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D, the baroreflex.

 

The baroreflex is when baroreceptors sense that blood pressure has increased. This causes a decrease of heart rate to compensate. In the Valsalva manoeuvre, blood pressure then decreases until release, then overshoots again causing tachycardia and feeling breathless after a big ol' push. 

 

This effect also happens in weightlifting and childbirth, for example.

 

I found out about this manoeuvre from Pocock pg 423 if you are interested!

Question: Which of the following receptors, when stimulated, causes an increase in the ventilation rate?
Explanation:
Proprioceptors are found in the joints and are triggered on movement, hence when the joints are moving the metabolic demand will be greater and as a result you want a greater ventilation rate.

Juxta-pulmonary receptors when stimulated are thought to limit the inflation of the lung.

Stretch receptors in the lung relay information back to limit inflation. They are thought to have an important role when a baby takes its first breath.

Irritant receptors trigger a cough.

The retrotrapezoid nucleus is the area in the medulla involved in expiration/ pre-inspiration.

Question: Which of the following statements about the effetcs of GIP and VIP are correct?
OptionA: Both VIP and GIP are stimulated by fatty chyme entering the duodenum
OptionB: Acts to decrease motility of the stomach by the meissner's ENS
OptionC: Acts to increase motility of the stomach by Auerbach's ENS
OptionD: Acts to increase motility of the stomach by Meissner's ENS
OptionE: Both act on G Gells to inhibit gastrin production.
Explanation:
Both VIP and GIP acts to increase the motility of the stomach via the ENS:

 

Meissner's = mucus secretion

Auerbach's = motility

 

VIP is stimulated by food entering the duodenum (distension of the wall). It acts to upregulate somatostatin production at the D cells.

 

GIP is stimulated by Fatty chyme entering the duodenum, and it is responsible for decreasing Gastrin secretion from G cells.
Tags: Digestion, Digestion and Absorption, Digestive system, PCS3, Case 3

Question: Fast forward 15 years - you've just started your million years of surgical training and have managed to accidentally have 3 children who you're neglecting in favour of your career. You turn around for 5 seconds and your youngest has ingested a whole tube of fluoride-containing toothpaste. What potentially harmful effect does fluoride have on the process of cellular respiration?
OptionA: Fluoride interferes with electron flow through complex IV of oxidative phosphorylation.
OptionB: Fluoride upregulates phosphofructokinase causing a build up of fructose-1,6-biphosphate.
OptionD: Fluoride inhibits electron flow through complex III of oxidative phospholylation.
OptionE: Fluoride prevents NADH being used in oxidative phosphorylation by inhibiting complex I.
Explanation:
A: This is the action of cyanide.

B: I just made that up, I don't know if anything actually does that.

C: Correct. Enolase is the enzyme used for step 9 of glycolysis. Can be lethal at extremely high doses.

D: This is the action of Antimycin.

E: This is the action of Amytal.
Tags: Aerobic Respiration, Metabolic pathways, Metabolism, Anaerobic Respiration, Glycolysis

Question:
A bright woman of 90, Natasha K., recently came to our clinic. Soon after her 88th birthday, she said, she noticed "a change." What sort of change? we queried.

"Delightful!" she exclaimed. "I thoroughly enjoyed it. I felt more energetic, more alive — I felt young once again. I took an interest in the young men. I started to feel, you might say, 'frisky' — yes frisky."

"This was a problem?"

"No, not at first. I felt well, extremely well — why should I think anything was the matter?"

"And then?"

"My friends started to worry. First they said, 'You look radiant — a new lease on life!,' but then they started to think it was not quite — appropriate. 'You were always so shy,' they said, 'and now you're a flirt. You giggle, you tell jokes — at your age, is that right?'"

"And how did you feel?"

"I was taken aback. I'd been carried along, and it didn't occur to me to question what was happening. But then I did. I said to myself, 'You're 89, Natasha, this has been going on for a year. You were always so temperate in feeling — and now this extravagance! You're an old woman, nearing the end. What could justify such a sudden euphoria?' And as soon as I thought of euphoria, things took on a new complexion… 'You're sick, my dear,' I said to myself. 'You're feeling too well, you have to be ill!'"

 

What do you diagnose Natasha with?
Explanation:
This extract is taken from 'The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat and Other Clinical Tales' - which is very interesting. Natasha has self-diagnosed herself with syphilis, which can go unnoticed at the time of contraction and cause neurological changes in it's later stages.

 

A) UTI - UTI's in older people are known to give delirium, but this would have likely presented more as confusion as opposed to behavioural changes

B) stroke in ACA - ACA supplies the frontal lobe, and so behavioural changes may well be observed. However, motor symptoms on the contralateral side of the stroke would also be observed. However, Phineas Gage had a frontal lobe injury and only had personality changes, so perhaps a minor stroke could also only cause personality changes.

C) Alzheimer's disease is caused by plaques and tangles, and effects memory most noticeably

E) An adrenal gland tumour could possibly increase levels of testosterone produced (which is responsible for sex drive), however there would be other symptoms present like Cushing's syndrome which is caused by prolonged exposure to cortisol (gives weight gain above  the neck, high blood pressure etc). 

 

Here is the rest of the extract, for those interested;

 

"Ill? Emotionally? Mentally ill?"

"No, not emotionally — physically ill. It was something in my body, my brain, that was making me high. And then I thought — goddam it, it's Cupid's Disease!"

"Cupid's Disease?" I echoed, blankly. I have never heard of the term before.

"Yes, Cupid's Disease — syphilis, you know. I was in a brothel in Salonika, nearly 70 years ago. I caught syphilis — lots of the girls had it — we called it 'Cupid's Disease.' My husband saved me, took me out, had it treated. That was years before penicillin, of course. Could it have caught up with me after all these years?"

There may be an immense latent period between the primary infection and the advent of neurosyphilis, especially if the primary infection has been suppressed, not eradicated. I had one patient, treated with Salvarsan by Ehrlich himself, who developed tabes dorsalis — one form of neurosyphilis — more than 50 years later.

But I had never heard of an interval of seventy years — nor of a self-diagnosis of syphilis mooted so calmly and clearly.

"That's an amazing suggestion," I replied after some thought. "It would have never occurred to me — but perhaps you are right."

She was right; the spinal fluid was positive, she did have neurosyphilis, it was indeed the spirochetes stimulating her ancient cerebral cortex. Now the question of treatment arose. But here another dilemma presented itself, propounded, with typical acuity, by Mrs. K herself.

"I don't know that I want it treated," she said. "I know it's an illness, but it's made me feel well. I've enjoyed it, I still enjoy it, I won't deny it. It's made me feel livelier, friskier, than I have in 20 years. It's been fun. But I know when a good thing goes to far, and stops being good. I've had thoughts, I've had impulses, I won't tell you, which are — well, embarrassing and silly. It was like being a little tiddly, a little tipsy, at first, but if it goes any further…"

She mimed a drooling, spastic dement. "I guessed I had Cupid's, that's why I came to you. I don't want it to get worse, that would be awful; but I don't want it cured — that would be just as bad. I wasn't fully alive until the wrigglies got me. Do you think you could keep it just as it is?"

We thought for a while, and our course, mercifully, was clear. We have given her penicillin, which has killed the spirochetes, but can do nothing to reverse the cerebral changes, the disinhibitions, they have caused.

And now Mrs. K. has it both ways, enjoying a mild disinhibition, a release of thought and impulse, without any threat to her self-control or further damage to her cortex. She hopes to live, thus reanimated, rejuvenated, to a hundred. "Funny thing," she says. "You've got to give it to Cupid."

Question:
a 28 year old male comes into your clinic. 

he says he and his wife are having trouble conceiving. 

 

you do some tests and see that LH and FSH levels are extremely high but testosterone and sperm count are low. 

 

what is your diagnosis?
Explanation: the high FSH and LH means that the pituitary and hypothalamus are sending the signals for testosterone to be formed and because it isn't, the levels keep rising as there is no negative feedback. a problem with the testes themselves means that it is primary hypogonadism. if the FSH and LH levels were low, it could be a problem higher up so iwith the pituitary gland or hypothalamus

Question: A 63 year old woman presents at your practice regarding her loss in appetite. She feels constantly bloated and says she feels 'pressure in her stomach', gesturing towards her lower abdomen. She feels an increasing urge to urinate and feels lethargic regardless of how much she sleeps. You conduct a bi-manual examination and palpate an enlarged ovary. You refer the patient to a gynecologist to have an ultrasound investigation. The ultrasound reveals an ovarian cancer. Which of the following regions of the ovary is the most likely site of origin for this ovarian cancer?
Explanation:
According to Dr Hannah Shaw's lecture in case 2 regarding the 'Normal reproductive physiology and anatomy', the site of 85-90% of ovarian cancers is the germinal epithelium. 'The majority of ovarian cancers originate from the germinal epithelium; but they can also develop from the germ cells themselves or the surrounding stroma'.

 

You will also notice that I said that the patient said 'stomach'. This is an example of how miscommunication can occur due to a lack of anatomical knowledge. This highlights the importance of fully explaining procedures to patients. She might be confused as to why you want to do a bi-manual examination for a problem that she believes to be GI related. 

 

For more information on the histology of the ovaries, check out:

http://www.histology.leeds.ac.uk/female/ovary.php

Question:
The late 1950s marked the beginning of the sexual revolution. Between the legalisation of the COCP, a growing acceptance of abortions and the advent of antibiotics, casual sex rocketed, leading into the decade known as the 'Swingin' 60s'. 

 

The first mass produced antibiotic was penicillin, which is still used today for treating a common STI. 

 

   

 

Which STI is penicillin used to treat?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. Syphilis used to be a huge killer before antibiotics became available for mainstream use. It is now at fairly low rates in the population. 

 

A: Gonorrhoea used to be treated with penicillin, but it is now generally resistant to it. Ceftriaxone with azithromycin is the standard treatment.

B: Penicillin is not used in chlamydia. Azithromycin and doxycycline tend to be used together to clear up chlamydia. 

D: Trichomoniasis is a protozoan, but can't be treated with penicillin. It can, however, be treated with nucleic acid synthesis inhibitor metronidazole.

E: HIV is a virus, so antibiotics do not work. While AIDS can be managed, once infected with HIV you cannot be cured.

Question: Which of the following drugs acts on the sympathetic nervous system by acting upon adrenoceptors, causing mydriasis and conjunctival whitening (via vasoconstriction)?
Explanation:
Tropicamide: Muscarinic Receptor Antagonist: Acts by blocking the muscarinic acetyl choline receptors of the parasympathetic nervous system. This paralyses the pupil constrictor muscle and the ciliary muscle. This causes pupil dilation (mydriasis) and loss of accommodation (cycloplegia).

Pilocarpine: Muscarinic Receptor Agonist: Acts on parasympathetic nervous system by acting upon muscarinic acetyl choline receptors. This causes the pupil constrictor muscle to contract. This causes pupil constriction (miosis) and conjunctival whitening (via vasoconstriction).

Cocaine: Local Anaesthetic + Noradrenaline Reuptake Inhibitor: Acts by blocking voltage gated Na+ channels in nerve axons, causing the loss of the corneal reflex. Also acts by blocking noradrenaline reuptake, increasing sympathetic stimulation. This causes the pupil dilator muscle to contract. This causes pupil dilation (mydriasis) and conjunctival whitening.

Tetracaine: Local Anaesthetic: Acts by blocking voltage gated Na+ channels in nerve axons. This stops action potentials from travelling along the axon. This causes the loss of the corneal reflex.

Question:
While veins are well known for elasticity, some arteries also have elastic properties. This dampens the pulse wave, allowing a more continuous flow of blood. 

 

 

 

Which of these arteries is an elastic artery?

The correct answer is D. It is a large vessel directly from the aorta, so is an elastic artery. 

 

All of the other options are muscular arteries. Instead of elastin, they have musculature to stop the vessels being compressed by movement of joints. 

 

The femoral artery is essentially an extension of the common iliac artery, but it is muscular by this point.

Question:
A patient presents to their GP with abdominal pain that is radiating across to their shoulder blade. The patient was annoyed because the pain came on midway through his 3rd Fattoush of the day. The doctor believes the most likely cause of the patient's pain is gallstones, which if left untreated will cause jaundice.

OptionA: Its bactericidal by inserting into the bacterial cell membrane causing ion pores to form that depolarise and kill the bacterium.
OptionB: Its bacteriostatic by inserting into the bacterial cell membrane causing ion pores to form that depolarise and stop the bacterium from replicating
OptionC: Its bactericidal via beta-lactam blocking peptidoglycan synthesis in the bacterial cell wall
OptionD: It is often given as a broad spectrum antibiotic
Explanation:

D - Its a last resort antibiotic

Question: What is the primary difference between Dendritic Cells and Macrophages?
OptionA: Dendritic Cells secrete cytokines, while Macrophages do not.
OptionB: Macrophages contain 'Pattern Recognition Receptors' (PRRs) and Dendritic Cells do not.
OptionC: Macrophages can migrate from the site of infection via lymphatic vessels to the nearest draining lymph node.
OptionD: Dendritic Cells are located in all peripheral tissues, while Macrophages are only located in certain peripheral tissues (e.g. epidermis of skin).
OptionE: Dendritic Cells can migrate from the site of infection via lymphatic vessels to the nearest draining lymph node.
Explanation:
Dendritic Cells are very similar to Macrophages and share many characteristics. They both:
- Are located in all peripheral tissues
- Possess PRRs
- Secrete inflammatory cytokines
- Can perform phagocytosis

However Dendritic Cells have an additional feature: they can migrate from the site of infection via lymphatic vessels to the nearest draining lymph node to present MHC/peptide complexes to T Cell Receptors (TCRs) on naive T cells, while Macrophages cannot migrate in this manner.

Question: Which antibiotic targets the prokaryotic and mitochondrial large subunit of the ribosome, inhibiting the peptidyle transferase reaction during translation?
Explanation:
A) Chloramphenicol is the correct answer

 

B & C) Erythromycin and Clarithromycin target the prokaryotic large subunit inhibiting the peptidyle transferase reaction and also translocation.

 

D) Ricin targets the eukaryotic 60s subunit. Its action is catalytic, removing a base from rRNA (which makes up the ribosome subunit). The lethal dose is humans = 10-4

 

E) Rifampicin inhibits mRNA synthesis and is often used in the treatment of TB
Tags: Transcription and Translation, PCS 2, PCS unit 2, PCS2, Cell replication

Question:
The morning is dragging on and you are excited for your lunch, so you decide to revise digestion. You see the long list of cells in the digestive tract and have your daily crisis, wondering if it's really that important to learn.

 

You read that as well as secreting hydrochloric acid, parietal cells in the stomach release another substance. 

    

 

What is the other substance released by parietal cells?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. Parietal cells release intrinsic factor, which allows the absorption of vitamin B12 in the duodenum. 

 

B: Gastrin has an effect on parietal cells, causing them to secrete more acid. It is released from the G-cells. Surprisingly, it doesn't contribute that much to the overall acid production directly. A more significant effect of gastrin is to cause histamine release from ECL cells. 

C: Trypsinogen is released by Chief Cells.

D: Histamine is released from ECL cells. This is either triggered by gastrin as pointed out above or by vagal stimulation. 

E: Somatostatin is secreted from D-cells. It inhibits cAMP production directly in parietal cells, antagonising histamine.

Question: You see a patient who is the first trimester of her pregnancy and is suffering from increased urinary urgency, lower abdominal pain and dysuria. You diagnose her with a urinary tract infection and prescribe a course of antibacterial drugs to stop the UTI progressing into pyelonephritis. You find out the organism causing the women's UTI is resistant to penicillin, what antibiotic would be best to prescribe?
Explanation:
The safest drugs to treat urinary tract infections in pregnancy are cephalosporin's and penicillin's. The organism is resistant to penicillin so it is the best option to give cephalexin (a cephalosporin).

 

A- Trimethoprim should be avoided during pregnancy because it is a folate antagonist and will create a teratogenic risk on the foetus (abnormalities in physical development).

B- Gentamicin should be avoided during pregnancy

C- Ciprofloxacin is a quinolone and they should be avoided during pregnancy

D- Correct

 

Source: https://www.evidence.nhs.uk/formulary/bnf/current/5-infections/51-antibacterial-drugs/5113-urinary-tract-infections

Question: Whilst skiing down the alps on a lovely, sunny day at blistering speeds, you begin to feel an aching pain in the dorsum of both your feet which radiates to the web space of your first and second toes. You stop to take your skii boots off, which helps to alleviate the pain and you no longer feel pain. You think the pain was caused by your boots being too tight, but which nerve was being compressed to cause this pain?
Explanation: Compression of the deep fibular nerve by tight-fitting ski boots may occur where the nerve passes deep to the inferior extensor retinaculum and the extensor hallucis brevis. Pain occurs in the dorsum of the foot and usually radiates to the web space between the first and second toes. Condition has also been called the 'ski boot syndrome', but it can also occur in football players and runners from tight shoes.

B: Lewy Body dementia shares symptoms with Alzheimer's Disease, but with AD you are unlikely to have hallucinations.

D: His very low MoCA score means MCI is unlikely.

E: The shuffle suggests Parkinsons, which is related to Lewy Body Dementia.

Question: Which Chromosomal abnormality has the highest incidence?
Explanation:
Trisomy describes the presence of an extra chromosome i.e. 3 copies of a chromosome instead of two

It often originates from non-disjunction during meiosis

  • Trisomy 18 (Edward syndrome) has an incidence of 1 in 8000 (few survive after one year)

Question: A 65 year old lady presents at your practice having fractured her scaphoid after falling on to her wrist. This is her 3rd fracture this year, as a result you screen for osteoporosis by conducting a DEXA test. The results show that she does in fact have osteoporosis. As a result you start her on bisphosphonates as a first line drug to treat osteoporosis. Which of the following describes one of the mechanisms by which bisphosphonates work to treat osteoporosis.
OptionA: Cause oestrogen to be released, increasing oestoblast function.
OptionB: Contains huge dosages of calcium and vitamin D
OptionC: Inhibits bone absorption by encouraging osteoclasts to die by apoptosis and so slows bone loss.
OptionD: Encourages angiogenesis, permeating the bone with more blood vessels.
OptionE: parathyroid hormone contained within the drug, causing new bone formation.
Explanation:
C- First line drugs

  • Alendronate reduces vertebral, wrist and hip fracture risk by 35-39%.
  • Works by preferential binding to calcium (so collects in high concentrations in bone) and mimics pyrophosphate (so inhibit enzymes which use it).
  • Inhibits bone absorption by encouraging osteoclasts to die by apoptosis and so slows bone loss.
  • May be stopped after 5y in low risk, 10y in high risk
  • Side effects: stomach, jaw osteonecrosis, bisphosphonate fracture

Calcium and vitamin D can also be given, but recent studies show little evidence their use reduces fracture risk

 

Strontium – increases bone deposit by osteoblasts and reduces absorption by osteoclasts so a dual action bone agent (DABA) but high risk of MI identified in 2013 so restricted use.


SERM – raloxifene reduces vertebral fracture risk. Selective (o)estrogen receptor modulator


PTH – teriparatide (recombinant parathyroid hormone) triggers new bone formation. But theoretical risk of osteosarcoma

 

See Bone Health lecture case 1 for further details.

Question: You go to Lidl today and pick up four packets of chocolate biscuits to fuel procrastination. As a reward for an attention span greater than 10 minutes, you indulge yourself in the consumption of one of Lidl's finest. The thought of this drives you to work, you notice that you begin to secrete more saliva every time the clock hits the 10 minute mark. This is an example of conditioning. With regards to salvia production, you are aware that primary secretions are isotonic and that secondary modification results in a more hypotonic solution being formed. This hypotonic solution is modified to have a higher concentration of which of the following ions vs that of primary secretion?
Explanation:
HCO3- is exchanged for Cl- causing its concentration to rise in the saliva. The HCO3- is important as it prevents the minerals in the dental hard tissues from dissolving.

K+ is also exchanged for Na+ leading to a rise in K+ in the saliva. 

 

In humans, the submandibular gland contributes around 70–75% of secretion, while the parotid gland secretes about 20–25% and small amounts are secreted from the other salivary glands.

Question:
Your nan comes to you complaining "the doctor has put me on more ruddy pills!". You check her prescription and see that she has been prescribed a statin. 

 

While you remember that Nan's statins inhibit HMG-CoA, you can't remember the sequence of lipoproteins later in the pathway. 

 

As Nan starts ranting "Now back in my day...", you decide to research the order of the lipoproteins. 

 

      

 

What is the correct order of lipoproteins between leaving the liver and entering the target blood vessel?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. Lipid transport is something I've always found it tough to wrap my head around. 

 

You may think I'm an idiot but imagining it as a story of a tragic romance makes it easier to remember.

 

1) Cholesterol and triglycerides in the intestines find love, forming a beautiful chylomicron.

2) It gets broken down by a homewrecker, lipoprotein lipase.

3) What's left, (a remnant of their relationship) goes into the liver and leaves cholesterol alone. (HMG-CoA reductase also forms cholesterol here)

4) Cholesterol gets back together with triglycerides again, but this time in the liver. 

5) They run off into the sunset together as a VLDL. 

6) That mean SoB lipoprotein lipase is back with a vengeance, slowly eating away at their relationship. 

7) The VLDL becomes an IDL, then a measly LDL before reaching the blood vessel as their relationship dwindles. 

8) Cholesterol and triglycerides make it inside the vessel and realise they don't need each other any more. They go their separate ways in the blood vessel. 

9) Cholesterol is used by the cells, but dreams of returning to where it rekindled love, the romantic haven of the liver. 

10) Excess cholesterol and triglycerides get back together for one last fling as their previous relationship becomes a tiny HDL 'friends with benefits' affair. 

11) They make it back to the liver and go their separate ways for good.

 

For those of you less silly than me, here's the diagram I got it from, in The Cardiovascular System at a glance (616.1 AAR if you're in the library).

Question:
Aaron is on his Year 7 school trip to the Brecon Beacons when he decides, despite his peanut allergy, he's going to eat some peanut puffs. He goes into anaphylactic shock and has to be flown to hospital.

 

As the helicopter lands in Heath, you speak to the paramedics on board. 

 

"We gave him his epipen, we've bought him some time."

 

     

 

What is the main reason adrenaline in an epipen helps in an anaphylactic shock?
OptionA: It speeds up the heart to counteract allergic bradycardia.
OptionB: It opens the alveoli so the patient can breathe more easily.
OptionC: It competitively inhibits IgE when in large doses.
OptionD: It non-competitively inhibits IgE in large doses.
OptionE: It counteracts the vasodilation following extreme histamine release.
Explanation:
The correct answer is E. A severe allergic reaction will cause mast cells to release a lot of histamine very quickly, which is a vasodilator. Endothelium becomes leaky and protein and fluid cannot reach the tissues, resulting in oedema. The vasoconstriction of adrenaline will counteract it until IV antihistamines and glucocorticoids can be given in hospital. 

 

All the other answers are made up.

 

This, amazingly, is a true story from my year 7 school trip to Paris. Aaron didn't realise peanut puffs had peanuts in them. Seriously.

 

(The helicopter cost him a lot afterwards...)

Question: In the pulmonary circulation, what happens when O2 decreases and CO2 increases?
Explanation:
B is in systemic circulation

Pulmonary circulation vasoconstricts to direct blood flow to areas that are well perfused

 

A pulmonary shunt often occurs when the alveoli fill with fluid, causing parts of the lung to be unventilated although they are still perfused. Intrapulmonary shunting is the main cause of hypoxemia (inadequate blood oxygen) in pulmonary edema and conditions such as pneumonia in which the lungs become consolidated.

 

PVR = mPAP – (PCWP/ cardiac output) (mPAP = mean pulm artery pressure, PCWP = pulmonary capillary wedge pressure). Pulmonary vascular resistance decreases when cardiac output increases - this is because of: 

  • recruitment - some capillaries, which were closed or open but with no blood flow, begins to conduct blood
  • distension - capillaries change from near flattened to more circular

Question: Which is the main area of the brain which is responsible for us being aware of pain?
Explanation:
The thalamus is the secondary relay station (after the dorsal horn of the spinal cord) in the ascending pain pathway. This then connects with other parts of the brain:

-The sensory cortex is the main area responsible for being aware of pain

-The limbic system is responsible for many of the emotions we feel when we experience pain

-The brainstem has a crucial role in reflex responses to pain and coordination of pain modulation.

Question:
Eugene is brought into hospital for a single Coronary Artery Bypass Graft. He tells you that one of his friends got a heart bypass a few years ago and has a huge scar down his leg.

 

You tell Eugene that you don't plan to use that vein, as another vessel is more commonly used now. 

 

    

 

Which vessel is used most often for a single CABG?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. The left internal thoracic artery (also known as the mammary artery) is used for a CABG. 

 

B: The subclavian vein is too large and too important to reroute.

C: The radial artery is used in CABG operations. It does, however, narrow over time, while the LITA does not. 

D: The basilic vein very rarely used. The only data I can find shows that 43% of patients got another thrombosis in the following 7 years in these vessels.

E: The great saphenous vein is the one mentioned by Eugene before. It has fallen out of favour because it narrows over time and loses patency relatively quickly. In a larger CABG such as a quadruple heart bypass, it will still be used.

Question:
You're in a lab testing anticoagulant drugs. The drug you are told to work with today just has the brand name 'coumadin' scrawled beside it. When you test it on blood in vitro, you find that it has no effect on coagulation. 

 

Confused, you give 'coumadin' to a rat. You see a marked increase in APTT, PT and INR. You come to the conclusion that this drug must only work in vivo.

 

    

 

Using these test results, what is the chemical name for the drug 'coumadin'?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. Because warfarin inhibits vitamin K reductase in the liver, it will not cause anticoagulant activity in a petri dish. 

 

A: Heparin works on antithrombin, inhibiting factors II, IX, X and XI.

C: LMWH works the same way but has a longer half life than regular (unfractionated) heparin.

D: Fondaparinux is a drug we don't need to have heard of. It inhibits factor Xa.

E: Clopidogrel is an antiplatelet, not an anticoagulant.

Question: You're chilling in the desert with your meerkat chums when you notice that you are starting to sweat. What carries the afferent pathway to the spinal cord for increasing temperature?
Explanation: Jenny the meerkat cant handle the heat.

Question: The pupillary light reflex is a reflex which controls the pupil diameter in response to light intensity. Which cranial nerve is the afferent limb for this reflex?
Explanation:
A: Trochlear nerve (CN IV)- Motor innervation of the superior oblique muscle of the eye

B: Abducens nerve (CN VI)- Motor innervation of the lateral rectus muscle of the eye

C: Optic nerve (CN II) -  vision (afferent limb of pupillary light reflex)

D: Oculomotor nerve (CN III)- Inferior oblique, superior, medial and inferior rectus, levator palpabrae, sphincter pupillae and ciliary muscles (efferent limb of pupillary light reflex)

E: Trigeminal nerve (CN V)- Ophthalmic division (V1) of the trigeminal nerve innervates the cornea, ciliary body, iris, lacrimal gland and conjunctiva
Tags: PCS Unit 3, PCS3, Case 6, Case 6 -Neruoanatomy, Cranial Nerves

Question: Which of the following CANNOT be caused by folic acid deficiency during pregnancy?
Explanation: Rickets is caused by vitamin D deficiency

Question: A patient presents with a pain which runs from his posterior thigh down to his left leg. He complains of a numbness and tingling sensation which runs down the length of his leg. You suspect that there has been damage to the sciatic nerve. Which of the following muscles, when inflamed, can compress the sciatic nerve to generate these symptoms?
Explanation: Inflammation of the piriformis muscle can lead to compression of the sciatic nerve resulting in these symptoms. This is due to the close relationship the two structures share.
Tags: Muscle, Muscle Actions, Muscles of the back, Case 1, muscle contraction

Question:
It 9:04pm on a Wednesday night and you are at your hockey social (of course).

After losing yet another round of "fingers in the middle" you are politely and conservatively encouraged by your fellow team mates to "see off" (drink very quickly) the cider black you just bought.

As you close your eyes and begin to gulp, you think back to CASE 3 when you learnt about the mechanism of SWALLOWING, and consider, which of the following phases of swallowing is/are under INVOLUNTARY Control?
Explanation:
Answer: B

 

The three phases of swallowing are oral (or buccal), pharyngeal and oesophageal.

(The intestinal phase is a phase of digestion)

 

ORAL PHASE- voluntary control. Areas of the motor cortex innervate muscles of mastication (innervated by V3), the salivary glands and muscles of the tounge (CN XII)

 

PHARYNGEAL PHASE-involuntary control. Activation of proprioceptors scattered over the base of the tongue, the palatoglossal and palatopharyngeal arches, the tonsillar fossa, uvula and posterior pharyngeal wall cause closure of the oral cavity by the tounge, closing of the nasopharynx and relaxation of the upper oesophageal sphincter. The larynx rises to pull epiglosstis across the trachea to prevent bolus of food/fluid entering the airway (aspiration) - this causes temporary halt in respiration (deglutition apnea)

 

OESOPHAGEAL PHASE- Involuntary control. If the bolus is stuck, mechanoreceptors are activated that cause a secondary peristaltic wave, aided by mucus secretion. Lower Oesophageal Sphincter relaxes in response to deglutition apnea. This is a vago-vagal reflex.

Question: 18 year old man comes into your practice complaining of extreme lethargy, fever like symptoms, swollen lymph nodes and pharyngitis. An inspection of his abdomen reveals splenomegaly and hepatomegaly. The man has just started University and thinks he has 'freshers' flu'. You inform him that he has glandular fever, otherwise known as Infectious mononucleosis. What is the causative agent of glandular fever?
Explanation:
The correct answer is the Epstein-Barr virus

 

It is best known as the cause of infectious mononucleosis (glandular fever). It is also associated with particular forms of cancer, such as Hodgkin's lymphoma, Burkitt's lymphoma, gastric cancer, nasopharyngeal carcinoma, and conditions associated with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), such as hairy leukoplakia and central nervous system lymphomas.

 

For more, refer to the lectures in PCS 2 regarding immunology.

Question:
Hydroencephalus is caused by a blockage in the CSF pathway in the brain. The blockage is most likely to occur in the cerebral aqueduct and causes a build up of pressure in the brain. How can this be treated?

 

(PSC 3 Anatomy)
OptionA: It cannot be treated - patients usually die within the first few months of life.
OptionB: A lumbar puncture can be performed to drain the CSF.
OptionC: A catheter is inserted into the 3rd ventricle to drain the excess fluid.
OptionD: The body spontaneously upregulates arachnoid villi in the subarachnoid space in response to the increase in pressure so that more CSF is reuptaken into the venous system.
OptionE: The fluid can be drained from the subarachnoid space via catheterisation.
Explanation: C is the correct. E and B would not relieve the pressure as the blockage is in the cerebral aqueduct and these sites of catherisation are downstream. D is incorrect because arachnoid villi are not something that can be upregulated like the presence of membrane channels etc.
Tags: Brain, CSF, Head, Head and Neck, PCS3

Question: A patient presents at your practice for a after being diagnosed with osteopaenia. She complains of being chronically fatigued as well as feeling as if 'her memory isn't as it was'. A measurement of her blood pressure reveals that she is also hypertensive. You suspect hyperparathyroidism. This is a tumour of the parathyroid glands resulting in the production of excess parathyroid hormone. This hormone acts to increase the level of what ion in the blood?
Explanation: The parathyroid is responsible for maintaining Calcium levels in the blood. Raised PTH increases the risk of atherosclerosis and as such can lead to hypertension/increased risk of MIs. It is also responsible for interfering with the electrical signalling of the heart, increasing risk of arrhythmia. It is also associated with damage to neurones, impacting cognition.

Question: Where in the nephron does the reabsorption of glucose occur?
A patient presents with ' homonymous hemianopia' .Which of the following best describes the site of the lesion which would cause homonymous hemianopia.
Explanation: Left homonymous hemianopia means visual field defect to the left, i.e. Lesion of right optic tract

Question: A worried mother comes into her practice with her 8 year old child. The child had a headache and thought he'd administer himself some paracetamol in order to elevate his symptoms. However, the child mistook a packet of warfarin for that of paracetamol. Which of the following food items could the mother give her child in order to act as an antidote for the warfarin?
Explanation:
Warfarin acts to inhibit vitamin K, the vitamin required for the formation of clotting factors 2,7,9, 10 (never going to clot again). As such the antidote to warfarin is an increased intake of vitamin K, as found in green leafy vegetables. 

  • Oranges are associated with vitamin C.
  • Carrots contain beta-carotene which is converted into vitamin A in the liver. 
  • Milk contains Calcium, although if you look at a milk bottle, it contains a myriad of added vitamins and minerals.
  • Red meat contains all kinds of stuff

See the vitamins and mineral lecture for more as well as the case 4 lightbulb.
Tags: Vitamins, PCS 2, Vitamins and Minerals, Case 4, Pharmacology

Question:
Ellen, a first year medical student, is washing her car and notices a hole in the hose she is using and wonders how she will repair it. She starts to think about the coagulation cascade that takes place to seal holes after damage to endothelium in blood vessels.

 

Which clotting factor can the coagulation cascade function without?
Explanation:
The extrinsic pathway activates the intrinsic pathway from factor XI downwards, so clotting can take place without factor XII.

Absence of VIII, IX or XI result in haemophilia
Tags: Blood, Blood Vessels, Blood supply, PCS 2, Circulation

Question: Which of the following is a result of the complement system which helps to facilitate the action of phagocytes?
Explanation: Opsonisation will facilitate phagocytosis. The micro-organism becomes coated with antibody, C3b and certain acute phase proteins. The macrophages and neutrophils have up regulation of phagocytic cell surface receptors in these circumstances, a process mediated by pro-inflammatory cytokines. These cells then engulf the micro organism.

Question:
A 28-year-old male scores in the 95th percentile on the WAIS-IV test, corresponding to a z score of 1.8. Using the formula z = (x –μ) / SD, what is the closest approximation of the participant’s IQ?

 

Scores are standardised to have a mean (μ) of 100 and a standard deviation (SD) of 15.
Explanation:
z = (x –μ) / SD

z = z score

x = test score

μ = the mean of the test score distribution

SD = the standard deviation of the test score distribution

 

So, we are trying to find what the test score (IQ) is (which is x in the equation). Plug in all the other numbers into the equation to give:

 

1.8 = (x - 100)/15

 

Re-arrange the equation:

1.8 x 15 = (x - 100)

27 = (x - 100)

x = 27 +100

x = 127

Question: Which of the following is the only antibiotic that can cross the blood-brain barrier in health?
Explanation: Other antibiotics such as penicillin can cross the BBB when a patient has meningitis.

Question:
During the bird flu pandemic of 2009, it became apparent that ducks could spread the disease as easily as chickens, but died far less often. This is because one of their immunoglobulins, IgY, is shaped differently. 

 

IgY is found in birds, reptiles and lungfish and shows many similarities to one of the mammalian immunoglobulins.

 

It provides the majority of long term antibody-based immunity and is able to pass into the yolk of birds' eggs.

  

 

Using this information, which mammalian antibody is replaced by IgY in these animals?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. IgG's main function is in antibody-mediated long term immunity. It can also pass into the placenta, the mammalian equivalent of the yolk of an egg. 

 

Roles of Immunoglobulins

IgA - Found in mucosal areas, such as the gut, respiratory tract and urogenital tract, and prevents colonization by pathogens. Also found in saliva, tears, and breast milk. Some antibodies form complexes that bind to multiple antigen molecules.


IgD - Functions mainly as an antigen receptor on B cells that have not been exposed to antigens. It has been shown to activate basophils and mast cells to produce antimicrobial factors.


IgE - Binds to allergens and triggers histamine release from mast cells and basophils, and is involved in allergy. Also protects against parasitic worms.


IgG - In its four forms, provides the majority of antibody-based immunity against invading pathogens. The only antibody capable of crossing the placenta to give passive immunity to the fetus.


IgM - Expressed on the surface of B cells (monomer) and in a secreted form (pentamer) with very high avidity. Eliminates pathogens in the early stages of B cell-mediated (humoral) immunity before there is sufficient IgG.

Question: you are looking at a car passing you whilst you are in the bus. as the car gets closer what happens to the lens of your eye and how?
OptionA: closer the car, the thicker the lens gets by relaxing the ciliary muscle.
OptionB: closer the car, the thinner the lens gets by contracting the ciliary muscle
OptionC: closer the car gets, the thicker the lens by contracting the ciliary muscle and the ligaments slack off.
Explanation:
the closer the object, the more light has to bend so you need a thicker lens. this is achieved by the parasympathetic nervous system and the ciliary muscle contracts and the ligaments slack off. 

when you are looking at a distant object, the light doesn't need to bend as much so you need a thin lens achieved by the sympathetic nervous system. the PS nervous system is inhibited so the muscles relax and the ligaments tense up pulling the lense into the thinner shape. there is no sympathetic innervation.

Question:
Diabetes mellitus has been linked with a decrease in trypsin release by the pancreas.

 

Trypsin is used as an activator for many zymogens, but some enzymes are released in an active form. 

 

 

 

Which of these enzymes is released by the pancreas in its active form?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D. Amylase, lipase, RNAase, DNAase and trypsin itself are the only enzymes released by the pancreas that are not activated by trypsin. 

 

There are very few articles about trypsin deficiency and diabetes, but those that I could find suggest that diabetes can cause more widespread pancreatic decline than just insulin. 

 

This information is from Jeff's PCS 2 lecture.
Tags: GI tract, Gastrointestinal System, PCS 2, Pancreas, Case 3

Question:
Mr Jackson is a 66 year old retired construction worker who presents at his GP with "aching joints". He explains that he has had problems with his joints for several years, and that they get very painful and stiff especially in the afternoon. The joints affected include his left knee and ankle, as well as his right shoulder and several distal and proximal interphalangeal joints on both hands. There is crepitus in some of the joints.

 

What condition is Mr Jackson most likely suffering from?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D - osteoarthritis.

 

Osteoarthritis is the degenerative disease of joints which leads to pain, stiffness and weakness, caused by wear of the articulating cartilage due to overuse. The pattern of arthritis is asymmetrical (i.e. doesn't occur equally on both sides of the body) and often gets worse throughout the day. It can lead to osteophytes (projections of bone), as well as Bochard's (DIP) and Herbeden's (PIP) nodes, we well as Crepitus - a crackling/grinding sound which occurs when the joints move.

 

A - Rheumatoid arthritis causes a symmetrical pattern of joint disease which would be worse in the morning. Also rheumatoid arthritis does not affect the distal interphalangeal joints.

 

B - osteoporosis is the reduction in bone density, and does not cause joint pain.

 

C - septic arthritis is caused by bacterial infection of the joints. As Mr Jackson explains that his joint pain has been developing over several years this cannot be correct. 

 

E - ankylosing spondylitis generally occurs in the early 20s. It is the pathological fusion of the vertebrae across the joint space caused by prolonged joint inflammation/infection.

Question:
--------------------- is an acute or chronic condition characterised by infection of the uterus, uterine tubes and ovaries. It is often caused by bacteria such as Chlamydia trachomatis and Neisseria gonorrhoeae, which ascend from the vagina. Symptoms are often mild, but may include pain in the lower abdomen, dysuria and intermenstrual bleeding.

 

What is this condition?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

 

Chlamydia and Gonorrhoea are causes of PID.

 

PID can cause pelvic adhesions - where scar tissue 'sticks together' within the uterus or uterine tubes. This can lead to ectopic pregnancies.

Question:
Cobalamin (Vitamin B12) is important in the synthesis of DNA. It can easily be damaged by the low pH of the stomach and must be protected by a protein in the saliva. 

 

 

What is the name of the protein which protects vitamin B12?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A. Haptocorrin binds to cobalamin at the low pH of the stomach, when cobalamin is liberated from the food in digestion. It then degrades in the more pH neutral duodenum. 

 

B: Somatostatin is released from D-cells and inhibits parietal cells.

C: Amylase is present in the saliva, but it is an enzyme for breaking down starch, not protecting B12.

D: Intrinsic factor is released in the stomach by parietal cells, but binds to B12 in the duodenum. 

E: Enterocyte processing binds cobalamin to transcobalamin II in the ileum. 

 

Absorption of B12 is covered in Jeff's PCS 2 lecture, there's a whole section at the end about B12 absorption.
Tags: GI Physiology, GI tract, Gastrointestinal System, PCS 2, Case 3

Question:
A 28 year old female FISH swims into your clinic and says to you "I suffer from short term memory loss, It's true, I forget things almost instantly. Well, at least I think I do."

She is accompanied by a worrisome orange companion who describes the patient's memory as lasting less than 10 seconds, and that she often feels lost and confused. 

After taking a full history with help from the friend, you suspect your patient has anterograde and retrograde amnesia. She scores 78 on Addenbrook's Cognitive Examination; a curious finding was that she recalled the address " P. Sherman, 42 Wallaby Way, Sydney" instead of Harry Barnes' address.

 

Which of the following is FALSE about memory systems?

 

An appropriate motto for the revision and exam period

 

*disclaimer, I cannot claim that memory systems of fish work in the same way as human memory systems
OptionA: Ribot's Law describes the phenomenon of retaining remote memories from early childhood and is often preserved in amnesia
OptionB: Procedural memory can be maintained even in patients with substantial medial temporal lobe damage
OptionC: Miller's Magic Number describes the capacity of short term memory as limited to 7+/- 2 digits
OptionD: Baddley and Hitch (1974) described short-term memory as purely a holding area for passive storage of information
OptionE: Consolidation (including rehersal and making meaningful associations) helps create STRONG and STABLE memory traces in the creation of long term memories
Explanation:
Answer = D

 

Baddley and Hitch (1974) described short-term memory as more than just a passive holding area, and instead was a form of "working memory" that could be manipulated and was linked to attention and conscious thought.

Working memory has 3 components:

 

1.) Phonological Loop- inner ear and inner voice can rehearse speech-like information

2.) Visuo-spatial sketchpad- visual images can be manipulated

3.) Central executive, controls the whole system, involved in planning and sequencing and acts as an 'episodic buffer'- an interface between working memory and long term memory

 

The rest of the options are correct, for more information see the lecture on memory and memory systems

 

Scenario copyright of Pixar Animated Studios

Question: In Homer's Illiad, the character Achilles is rendered immortal after being dipped in the river Styx by his mother. The only part of his body being mortal being his calcaneal tendon. From this myth we have the name 'Achilles' tendon' as an alternative to the calcaneal tendon and as a metaphor for a weakness in spite of overall strength. Which of the following muscles merges with the calcaneal tendon to form its attachment to the calcaneus?
Explanation:
There are three muscles which blend with the calcaneal tendon to insert on the calcaneus. These are the: Gastrocnemius, Soleus and Plantaris. All muscles are innervated by the tibial nerve and are responsible for plantarflexion at the ankle. 

 

The gastrocnemius is the most superficial of all the muscles in the posterior leg. It has two heads – medial and lateral, which converge to form a single muscle belly.

Attachments: The lateral head originates from the lateral femoral condyle, and medial from the medial condyle. The fibres converge, and form a single muscle belly. In the lower part of the leg, the muscle belly combines with the soleus to from the calcaneal tendon, with inserts onto the calcaneus (the heel bone).

 

Actions: It plantarflexes at the ankle joint, and because it crosses the knee, it is a flexor there.

 

Innervation: Tibial nerve.

 

 

For more http://teachmeanatomy.info/lower-limb/muscles/leg/posterior-compartment/

Question:
Kenneth's arterial blood gases come back and you see these results. 

_____________________

pH: 7.32
PaCO2: 65 mmHg
[HCO3-]: 32 mEq/L

_____________________

 

The reference values are as follows:

 

pH = 7.35-7.45

PaCO2 = 35-45 mmHg

[HCO3-] = 22-26 mEq/L

 

What is the correct interpretation for these results?
OptionB: Metabolic acidosis, partially compensated by respiratory alkalosis
OptionC: Respiratory acidosis, partially compensated by metabolic alkalosis
OptionD: Metabolic alkalosis, partially compensated by respiratory acidosis
OptionE: Respiratory alkalosis, partially compensated by metabolic acidosis
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. The pH and CO2 levels are both acidotic, so the primary mechanism is a respiratory acidosis. The metabolic alkalosis is compensation for the CO2, but the pH is not within normal limits, so it is only partially effective.

 

I found these really difficult until I was sent the link to this website. You can test yourself and see if you really know your arterial blood gases.

Question: Which out of the following is the longest muscle?
Explanation:
Sartorius is the longest muscle in the body. 

 

Origin: Inferior portion of the anterior superior iliac spine


Insertion: Upper medial surface of tibial shaft at the tibial flare


Action: Assists with hip flexion, knee flexion, medial rotation of the knee, lateral rotation of the hip


Innervation: Anterior division of the femoral nerve (L3- 4)


Blood Supply: Branches from the femoral artery

Question:
Free functioning muscle transfer is a surgical technique whereby a muscle from one limb can be grafted into another in order to replace a damage muscle. An example of this is the use of gracilis being inserted into the arm. Gracilis is a muscle of the adductor compartment of muscles in the thigh. Which of the following describes its area of origin? 

 

For more on FFMT, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12178-014-9203-5
OptionA: The inferior rami of the pubis, and the body of the pubis.
OptionB: Originates from the gluteal (posterior) surface of the ilium, sacrum and coccyx.
OptionE: Medial and lateral condyle of the femur.
Explanation:
A-Correct

B-Gluteus Maximus

C-Gluteus Minimus

D-Sartorius

E-gastrocnemius

 

This is one of the smaller muscles of the medial thigh, and it is located most superiorly.

Attachments: It originates from the membrane of the obturator foramen, and adjacent bone. It passes under the neck of femur, attaching to the posterior aspect of the greater trochanter.


Actions: Laterally rotates the thigh.


Innervation: Obturator nerve (L2-L4).

Question: Which cytochrome p450 enzyme is used to metabolise caffeine?
Explanation:
CYP1A2 is used in the metabolism of caffeine and theophylline

 

CYP3E4 is responsible for approximately half of all phase I metabolism

CYP1A1 prefers to metabolise theophylline

CYP2E1 metabolises ethanol (alcohol)

 

CYP1A2 and CYP2E1 are also used in the metabolism of paracetamol, producing the toxic species NAPBQI which must be deactivated by conjugation with glutathione.

 

(from Dr Coffey's lecture on hepatic drug metabolism)

Question:
A 6 year old patient comes into your GP practice requiring a vaccination. The nurse asks the child to count backwards from 10 while administering the vaccination.

What type of psychological pain modulation does this encompass?
Explanation:
Attention orientating can reduce the intensity of the painful stimulus.

 

Distracting the attention from the painful stimulus (e.g. by counting) reduces the activity in the sensory S1 and S2 areas and thalamus in the brain which are part of the lateral pain system. This system is important in the sensory aspects of pain.

 

It increases activity in the medial pain system in the pre-frontal cortex (the ACC) and stimulated activity of the PAG. This can cause descending pathway modulation by release of endogenous opioids thus reducing the painful sensation.

Question:
After your last meeting with Gran, she has a follow up call telling you how emaciated you look because you're not eating enough! She encourages you to buy some multivitamins.

This gets you thinking about vitamins and their absorption!

Which substance protects Vitamin B12 from the acidic stomach environments?
Explanation:
• Haptocorrin protects vitamin B12 from acidic stomach environment but is digested in duodenum

B12 binds to intrinsic factor (glycoprotein secreted by parietal cells of gastric mucosa) forms a complex recognised by cubulin receptor in brush border membrane of cells in lower ileum then the complex is endocytosed by enterocytes
• B12 released from cubulin, then intrinsic factor complex is transported across basolateral membrane, enters capillary endothelial cells,  binds to transcobalamin II prior to its transport in the blood

 

Information from Pococks, further reading on B12 absorption

Question: Which of the following drugs is an ACE inhibitor?
Explanation:
Aspirin- anti-platelet drug that irreversibly inhibits COX domain

Clopidogrel- also an anti-platelet drug which works by ADP dependent activation of glycoprotein IIb/IIIa receptor

Losartan- angiotentin II receptor antagonist, decreases angiotensin II

Question:
On placement, your GP lets you sit in on a consultation with a patient.

This patient has presented with symptoms that, combined with their history (obesity, smokes, hypertension), makes your GP worry about risk of an aneurysm of the posterior communicating artery. Your GP organises an MRI to detect the aneurysm, and find out if it can be treated.

If the aneurysm is pressing on a cranial nerve, which one is most likely and what symptoms may the patient have presented with?
OptionA: CN X: patient is struggling to swallow all food and water, and you note a bovine cough (cough without any force).
OptionB: CN III: patient has unilateral ptosis (drooping eyelid) and blown pupil (dilated). May have a 'down and out' position of one pupil.
OptionC: CN XI: patient complains of shoulder pain, and is struggling to reach up to high shelves. Upon examination, cannot shrug shoulders or turn head against any resistance.
OptionD: CN XII: patient complains that they have been struggling to talk, slurring their speech as their tongue feels heavy. Upon examination, one side of the tongue is atrophied
Explanation:
The posterior communicating artery is a relatively common site of aneurysm in the Circle of Willis. It is more common in patients with risk factors such as smoking, hypertension, etc.

This would most probably affect CN III, which is the oculomotor nerve, because of its proximity to the artery.

Oculomotor supplies motor innervation to inferior oblique, inferior rectus, medial rectus, and superior rectus, hence the 'down and out' position of the eye.

It also provides motor innervation of the levator palpable superiors (upper eyelid), so you would see ptosis.

The pupil would be blown/dilated because oculomotor nerve provides parasympathetic innervation to the constrictor pupillae muscle, and so with this muscle not working there is unopposed dilation.

 

Let me know if you have any questions or if I'm wrong!
Tags: Eye Anatomy, Blood Vessels, Brain, PCS 3, PCS Unit 3

Question: Which of the following cranial nerves is not a general sensory afferent (GSA)?
Explanation: XII - Hypoglossal is not an afferent/sensory nerve.

Question:
A woman goes to the GP complaining of unexpected breast milk production, irregular periods, reduced libido and headaches.

 

She is also complaining of visual field defects. 

 

She is referred to a specialist who orders blood tests which find an increased level of prolactin in the blood.

 

Based on the symptoms above, what is the most likely visual defect the woman is experiencing?
OptionA: Ipsilateral monocular vision loss
OptionB: Bitemporal hemianopia
OptionC: quadrantanopia
OptionD: Contralateral homonymous hemianopia
OptionE: Contralateral Right homonymous hemianopia with macular sparing
Explanation:
The symptoms are describing a type of pituitary tumour: a prolactinoma.

It is a prolactin-producing benign tumour of the pituitary gland. 

Symptoms:

  • discharge from breasts (Galactorrhoea) - females
  • irregular periods or loss of normal menstrual function (Amenorrhoea) - adult females
  • impotence - adult males
  • reduced fertility
  • decrease libido
  • headaches
  • vision disturbance

There are other types of tumour and pituitary conditions explained here: https://www.pituitary.org.uk/information/pituitary-conditions/

 

The visual defect is caused due to compression of the optic chiasm due to the growing tumour (this does not always happen-depends on size). This is known as Bitemporal hemianopia.

Question: To escape the impending exams, you start climbing a mountain and you keep going. After a long time, you start to feel ill and breathless even when resting. What is causing this symptom?
Explanation:
High altitude leads to hypoxamia in the lungs

The hypoxia leads to general vasoconstriction → increased pulmonary vascular resistance→ Increased extravascular fluid accumulation= High altitude pulmonary oedema

 

(Pulmonary circulation and lung disease lecture)

Question: What is the action of the drug salbutamol?
OptionA: Potent anti-inflammatory steroid which forms complex with glucocorticoid receptor which then acts as transcriptional regulator to (strongly) reduce inflammation
OptionB: Muscarinic (mostly M3) acetylcholine receptor antagonists. Blocking M3 ACh receptors on bronchial smooth muscle cells leads to reduced cGMP and smooth muscle cell relaxation with subsequent dilation of the bronchi
OptionC: Beta2 agonists - activation of beta-2 GPCR in bronchial tissue causes cAMP-mediated bronchial smooth muscle cell relaxation which dilates the bronchi and facilitates air-flow
OptionD: Beta2 antagonists - inhibition of beta-2 GPCR in bronchial tissue causes cAMP-mediated bronchial smooth muscle cell relaxation which dilates the bronchi and facilitates air-flow
OptionE: Directly breaks down mucus in the bronchi to dilate the bronchi
Explanation:
A - fluticasone (used to treat asthma long term as opposed to alleviating the symptoms)

B - ipratropium and tiotropium 

D - beta blockers are beta receptor antagonists, but they cause bronchoconstriction as a side effect (if they are non-selective). Selective beta-blockers only block b1 receptors

E - made up

 

Salbutamol and salmeterol act in the same way, and are both used in acute episodes of asthma/COPD. Info is from case 5 lightbulb

Question:
Evan is a 22 year old male who has fallen whilst skateboarding. He has injured his left ankle and he is in some pain. 

When you ask him about his pain, he describes it as 6/10. 

Upon examination, there is tenderness 8cm distal to the posterior edge of the tibia. 

When the incident happened, 3 hours ago, he was unable to bear weight on his left foot, but, by now, he is able to. 

What do you suggest is the next course of action?
OptionD: Tell him to go away because you're too busy
Explanation:
According to the Ottawa ankle rules, ankle x-rays are only required if:

There is any pain in the malleolar zone and any one of the following:
• Bone tenderness along the distal 6 cm of the posterior edge of the tibia or tip of the medial malleolus, OR
• Bone tenderness along the distal 6 cm of the posterior edge of the fibula or tip of the lateral malleolus, OR
• An inability to bear weight both immediately and in the emergency department for four steps.

Evan did not satisfy these rules (he can walk by now and has tenderness 8cm distal to the posterior edge of his tibia). 

Therefore, for Evan, who doesn't seem in an awful lot of pain, PRICE and 1g of paracetamol should be recommended. If there is a lot of swelling, ibuprofen may be recommended too. Make sure to check for any ADRs/contra-indications before providing any meds. 

 

The Ottawa ankle rules also provide guidance for foot x-rays: 
It states that an x-ray is required if there any pain in the midfoot zone; and any one of the following:

• Bone tenderness at the base of the fifth metatarsal (for foot injuries), OR
• Bone tenderness at the navicular bone (for foot injuries), OR
• An inability to bear weight both immediately and in the emergency department for four steps.

Question:
You are on a GP placement and your GP introduces you to a parent and their young infant. After observing the consultation, the GP asks you what sort of nerve injury the infant had, and what the likely mechanism of injury was.

 

The infant had their arm medially rotated, their forearm pronated and their hand flexed at the wrist.
OptionA:
Erb's palsy - upper brachial plexus injury.

Likely mechanism would be as a result of a difficult birth.
OptionB:
Klumpke Palsy - lower brachial plexus palsy.

Likely mechanism would be that the infant was playing in a tree, and caught a branch when falling.
OptionC:
Damage to the radial nerve in the axilla.

Likely mechanism would be dislocation at the shoulder joint.
OptionD:
Damaged to the ulnar nerve at the wrist.

Likely mechanism would be lacerations.
Explanation:
It would be Erb's palsy. The position described is the 'waiter's tip' position. During birth, the neck and shoulder are excessively pulled apart, which can stretch the plexus (especially at the top). This damaged the C5 and C6 roots (musculocutaneous, axillary, supra scapular, subclavius) so causes paralysis/weakness of the muscles supplied. Their is, therefore, unopposed medial rotation due to pectorals major pulling on the arm, and unopposed pronation. This also may have been given away by the diagram :P

 

B is incorrect: the patient is an infant, so unlikely to be climbing a tree (infant roughly refers to the first year of life, or at least before walking and climbing trees!). It would affect T1 root nerves (ulnar and median), causing a clawed appearance of the hand.

 

C is incorrect: again, the patient is an infant, so hopefully would not have any dislocations/fractures of proximal humerus, and also damage to the radial nerve presents as unopposed flexion of the wrist ('wrist drop') which may appear similar, but lacks the medial rotation.

 

D is incorrect: hopefully an infant would not sustain any wrist lacerations, but also ulnar nerve damage at the wrist leads to 'ulnar claw.' This is where digits 4 and 5 (ring and pinkie!) cannot extend properly - whilst the other digits can extend normally, digits 4 and 5 can extend at the metacarpophalangeal joints, but will remain flexed at the interphalangeal joints.

 

Side note: I always get ulnar claw and the hand of benediction mixed up, since they look similar in pictures.

The difference comes in what is being asked of the patient:

With ulnar claw, they are asked to extend their fingers to make a flat hand, but cannot extend digits 4 and 5 so they remain flexed.

With the 'Hand of Benediction,' they are asked to make a fist, but cannot flex digits 2 and 3 (point and index) so end up with 2 and 3 extended, but 4 and 5 flexed.

 

Let me know if you disagree with the answers (I may have misunderstood something!!!)
Tags: Nerves, Upper Limb Innervations, Upper Limb innervation, PCS 1, Clinical Significance

Question:
For this question, the Michaelis-Menten equation is provided:

 

Which of the following are suitable units for Km?
Explanation: Km is the substrate concentration at which the rate of reaction (V0) is exactly half of the maximum possible rate (Vmax).

Question:
For this question, the Michaelis-Menten equation is provided:


 

In a Lineweaver-Burke plot, which variable goes on the horizontal (x) axis?
Explanation:
The diagram above demonstrates a Lineweaver-Burke plot. 1/[S] is on the horizontal axis, and 1/V0 is on the vertical axis.

 

V0 is synonymous with V in the diagram above; however, Vmax is a different quantity - the maximum speed at which an enzyme catalysed reaction can occur.

 

The line of the Lineweaver-Burke plot has a formula directly rearranged from the Michaelis-Menten equation, so it is analogous to y = mx + c, meaning you can use the y-intercept and the gradient to find 1/Vmax and Km/Vmax respectively.

Question:
For this question, the Michaelis-Menten equation is provided:

 

 

Which of the following graphs demonstrates a competitive inhibitor?
Explanation:
In competitive inhibition (D), Vmax is not affected, so the y-intercept of the line will not change. Km will appear to increase, which causes an increase in the gradient. This inhibition is decreased by increasing [S].

In uncompetitive inhibition (A), the inhibition only occurs when the enzyme-substate complex is formed. Km does not change but Vmax decreases. This form of inhibition is not affected by increasing [S]. The gradient does not change due to some complicated enzyme kinetics involving [I].

In non-competitive inhibition (C), the inhibitor binds to an allosteric site. Km does not change but Vmax decreases. This will increase the gradient and will increase the y-intercept. Increasing [S] does nothing for this form of inhibition either.

Question:
After sitting your S1 paper you go home and binge on copious amounts of comfort food, including a tub of Ben and Jerry's Cookie dough and a Domino's pizza.

This gets you thinking about the hormone signalling involved in the regulation of digestion.

During the intestinal phase the hormone Cholecystokinin is released. Which description best matches it?
OptionA: It is released from S cells in the duodenum, it inhibits gastrin secretion through reducing the parietal cells sensitivity to gastrin. It also stimulates bicarbonate rich fluid from duct cells in the pancreas.
OptionB: It's released from I cells in the duodenum. Release is stimulated by a low pH in the duodenum. It competitively inhibits the binding of gastrin to the parietal cells. It also stimulates the secretion of bile by relaxation of the sphincter of oddi, and stimulates pancreatic secretions.
OptionC: It's released from I cells in the duodenum. Release is stimulated by the products of the digestion of fat and lipids in the duodenum. It competitively inhibits the binding of gastrin to the parietal cells. It also stimulates the secretion of bile by relaxation of the sphincter of oddi, and stimulates pancreatic secretions.
OptionD: It is released from D cells in the oxyntic (gastric) gland. It's release is stimulated in the intestinal phase by enterogastrones and it's the main mechanism by which gastric secretion is inhibited.
OptionE: It's released from I cells in the duodenum. Release is stimulated by low pH and the products of the digestion of fat and lipids in the duodenum. It inhibits gastrin secretion from G-cells. It also stimulates the secretion of bile by relaxation of the sphincter of oddi, and stimulates pancreatic secretions..
Explanation:
A- is a description of the hormone secretin. 

B- CCK is stimulated by the products of fat and protein in the duodenum

C- correct!

D- is a description of somatostatin 

E- incorrect
